{"title_page": "St. Elmo (secret society)", "text_new": "{{other uses|St. Elmo (disambiguation)|San Telmo (disambiguation)}}\n\n[[File:St Elmo's Society.png|thumb|100px|St. Elmo's Society logo]]\n\n'''St. Elmo Society''', or Elmo's, is a [[secret society]] (or, rather, open secret society) at [[Yale University]].{{citation needed|date=June 2011}} It was founded in 1889 as an independent entity for seniors within the nationally chartered fraternity, [[Delta Phi]] (\u0394\u03a6), Omicron Chapter (1889\u20131925).\n\nDelegations are selected from the entire junior class pool based on students' scholastic standing, his or her seriousness of purpose, maturity, individuality, and other achievements at the university as well as representation of the different backgrounds and interests in each class. There are eight men and eight women in each year's delegation.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n\n== History ==\n\n[[File:St Elmos semi-centennial dinner.png|thumb|St. Elmo's Semi-centennial Dinner]]\n[[File:St Elmos Second Tomb.jpg|thumb|St. Elmo's 2nd Tomb, now owned by Yale University and known as Rosenfeld Hall, at 109 Grove Street, photographed circa 1940]]\n[[File:Rosenfeld Hall.jpg|thumb|St. Elmo's 2nd Tomb, at 109 Grove Street as it looks today. It was purchased by Yale and is used as annex housing for Timothy Dwight College]]\n\nFounded in 1889 as an unincorporated association within Delta Phi, St. Elmo was the third senior society (after [[Berzelius (secret society)|Berzelius]], 1848; and [[Book and Snake]], 1863) at the [[Sheffield Scientific School]], Yale's sciences and engineering college from 1854 to 1956. These Sheffield Societies were once populated by members from the sophomore, junior, and senior classes, who maintained separate residential quarters within their societies' tombs. St. Elmo's is a member of the \u201cancient eight consortium\u201d which includes the seven other original societies at Yale: [[Skull and Bones]], [[Scroll and Key]], [[Wolf's Head (secret society)|Wolf's Head]], [[Book and Snake]], [[Elihu (secret society)|Elihu]], [[Berzelius (secret society)|Berzelius]], and [[Mace and Chain]].\n\nThe society's original club house, at 111 Grove Street, was built in 1895.<ref>http://www.library.yale.edu/mssa/YHO/ExtracurricularandSocialOrganizations.pdf</ref>\n\n[[File:St. Elmo 1895.jpg|thumb|St. Elmo's 1st Tomb, 1895, at 111 Grove Street]]\n\nIn June 1905, the group incorporated under Connecticut state law to form the St. Elmo Corporation, with the primary purpose of holding the title to 111 Grove Street and financial assets.\n\nIn 1912, the society built a new clubhouse next door at 109 Grove Street. Dubbed St. Elmo Hall, it was constructed from designs by [[Kenneth MacKenzie Murchison|Kenneth M. Murchison]] that echoed an Elizabethan manor house.\n\n[[File:St Elmo Society Lynwood.jpg|thumb|upright|St. Elmo's current Tomb, 1985, on Lynwood Place]]\nIn July 1925, the Omicron Chapter of Delta Phi, and, in turn, the society, severed its ties with the national fraternity and became an independent organization.\n\nThe creation of Yale's residential college system in 1933 led some Sheffield organizations to sell their buildings, but St. Elmo's (along with some others) pressed on, incorporating itself as the Rhinelander Trust Association.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://darkdownhere.com/?p=27 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2009-03-04 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708232225/http://darkdownhere.com/?p=27 |archive-date=2011-07-08 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn late 1956, the corporation lost its incorporation status due to clerical errors but reincorporated in 1964 as St. Elmo Incorporated.\n\nIn 1962, Yale, which had leased dormitory space in the Hall since 1945, bought the building from Elmo's. The university leased part of it to the society, with the understanding that the university would continue to do so; the hall is now known as Rosenfeld Hall.<ref>[http://www.facilities.yale.edu/Campus/Building1.asp?lstBldg=1715 ]{{dead link|date=March 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1965, a decade after the Sheffield school had been incorporated into Yale College, St. Elmo became a secret society in the traditional sense of [[Skull and Bones]] (1832), [[Scroll and Key]] (1841), and [[Wolf's Head (secret society)|Wolf's Head]] (1883), which had selected its members from the Academic Department (the liberal arts college).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conspiracyarchive.com/NWO/Tombs_and_Taps.htm |title=Tombs and Taps, An inside look at Yale's Fraternities, Sororities and Societies |publisher=Conspiracyarchive.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, the university refused to renew St. Elmo's lease  at 109 Grove Street, leaving the society with little time to move out and nowhere to go. The following year, St. Elmo moved to a building at 35 Lynwood Place.  St. Elmo Society, Inc. owns the property, like other \u201clanded\u201d or \u201cabove-ground\u201d societies that are run by private organizations.\n\nAs of 2008, the renamed Rosenfeld Hall is used for residential annex and classroom space, and most of the cryptic and historic areas are used for furniture storage or have been boarded up.<ref>{{cite web|last=Guo |first=Jerry |url=http://www.gadling.com/2008/05/29/connecticut-journal-inside-yales-secret-societies/ |title=Connecticut Journal: Inside Yale's secret societies |publisher=Gadling.com |date=2008-05-29 |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref>\n\n== Membership ==\n[[File:John Ashcroft by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|upright|[[John Ashcroft]] U.S. Attorney General and member of the 1964 delegation]]\n[[File:CalvinHill1979.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Calvin Hill]] American football running back and member of the 1969 delegation]]\nNotable members include:\n* Harry Valette Day (1895), president, manager, and first member of the board of directors of Custer Consolidated Mining Company, which in 1913 merged with the adjacent Tamarack & Chesapeake Mining Company, forming the Tamarack & Custer Consolidated Mining Company<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jEJAAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA38&lpg=PA38&dq=sheffield+scientific+school+st.+elmo&source=web&ots=IYifMwbRqc&sig=kzrme_YyD3M4itZGM5zTSwe-kPg&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=5&ct=result#PPA37,M1 |title=Quindecennial record of the class of 1895 Sheffield scientific school of ... \u2013 Yale University. Sheffield Scientific School. Class of 1895, William Usher Parsons \u2013 Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lib.uidaho.edu/special-collections/Manuscripts/dmginv/mg246.htm |title=Custer Consolidated Mining Company |publisher=Lib.uidaho.edu |date=2000-06-12 |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref>\n* [[Charles James Freeborn]] (1899), [[Croix de Guerre]] recipient for his service in World War I and captain in the [[United States Army]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a7gIX6_9DX4C&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=charles+freeborn+yale&source=bl&ots=lPgVOOsH6e&sig=YoYypF8Uf5a6afT2-AkP2oIEX7Y&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=6&ct=result |title=Yale in the World War, Part One \u2013 George He Nettleton \u2013 Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date=1920-11-21 |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref>\n* [[Guy Hutchinson]] (1906), president of Proctor & Schwartz Electric Company, which merged with Silex Company to form [[Proctor Silex]] in 1960; he was also an [[College Football All-America Team|All-American Football]] quarterback, 1905<ref>{{cite web|author=J. Griffin |url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~hutch/HUTCH/GUY/index.htm |title=Guy Hutchinson Page |publisher=Freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref>\n* Arthur Harding Bosworth (1908), founder and president of Bosworth, Chanute, Loughridge & Co, which eventually merged with [[Royal Bank of Canada|RBC Wealth Management]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinfinanc01leongoog |page=[https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinfinanc01leongoog/page/n99 77] |quote=st. elmo society yale. |title=Who's who in Finance and Banking \u2013 John William Leonard \u2013 |via=[[Internet Archive]] |year=1922 |publisher=Who's Who in Finance Incorporated |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref>\n* Robert Bensen Meyer (1914), [[Navy Cross (United States)|Navy Cross]] recipient for his service in World War I and lieutenant in the [[United States Navy]]<ref>http://mssa.library.yale.edu/obituary_record/1925_1952/1951-52.pdf</ref>\n* Fotzhugh Quarrier (1935), colonel in World War II in the N.Y. Air Defense Wing and assisted [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] in organizing the [[Women's Army Corps (United States Army)|WAACs]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9807E1DC133DF931A35750C0A9639C8B63 |title=Paid Notice - Deaths QUARRIER, FITZHUGH - Paid Death Notice - NYTimes.com |publisher=New York Times |date=2005-03-02 |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref>\n* [[Ivan Sergeyevich Obolensky|Ivan Obolensky]] (1947), [[Naval]] pilot, [[Pulitzer Prize]] publisher, vice president of Shields & Company, long-time financial analyst, son of Prince [[Serge Obolensky]], Russian Prince and vice chairman of the board of [[Hilton Hotels Corporation]], and grandson of [[John Jacob Astor IV]], great-grandson of [[John Jacob Astor]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://people.forbes.com/profile/ivan-obolensky/83151 |title=Theo Albrecht \u2013 Forbes |publisher=People.forbes.com |date=2012-04-18 |accessdate=2013-03-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090621172238/http://people.forbes.com/profile/ivan-obolensky/83151 |archive-date=2009-06-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=EDWIN McDOWELLPublished: October 09, 1989 |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=950DE3DF1631F93AA35753C1A96F948260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all |title=THE MEDIA BUSINESS; Financial Analyst of Publishing Companies Who's Done a Thing or Two |publisher=New York Times |date=1989-10-09 |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref>\n*[[Jim Fuchs|James E. Fuchs]] (1950), [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] medalist, 1948 and 1952, [[Pan-American Games]] medalist, and former [[world record]] holder, [[shot put]]. President, chairman, and executive director of the Silver Shield Foundation; chairman and co-chief executive of the Cosamar Group Inc.; former chairman and chief executive officer of The Grenfox Group Inc.; former senior advisor to the committee to Encourage Corporate Philanthropy; former CEO of Fuchs, Cuthrell & Co Inc.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.silvershieldfoundation.org/jimbio.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228154638/http://www.silvershieldfoundation.org/jimbio.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-02-28 |title=jimbio |publisher=Silvershieldfoundation.org |date= |access-date=2013-03-01 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Sellers |first=Patricia |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1988/09/26/71046/index.htm |title=THE OLYMPIANS OF BUSINESS \u2013 September 26, 1988 |publisher=Money.cnn.com |date=1988-09-26 |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref>\n*Alan K. McAdams (1952), professor at [[S.C. Johnson Graduate School of Management|Johnson Business School]] at Cornell and past senior staff member of the President's [[Council of Economic Advisers]]\n*Andrew H. Marks (1961), former president and CEO of Bollinger, Inc.\n* [[Robert Morse Crunden]] (1962), professor at the [[University of Texas]], director of American Studies Department, 1985\u20131990, member of the History Department as well<ref>{{cite web |url=http://alumni.yale.edu/classes/yc1962/obituaries/crunden.html |title=Yale '62 \u2013 Obituaries \u2013 Professor Robert Morse Crunden |publisher=Alumni.yale.edu |date= |access-date=2013-03-01 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060106185730/http://alumni.yale.edu/classes/yc1962/obituaries/crunden.html |archive-date=2006-01-06 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.utexas.edu/faculty/council/2000-2001/memorials/Crunden/crunden.html |title=Office of the General Faculty Home Page |publisher=Utexas.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref>\n* John Richard Sack (1963), author of ''The Franciscan Conspiracy,'' translated into 20 languages and a top-10 bestseller in Germany, Brazil, France, Italy and the Netherlands\n* [[John Ashcroft]] (1964), 79th [[United States Attorney General]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.yaledailynews.com/articles/view/15924 |title=Viewers of Le\u2019s records may be fired &#124; Yale Daily News &#124; Page 15924 |publisher=Yale Daily News |date=2009-10-07 |access-date=2013-03-01 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090318011938/http://www.yaledailynews.com/articles/view/15924 |archive-date=2009-03-18 |df= }}</ref>\n* [[Barrington Daniels Parker Jr.]] (1965), a [[federal judge]] on the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit]]<ref>[http://www.aliciapatterson.org/APF001974/Coombs/Coombs02/Coombs02.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071022012341/http://www.aliciapatterson.org/APF001974/Coombs/Coombs02/Coombs02.html |date=October 22, 2007 }}</ref>\n* [[Calvin Hill]] (1969), All-Pro [[NFL]] running back; father of [[NBA]] All-Star, [[Grant Hill (basketball player)|Grant Hill]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://research.yale.edu/afam/pagedocs/PROGRAM.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-04-29 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070317024613/http://research.yale.edu/afam/pagedocs/PROGRAM.pdf |archive-date=2007-03-17 |df= }}</ref>\n* Dick Caples (1971), executive director of [[Lar Lubovitch Dance Company]]\n* Gandolfo Vincent DiBlasi (1975), partner at [[Sullivan & Cromwell]], recognized as one of the top litigation attorneys in America\n* Arturo Cazares (1979), epidemiologist M.D., M.P.H., Program and Executive Research Coordinator at the [[National Institutes of Health]], recognized contractor to the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]]\n* James L. Shulman (1987), author and president of [[ARTstor]]\n*Matt McCarthy (2002), author of ''Odd Man Out'', which was ranked number 21 on the [[New York Times Best Seller list|New York Times Non-Fiction Best Seller List]] in March 2009<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/03/sports/baseball/03book.html?_r=1 | work=The New York Times | first1=Benjamin | last1=Hill | first2=Alan | last2=Schwarz | title=Errors Cast Doubt on a Baseball Memoir | date=2009-03-03}}</ref><ref>[http://www.yalealumnimagazine.com/yotw/index.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090521182357/http://www.yalealumnimagazine.com/yotw/index.html |date=May 21, 2009 }}</ref>\n*[[Allison Williams (actress)|Allison Williams]] (2010), actress, Jordan Peele's [[Get Out]], HBO's ''[[Girls (TV series)|Girls]]''\n*[[Ron DeSantis (politician) |Ron DeSantis|]] (2001), current governor of Florida\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Secret Societies at Yale University]]\n*[[Collegiate secret societies in North America]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050404050959/http://www.yalealumnimagazine.com/issues/2004_09/old_yale.html How the Secret Societies Got That Way]\n* [http://www.yalealumnimagazine.com/issues/01_03/groups.html Yale Alumni Magazine 2001]\n* [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1895/06/09/106063935.pdf NY Times Article, St. Elmo Hall 1]\n* [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1895/12/23/106076503.pdf NY Times Article, St. Elmo Hall 2]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1925/10/12/archives/st-elmo-quits-delta-phi-yale-club-is-hereafter-to-be-an-independent.html New York Times Article, St. Elmo Society]\n* [https://archive.org/stream/yalehercampuscla00welc/yalehercampuscla00welc_djvu.txt Sheffield Scientific School Recordings]\n* [http://www.library.yale.edu/mssa/YHO/ExtracurricularandSocialOrganizations.pdf Yale Organizations 1780\u20131960]\n* [http://mssa.library.yale.edu/obituary_record/1925_1952/1951-52.pdf Sheffield Scientific School Obituary 1951\u20131952]\n* [http://www.conspiracyarchive.com/NWO/Tombs_and_Taps.htm Tombs and Taps: An inside look at Yale's Fraternities, Sororities and Societies]\n* [http://www.facilities.yale.edu/Campus/Building1.asp?lstBldg=1715 Buildings & Grounds]\n* [http://www.gadling.com/2008/05/29/connecticut-journal-inside-yales-secret-societies/ Inside Yale's Secret Societies]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081014071837/http://yaledailynews.com/articles/view/4583 Secret societies: tombs and tradition]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110708232225/http://darkdownhere.com/?p=27 Light and Truth]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090228125404/http://saintanthonyhall.com/About/ St. Anthony]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:St. Elmo (Secret Society)}}\n[[Category:Secret societies at Yale]]\n[[Category:1889 establishments in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Student organizations established in 1889]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|St. Elmo (disambiguation)|San Telmo (disambiguation)}}\n\n[[File:St Elmo's Society.png|thumb|100px|St. Elmo's Society logo]]\n\n'''St. Elmo Society''', or Elmo's, is a [[secret society]] (or, rather, open secret society) at [[Yale University]].{{citation needed|date=June 2011}} It was founded in 1889 as an independent entity for seniors within the nationally chartered fraternity, [[Delta Phi]] (\u0394\u03a6), Omicron Chapter (1889\u20131925).\n\nDelegations are selected from the entire junior class pool based on students' scholastic standing, his or her seriousness of purpose, maturity, individuality, and other achievements at the university as well as representation of the different backgrounds and interests in each class. There are eight men and eight women in each year's delegation.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n\n== History ==\n\n[[File:St Elmos semi-centennial dinner.png|thumb|St. Elmo's Semi-centennial Dinner]]\n[[File:St Elmos Second Tomb.jpg|thumb|St. Elmo's 2nd Tomb, now owned by Yale University and known as Rosenfeld Hall, at 109 Grove Street, photographed circa 1940]]\n[[File:Rosenfeld Hall.jpg|thumb|St. Elmo's 2nd Tomb, at 109 Grove Street as it looks today. It was purchased by Yale and is used as annex housing for Timothy Dwight College]]\n\nFounded in 1889 as an unincorporated association within Delta Phi, St. Elmo was the third senior society (after [[Berzelius (secret society)|Berzelius]], 1848; and [[Book and Snake]], 1863) at the [[Sheffield Scientific School]], Yale's sciences and engineering college from 1854 to 1956. These Sheffield Societies were once populated by members from the sophomore, junior, and senior classes, who maintained separate residential quarters within their societies' tombs. St. Elmo's is a member of the \u201cancient eight consortium\u201d which includes the seven other original societies at Yale: [[Skull and Bones]], [[Scroll and Key]], [[Wolf's Head (secret society)|Wolf's Head]], [[Book and Snake]], [[Elihu (secret society)|Elihu]], [[Berzelius (secret society)|Berzelius]], and [[Mace and Chain]].\n\nThe society's original club house, at 111 Grove Street, was built in 1895.<ref>http://www.library.yale.edu/mssa/YHO/ExtracurricularandSocialOrganizations.pdf</ref>\n\n[[File:St. Elmo 1895.jpg|thumb|St. Elmo's 1st Tomb, 1895, at 111 Grove Street]]\n\nIn June 1905, the group incorporated under Connecticut state law to form the St. Elmo Corporation, with the primary purpose of holding the title to 111 Grove Street and financial assets.\n\nIn 1912, the society built a new clubhouse next door at 109 Grove Street. Dubbed St. Elmo Hall, it was constructed from designs by [[Kenneth MacKenzie Murchison|Kenneth M. Murchison]] that echoed an Elizabethan manor house.\n\n[[File:St Elmo Society Lynwood.jpg|thumb|upright|St. Elmo's current Tomb, 1985, on Lynwood Place]]\nIn July 1925, the Omicron Chapter of Delta Phi, and, in turn, the society, severed its ties with the national fraternity and became an independent organization.\n\nThe creation of Yale's residential college system in 1933 led some Sheffield organizations to sell their buildings, but St. Elmo's (along with some others) pressed on, incorporating itself as the Rhinelander Trust Association.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://darkdownhere.com/?p=27 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2009-03-04 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708232225/http://darkdownhere.com/?p=27 |archive-date=2011-07-08 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn late 1956, the corporation lost its incorporation status due to clerical errors but reincorporated in 1964 as St. Elmo Incorporated.\n\nIn 1962, Yale, which had leased dormitory space in the Hall since 1945, bought the building from Elmo's. The university leased part of it to the society, with the understanding that the university would continue to do so; the hall is now known as Rosenfeld Hall.<ref>[http://www.facilities.yale.edu/Campus/Building1.asp?lstBldg=1715 ]{{dead link|date=March 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1965, a decade after the Sheffield school had been incorporated into Yale College, St. Elmo became a secret society in the traditional sense of [[Skull and Bones]] (1832), [[Scroll and Key]] (1841), and [[Wolf's Head (secret society)|Wolf's Head]] (1883), which had selected its members from the Academic Department (the liberal arts college).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conspiracyarchive.com/NWO/Tombs_and_Taps.htm |title=Tombs and Taps, An inside look at Yale's Fraternities, Sororities and Societies |publisher=Conspiracyarchive.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, the university refused to renew St. Elmo's lease  at 109 Grove Street, leaving the society with little time to move out and nowhere to go. The following year, St. Elmo moved to a building at 35 Lynwood Place.  St. Elmo Society, Inc. owns the property, like other \u201clanded\u201d or \u201cabove-ground\u201d societies that are run by private organizations.\n\nAs of 2008, the renamed Rosenfeld Hall is used for residential annex and classroom space, and most of the cryptic and historic areas are used for furniture storage or have been boarded up.<ref>{{cite web|last=Guo |first=Jerry |url=http://www.gadling.com/2008/05/29/connecticut-journal-inside-yales-secret-societies/ |title=Connecticut Journal: Inside Yale's secret societies |publisher=Gadling.com |date=2008-05-29 |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref>\n\n== Membership ==\n[[File:John Ashcroft by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|upright|[[John Ashcroft]] U.S. Attorney General and member of the 1964 delegation]]\n[[File:CalvinHill1979.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Calvin Hill]] American football running back and member of the 1969 delegation]]\nNotable members include:\n* Harry Valette Day (1895), president, manager, and first member of the board of directors of Custer Consolidated Mining Company, which in 1913 merged with the adjacent Tamarack & Chesapeake Mining Company, forming the Tamarack & Custer Consolidated Mining Company<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jEJAAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA38&lpg=PA38&dq=sheffield+scientific+school+st.+elmo&source=web&ots=IYifMwbRqc&sig=kzrme_YyD3M4itZGM5zTSwe-kPg&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=5&ct=result#PPA37,M1 |title=Quindecennial record of the class of 1895 Sheffield scientific school of ... \u2013 Yale University. Sheffield Scientific School. Class of 1895, William Usher Parsons \u2013 Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lib.uidaho.edu/special-collections/Manuscripts/dmginv/mg246.htm |title=Custer Consolidated Mining Company |publisher=Lib.uidaho.edu |date=2000-06-12 |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref>\n* [[Charles James Freeborn]] (1899), [[Croix de Guerre]] recipient for his service in World War I and captain in the [[United States Army]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a7gIX6_9DX4C&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=charles+freeborn+yale&source=bl&ots=lPgVOOsH6e&sig=YoYypF8Uf5a6afT2-AkP2oIEX7Y&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=6&ct=result |title=Yale in the World War, Part One \u2013 George He Nettleton \u2013 Google Books |publisher=Books.google.com |date=1920-11-21 |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref>\n* [[Guy Hutchinson]] (1906), president of Proctor & Schwartz Electric Company, which merged with Silex Company to form [[Proctor Silex]] in 1960; he was also an [[College Football All-America Team|All-American Football]] quarterback, 1905<ref>{{cite web|author=J. Griffin |url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~hutch/HUTCH/GUY/index.htm |title=Guy Hutchinson Page |publisher=Freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref>\n* Arthur Harding Bosworth (1908), founder and president of Bosworth, Chanute, Loughridge & Co, which eventually merged with [[Royal Bank of Canada|RBC Wealth Management]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinfinanc01leongoog |page=[https://archive.org/details/whoswhoinfinanc01leongoog/page/n99 77] |quote=st. elmo society yale. |title=Who's who in Finance and Banking \u2013 John William Leonard \u2013 |via=[[Internet Archive]] |year=1922 |publisher=Who's Who in Finance Incorporated |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref>\n* Robert Bensen Meyer (1914), [[Navy Cross (United States)|Navy Cross]] recipient for his service in World War I and lieutenant in the [[United States Navy]]<ref>http://mssa.library.yale.edu/obituary_record/1925_1952/1951-52.pdf</ref>\n* Fotzhugh Quarrier (1935), colonel in World War II in the N.Y. Air Defense Wing and assisted [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] in organizing the [[Women's Army Corps (United States Army)|WAACs]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9807E1DC133DF931A35750C0A9639C8B63 |title=Paid Notice - Deaths QUARRIER, FITZHUGH - Paid Death Notice - NYTimes.com |publisher=New York Times |date=2005-03-02 |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref>\n* [[Ivan Sergeyevich Obolensky|Ivan Obolensky]] (1947), [[Naval]] pilot, [[Pulitzer Prize]] publisher, vice president of Shields & Company, long-time financial analyst, son of Prince [[Serge Obolensky]], Russian Prince and vice chairman of the board of [[Hilton Hotels Corporation]], and grandson of [[John Jacob Astor IV]], great-grandson of [[John Jacob Astor]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://people.forbes.com/profile/ivan-obolensky/83151 |title=Theo Albrecht \u2013 Forbes |publisher=People.forbes.com |date=2012-04-18 |accessdate=2013-03-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090621172238/http://people.forbes.com/profile/ivan-obolensky/83151 |archive-date=2009-06-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=EDWIN McDOWELLPublished: October 09, 1989 |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=950DE3DF1631F93AA35753C1A96F948260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all |title=THE MEDIA BUSINESS; Financial Analyst of Publishing Companies Who's Done a Thing or Two |publisher=New York Times |date=1989-10-09 |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref>\n*[[Jim Fuchs|James E. Fuchs]] (1950), [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] medalist, 1948 and 1952, [[Pan-American Games]] medalist, and former [[world record]] holder, [[shot put]]. President, chairman, and executive director of the Silver Shield Foundation; chairman and co-chief executive of the Cosamar Group Inc.; former chairman and chief executive officer of The Grenfox Group Inc.; former senior advisor to the committee to Encourage Corporate Philanthropy; former CEO of Fuchs, Cuthrell & Co Inc.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.silvershieldfoundation.org/jimbio.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228154638/http://www.silvershieldfoundation.org/jimbio.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-02-28 |title=jimbio |publisher=Silvershieldfoundation.org |date= |access-date=2013-03-01 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Sellers |first=Patricia |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1988/09/26/71046/index.htm |title=THE OLYMPIANS OF BUSINESS \u2013 September 26, 1988 |publisher=Money.cnn.com |date=1988-09-26 |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref>\n*Alan K. McAdams (1952), professor at [[S.C. Johnson Graduate School of Management|Johnson Business School]] at Cornell and past senior staff member of the President's [[Council of Economic Advisers]]\n*Andrew H. Marks (1961), former president and CEO of Bollinger, Inc.\n* [[Robert Morse Crunden]] (1962), professor at the [[University of Texas]], director of American Studies Department, 1985\u20131990, member of the History Department as well<ref>{{cite web |url=http://alumni.yale.edu/classes/yc1962/obituaries/crunden.html |title=Yale '62 \u2013 Obituaries \u2013 Professor Robert Morse Crunden |publisher=Alumni.yale.edu |date= |access-date=2013-03-01 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060106185730/http://alumni.yale.edu/classes/yc1962/obituaries/crunden.html |archive-date=2006-01-06 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.utexas.edu/faculty/council/2000-2001/memorials/Crunden/crunden.html |title=Office of the General Faculty Home Page |publisher=Utexas.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-03-01}}</ref>\n* John Richard Sack (1963), author of ''The Franciscan Conspiracy,'' translated into 20 languages and a top-10 bestseller in Germany, Brazil, France, Italy and the Netherlands\n* [[John Ashcroft]] (1964), 79th [[United States Attorney General]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.yaledailynews.com/articles/view/15924 |title=Viewers of Le\u2019s records may be fired &#124; Yale Daily News &#124; Page 15924 |publisher=Yale Daily News |date=2009-10-07 |access-date=2013-03-01 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090318011938/http://www.yaledailynews.com/articles/view/15924 |archive-date=2009-03-18 |df= }}</ref>\n* [[Barrington Daniels Parker Jr.]] (1965), a [[federal judge]] on the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit]]<ref>[http://www.aliciapatterson.org/APF001974/Coombs/Coombs02/Coombs02.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071022012341/http://www.aliciapatterson.org/APF001974/Coombs/Coombs02/Coombs02.html |date=October 22, 2007 }}</ref>\n* [[Calvin Hill]] (1969), All-Pro [[NFL]] running back; father of [[NBA]] All-Star, [[Grant Hill (basketball player)|Grant Hill]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://research.yale.edu/afam/pagedocs/PROGRAM.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-04-29 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070317024613/http://research.yale.edu/afam/pagedocs/PROGRAM.pdf |archive-date=2007-03-17 |df= }}</ref>\n* Dick Caples (1971), executive director of [[Lar Lubovitch Dance Company]]\n* Gandolfo Vincent DiBlasi (1975), partner at [[Sullivan & Cromwell]], recognized as one of the top litigation attorneys in America\n* Arturo Cazares (1979), epidemiologist M.D., M.P.H., Program and Executive Research Coordinator at the [[National Institutes of Health]], recognized contractor to the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]]\n* James L. Shulman (1987), author and president of [[ARTstor]]\n*Matt McCarthy (2002), author of ''Odd Man Out'', which was ranked number 21 on the [[New York Times Best Seller list|New York Times Non-Fiction Best Seller List]] in March 2009<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/03/sports/baseball/03book.html?_r=1 | work=The New York Times | first1=Benjamin | last1=Hill | first2=Alan | last2=Schwarz | title=Errors Cast Doubt on a Baseball Memoir | date=2009-03-03}}</ref><ref>[http://www.yalealumnimagazine.com/yotw/index.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090521182357/http://www.yalealumnimagazine.com/yotw/index.html |date=May 21, 2009 }}</ref>\n*[[Allison Williams (actress)|Allison Williams]] (2010), actress, Jordan Peele's [[Get Out]], HBO's ''[[Girls (TV series)|Girls]]''\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Secret Societies at Yale University]]\n*[[Collegiate secret societies in North America]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== Sources ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050404050959/http://www.yalealumnimagazine.com/issues/2004_09/old_yale.html How the Secret Societies Got That Way]\n* [http://www.yalealumni