inks==\n* [http://www.stbedesbradford.net/ St Bede's Grammar School]\n* [http://sbsj.co.uk/ St Bede's and St Joseph's Catholic College]\n\n{{Schools in the City of Bradford}}\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Leeds}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Bede's Grammar School}}\n[[Category:1900 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Defunct Catholic schools in the Diocese of Leeds]]\n[[Category:Defunct grammar schools in England]]\n[[Category:Defunct schools in the City of Bradford]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1900]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions disestablished in 2014]]\n[[Category:Schools in Bradford]]\n[[Category:2014 disestablishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "Danstarr69", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St_Bede%27s_Grammar_School"}
{"title_page": "Tornadoes of 2020", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Notable tornadoes and tornado outbreaks in 2020}}\n{{Infobox tornado year\n|name          = Tornadoes of 2020\n|image         = 2020 United States tornado count.png\n|caption       = A chart of the 2020 United States tornado count estimated from the number of preliminary reports\n|timespan      = January 3 - ongoing\n|max_EF        = EF4\n|max_location  = [[Cookeville, Tennessee]]\n|max_date      = March 3\n|max_location2  = [[Jayess, Mississippi]]\n|max_date2      = April 12\n|max_location3  = [[Bassfield, Mississippi]]\n|max_date3      = April 12\n|tornadoes_usa = 368\n|total_damages_usa = >$4.4&nbsp;billion total economic losses\n|total_fatalities_world = 72\n|total_fatalities_usa = 72\n|year = 2020\n}}\n\nThis page documents notable [[tornado]]es and [[tornado outbreak]]s worldwide in '''2020'''. Strong and destructive tornadoes form most frequently in the [[United States]], [[Argentina]], [[Brazil]], [[Bangladesh]], and [[East India|Eastern India]], but can occur almost anywhere under the right conditions. Tornadoes also develop occasionally in southern [[Canada]] during the [[Northern Hemisphere]]'s summer and somewhat regularly at other times of the year across [[Europe]], [[Asia]], [[Argentina]], [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]]. Tornadic events are often accompanied by other forms of [[severe weather]], including strong [[thunderstorm]]s, strong [[winds]], and [[hail]].\n\nThere have been 456 preliminary filtered reports of tornadoes in the United States in 2020,<ref>{{cite web |title=Annual Severe Weather Report Summary 2020 |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/online/monthly/2020_annual_summary.html |publisher=Storm Prediction Center |accessdate=January 8, 2020}}</ref> of which at least 368 have been confirmed. Worldwide, 72 tornado-related deaths have been confirmed, all in the United States.\n\n==Events==\n{{Tornadoes of 2020/Deadly}}\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020}}\n\n===United States yearly total===\n<!-- This section is transcluded to other articles; modify with caution. -->\n<onlyinclude>\n{{Tornado Chart\n|Total = 368\n|FU = 7\n|F0 = 110\n|F1 = 174\n|F2 = 54\n|F3 = 14\n|F4 = 3\n|F5 = 0\n| Enhanced=yes\n}}\n</onlyinclude>\n\n==January==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#January}}\nThere were 90 tornadoes reported in the United States in January, of which 87 were confirmed. Overall, January was an active month, with over twice the national average of 35 tornadoes.\n\n===January 3 (South Africa)===\nOn January 3, severe thunderstorms developed over the [[Mpumalanga]] province of [[South Africa]]. One thunderstorm developed into a supercell which produced an EF3 tornado that caused significant damage to a farm, destroyed the houses of seven families, and destroyed about {{convert|200|hectare|acre|sigfig=1}} of pine forest.<ref>{{cite web |title=Media Release: Panbult tornado (Mpumalanga) on the 3rd of January 2020. |url=https://twitter.com/SAWeatherServic/status/1214087467692941312?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1214087467692941312&ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.news24.com%2FSouthAfrica%2FNews%2Fwatch-tornado-lasting-about-40-minutes-destroyed-farm-and-7-houses-in-mpumalanga-saws-confirms-20200106 |website=Twitter |publisher=South African Weather Service |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===January 10\u201311===\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of January 10\u201311, 2020}}\n{{stack begin}}{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 25|EF1= 41|EF2= 13|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU=0}}{{stack end}}\n[[File:Carollton EF2 damage1.jpg|thumb||float|left|High-end EF2 damage to a house near Carrollton, Alabama.]]\nOn January 10, the Storm Prediction Center issues a moderate risk of severe weather for much of the Southern United States, including a 15% hatched risk of tornadoes. A squall line of severe thunderstorms with numerous embedded circulations and semi-discrete supercell structures moved from [[Texas]] and [[Oklahoma]] to the [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]], producing numerous tornadoes. A high-end EF2 tornado near [[Carrollton, Alabama]] destroyed multiple homes and mobile homes, and resulted in three fatalities.<ref>{{cite web |title=Three people killed in Pickens Co. tornado |url=https://www.wbrc.com/2020/01/11/three-people-killed-pickens-co-tornado/ |publisher=WBRC |accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> Three people were fatally injured when a long-tracked EF2 tornado destroyed two mobile homes south of [[Haughton, Louisiana]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Enfinger |first1=Emily |title=87-year-old dies from injuries from Haughton tornado |url=https://eu.shreveporttimes.com/story/news/local/2020/01/15/third-death-confimred-haughton-tornado/4480014002/ |publisher=Shreveport Times |accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref> and an EF1 tornado killed one person near [[Nacogdoches, Texas]] when a large tree fell onto a mobile home.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brackett |first1=Ron |last2=Wesner Childs |first2=Jan |title=Tornadoes, Severe Storms Kill 8; More Than 300,000 Lose Power |url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-01-11-severe-storms-tornadoes-impact-texas-louisiana-tennessee-arkansas-mississippi |website=weather.com |publisher=The Weather Channel |accessdate=January 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Houston, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey for January 10 Burleson County Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSHGX&e=202001112109|date=January 11, 2020|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> An EF2 tornado struck [[Rome, Mississippi]], causing significant damage and destroying the local post office. An EF2 tornado also struck [[Union Grove, Alabama]], significantly damaging a school building in the community. Another school also sustained major damage near [[Kershaw, South Carolina]], as a result of another EF2 tornado. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 79 tornadoes, and resulted in 7 fatalities. Total damage from the event reached $1.1&nbsp;billion according to the [[National Centers for Environmental Information]].<ref name=\"NCEI_billion\">{{cite web|publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information|year=2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Billion-Dollar Weather and Climate Disasters: Events|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/billions/events}}</ref>\n\n==February==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#February}}\nThere were 51 tornadoes reported in the United States in February, of which 42 were confirmed. February was also an active month, besting the national average of 29 tornadoes.\n\n===February 5\u20137===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 9|EF1= 21|EF2= 6|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU=1}}\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of February 5\u20137, 2020}}\n[[File:KannapolisNCEF2-2020.jpg|thumb||float|left|EF2 damage to a house near Kannapolis, North Carolina.]]\nBeginning on February 5, a moderate tornado outbreak affected the Deep South and Eastern United States. On the first day of the outbreak, an EF2 tornado caused significant tree and outbuilding damage near [[Pickens, Mississippi]], and injured four people. A long-tracked EF2 tornado touched down near [[Bay Springs, Mississippi]] and passed though the town of [[Enterprise, Clarke County, Mississippi|Enterprise]], downing numerous trees and power poles and toppling a metal fire tower. This tornado tore large sections of roofing off of multiple homes in rural areas as well. On February 6, one person was killed in [[Marengo County, Alabama]] when an EF1 tornado destroyed a mobile home near [[Demopolis, Alabama|Demopolis]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Birmingham, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey for 02/06/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=202002070055|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Jackson, Mississippi|title=NWS Damage Survey for 02/05/2020 - 02/06/2020 Tornado Event - Update #1|url=http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSJAN&e=202002070252|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref> An EF2 tornado also touched down near [[Kannapolis, North Carolina]], to the north of [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]]. No injuries were reported, though multiple homes were damaged, including one that lost its roof and some exterior walls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/02/06/tornado-touches-down-kannapolis/|title=Tornado touches down in Kannapolis|website=WBTV|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wcnc.com/article/weather/confirmed-tornado-damages-homes-in-kannapolis/275-3a51f749-53cd-490f-bf2c-3fd08c8c793c|title=Confirmed tornado damages homes in the Kannapolis area|website=WCNC|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Tornado rips roof off home in Kannapolis, North Carolina|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gE8N-dBHI7k|language=en|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> Another EF2 downed metal truss transmission towers near [[Kings Mountain, North Carolina|Kings Mountain]], and an EF1 tornado caused damage in the southern suburbs of Charlotte.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://salisburypost.com/2020/02/08/three-rescued-from-flood-waters-weather-service-confirms-tornado-in-rowan-county/|title=As flooding, damage lingers, 3 rescued from Third Creek, weather service confirms tornadoes in Rowan|last=Walker|first=Shavonne|work=[[Salisbury Post]]|date=2020-02-08|accessdate=2020-02-08}}</ref><ref name=WBTV>{{cite news|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/02/07/nws-confirms-ef-tornado-near-pineville/|title=NWS confirms EF-1 tornado near Pineville|last=Myers|first=Jason|work=[[WBTV]]|date=2020-02-07|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wcnc.com/article/weather/tornado-stanly-albemarle-damage-storm/275-227d0b28-9341-4b91-a7a0-057602e4a803|title=EF-1 tornado confirmed near Albemarle|work=[[WCNC-TV]]|date=2020-02-07|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> A high-end EF1 tornado moved directly through [[Spartanburg, South Carolina]] as well, causing considerable damage to homes and businesses.<ref name=WBTV/> On February 7, five tornadoes touched down in Maryland, including an EF1 that struck [[Westminster, Maryland|Westminster]] and [[Manchester, Maryland|Manchester]], causing moderate damage. An EF0 tornado also caused minor damage in [[Leesburg, Virginia]]. Along with the tornadic storms, a widespread amount of flooding has also occurred throughout the southern states. Total economic losses from the event exceeded $925&nbsp;million. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 37 tornadoes, and resulted in one fatality.<ref>{{cite report|publisher=Aon|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Global Catastrophe Recap: February 2020|url=http://thoughtleadership.aonbenfield.com/Documents/20200309_analytics-if-february-global-recap.pdf|page=4|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n==March==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#March}}\nThere were 106 tornadoes reported in the United States in March, of which 77 were confirmed. Although March was slightly below average in number of tornadoes, the series of severe weather outbreaks and tornadoes throughout March inflicted widespread damage across the country. Combined economic losses reached approximately $2.4&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|author=Matt Sheehan|publisher=Reinsurance News|date=April 14, 2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Separate billion-dollar events mark active month for US tornadoes: Aon|url=https://www.reinsurancene.ws/separate-billion-dollar-events-mark-active-month-for-us-tornadoes-aon/}}</ref>\n\n===March 2\u20133===\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of March 2\u20133, 2020}}\n[[File:CookevilleTNEF4rubbleanddamage.jpg|thumb||float|left|EF4 damage in a residential area of Cookeville, Tennessee.]]\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 5|EF1= 3|EF2= 4|EF3= 1|EF4= 1|EF5= 0|EFU= 1}}\nA small but devastating tornado outbreak affected parts of the Southern United States on the evening of March 2 into the early morning hours of March 3, with the most severe damage and all fatalities occurring in Tennessee. [[Nashville, Tennessee]] was directly struck by a high-end EF3 tornado just after 12:30&nbsp;a.m. CDT on March 3. Major structural damage and six fatalities occurred as the tornado passed just north of downtown Nashville and through [[Mount Juliet, Tennessee|Mount Juliet]] to the east. Additional tornadoes were reported in [[Missouri]], [[Alabama]], [[Tennessee]], and [[Kentucky]]. An EF2 tornado killed one person and caused significant damage to homes, mobile homes, and outbuildings near [[Camden, Tennessee]] as well. The majority of the deaths occurred in Putnam County, where a violent EF4 tornado touched down near [[Baxter, Tennessee|Baxter]] shortly before 2:00&nbsp;a.m. and moved into western [[Cookeville, Tennessee|Cookeville]]. Many homes and other buildings were completely leveled or swept away in residential areas of Cookeville, and 19 people were killed in town.<ref name=\"OHX\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Nashville, Tennessee|title=March 2-3, 2020 Tornadoes and Severe Weather|url=https://www.weather.gov/ohx/20200303|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=March 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=21 killed, 221 hospitalized after tornadoes rip through Nashville, surrounding areas|url=https://www.abcactionnews.com/news/national/six-killed-at-least-20-hurt-after-tornadoes-rip-through-nashville-surrounding-areas|publisher=ABC Action News|date=March 3, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> In addition, two EF2 tornadoes also downed numerous trees in forested areas near [[Alvaton, Kentucky]] and [[Clarkrange, Tennessee]] as well. A lone, long-tracked [[supercell]] thunderstorm was responsible for all nine of the tornadoes in Tennessee as it moved from near [[Dyersburg, Tennessee|Dyersburg]] in West Tennessee to near [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]] in East Tennessee. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 15 tornadoes, and resulted in 26 fatalities.<ref name=\"OHX\"/>\n\n===March 18\u201319===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 5|EF1= 11|EF2= 5|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nDuring the evenings of March 18 and 19, rounds of severe storms impacted a large area from [[West Texas]] to [[Ohio]], spawning several tornadoes. On March 18, an intense [[supercell thunderstorm]] spawned numerous weak tornadoes as it tracked through [[Jack County, Texas|Jack]], [[Stephens County, Texas|Stephens]], [[Wise County, Texas|Wise]], and [[Young County, Texas|Young counties]] in [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Fort Worth, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/18/2020 Tornado Event - Update #2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSFWD&e=202003201858|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Overnight, an EF2 tornado damaged a farm southwest of [[Merkel, Texas]], and another EF2 debarked trees and damaged a home nearby (these two tracks may have been the same tornado).<ref name=\"SJT0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in San Angelo, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event - Update #1|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSSJT&e=202003201627|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The thunderstorm responsible for those tornadoes went on to produce an EF1 and an EF2 tornado that damaged a large building and over 100 cars northeast of [[Abilene, Texas|Abilene]].<ref name=\"SJT0319\"/>\n\nOn March 19, a large portion of the southern [[Great Plains]] was in line for severe storms.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Darrow|title=Mar 19, 2020 0100 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2020/day1otlk_20200319_0100.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> During the afternoon, a squall line with several embedded supercells formed from [[Oklahoma]] to [[Indiana]], producing tornadoes in [[Oklahoma]], [[Illinois]], and [[Arkansas]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tulsa, Oklahoma|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTSA&e=202003210250|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PAH0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003202132|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"LZK0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornadoes Update #2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLZK&e=202003212158|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 21, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> A large EF2 tornado touched down near [[Everton, Arkansas]], removing the top floor from one house and tossing an exercise bike into the side window of a [[Chevrolet Suburban|Chevy suburban]].<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/> Three EF1 tornadoes touched down in Arkansas, one of which caused damage between [[Gassville, Arkansas|Gassville]] and [[Mountain Home, Arkansas|Mountain Home]], destroying one home and tearing the roof off of another.<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/> One person was injured in Illinois,<ref name=\"PAH0319\"/> and another in Arkansas.<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/>\n\n===March 28\u201329===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 3|EF1= 11|EF2= 2|EF3= 1|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 3}}\nAn EF3 tornado struck the city of [[Jonesboro, Arkansas]], while being streamed live on local news stations, producing major damage and causing 22 injuries.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tornado flattens buildings in Jonesboro, Arkansas, as severe weather moves across the Midwest, Lower Mississippi River Valley |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/28/weather/tornadoes-severe-storms-forecast-saturday/index.html |website=CNN |publisher=CNN |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Damage Reported in Northeastern Arkansas as Tornado Strikes Jonesboro |url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-03-28-severe-weather-tornado-impacts-plains-south-midwest |website=Weather.com |publisher=The Weather Channel |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"20200328 reports\">{{cite web |title=Today's Storm Reports (20200328 1200 UTC - 20200329 1159 UTC) (Print Version) |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200328_rpts.html|website=NOAA |publisher=NOAA |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MEG0328\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Memphis, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMEG&e=202003292239|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Damage from Jonesboro shows numerous cars lofted and mangled in a shopping mall parking lot, with missile debris embedded into the ground. A train was also derailed, while the municipal airport sustained major damage, with hangars demolished and at least one plane flipped.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zoellner |first1=Danielle |title=Tornado rips through Arkansas town, injuring six people |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/arkansas-tornado-jonesboro-weather-injured-a9432511.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\nThe same storm that produced this tornado also produced two EF1 tornadoes, one before and one after it moved over Jonesboro.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLZK&e=202003292104|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MEG0328\"/>\nInto the evening, numerous weak tornadoes touched down in [[Iowa]] and [[Illinois]], and another in southwest [[Wisconsin]].<ref name=\"20200328 reports\"/>\nAn EF2 tornado was on the ground for 17 miles southwest of [[Henderson, Kentucky]], destroying a barn and damaging dozens of homes and outbuildings.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Henderson County KY Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003300139|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\nAnother EF2 touched down concurrently in [[Newburgh, Indiana]], removing portions of roofs or walls on five homes and damaging several others. Two people were injured.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Newburgh Indiana Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003300138|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEarly in the morning of March 29, the same storm system produced an EF0 tornado that mainly damaged trees near [[Sparta, Tennessee]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Nashville, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/29/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSOHX&e=202003311858|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March 30\u201331 ===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 9|EF1= 3|EF2= 1|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 2}}\nOn the evening of March 30, isolated supercells developed across Texas and Oklahoma, producing two weak tornadoes. One of these was given an EFU rating, and the other, which was a [[landspout]] or non-mesocylonic tornado, was given an EF0 rating.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Amarillo, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/30/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSAMA&e=202003312336|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> \nOn March 31, multiple supercells and embedded mesocyclones formed along and just ahead of a convective line, with 15 preliminary tornado reports in the [[southeastern United States]].<ref name=\"SPC 3/31\">{{cite web |title=SPC Storm reports for03/31/20 |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200331_rpts.html |publisher=Storm Prediction |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\nAn EF2 tornado caused significant damage in [[Eufaula, Alabama]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fuentes |first1=Carmen |title=Eufaula tornado runs through neighborhood |url=https://www.wtvy.com/content/news/Eufaula-tornado-runs-through-neighborhood-569268011.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |agency=WTVY |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BMX0331\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Birmingham, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/31/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=202004020401|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> and several weaker ones were reported in southeast [[Mississippi]], southern [[Alabama]], and northern [[Florida]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee, Florida|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/31/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTAE&e=202004032145|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 3, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BMX0331\"/> Another tornado was caught on video around 2:30&nbsp;p.m. PDT in [[Washington (state)|Washington state]].<ref name=\"SPC 3/31\"/>\n\n==April==\n{{see also|List of United States tornadoes in April 2020}}\nThere have been 162 tornadoes confirmed in the United States in April.\n\n===April 7\u20139===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 20|EF1= 10|EF2= 1|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nSeveral tornadoes touched down across [[Ohio]] and [[Pennsylvania]] late on April 7 and into the early morning of April 8. Later in the afternoon on April 8, an EF0 tornado briefly touched down west-southwest of [[Jonesboro, Arkansas]] near the town of [[Cash, Arkansas|Cash]], followed by an EF2 tornado in the vicinity of [[Weiner, Arkansas|Weiner]] and [[Harrisburg, Arkansas]] in [[Poinsett County, Arkansas|Poinsett County]].<ref>https://twitter.com/nwsmemphis/status/1248334194377232384?s=21</ref><ref>https://media.arkansasonline.com/img/photos/2020/04/09/storm1_t800.jpg?90232451fbcadccc64a17de7521d859a8f88077d</ref> In Harrisburg, one home was completely leveled by the tornado, and several homes nearby were also badly damaged as well.<ref>https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2020/apr/09/forecasters-tornado-touched-down-overnight-northwe/#.Xo9c00N8lmQ.twitter</ref> Numerous homes were heavily damaged and two people were injured in Harrisburg.<ref>https://twitter.com/kwoodallTV/status/1248076374084124673?s=19</ref> More tornadoes, mainly weak and short-lived, occurred across [[Indiana]], [[Kentucky]], and Ohio.\n\n=== April 12\u201313 ===\n{{Tornado chart small|FU = 0|F0 = 29|F1 = 67|F2 = 21|F3 = 12|F4 = 2|F5 = 0|Enhanced=yes}}\n{{main|2020 Easter tornado outbreak}}\nFrom the late morning of April 12 through the early morning of April 13, a major tornado outbreak unfolded across the [[Southeastern United States]], with more than 100 tornadoes touching down in 24 hours over two days. Over a 48 hour period from nighttime on April 11 to the evening of April 13, 131 tornadoes touched down from Texas to Marylans. his event was well forecasted, with the [[Storm Prediction Center]] issuing severe weather outlooks as early as five days before the outbreak. At 10:40 a.m. CDT on April 12, a [[Particularly Dangerous Situation]] [[Tornado Watch]] was issued by the Storm Prediction Center across northeast [[Louisiana]], southeast [[Arkansas]], and central and northern [[Mississippi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0106.html|title=PDS Watch 106|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At 11:44 a.m. CDT, a [[Tornado emergency|tornado emergency]] was issued for [[Monroe, Louisiana]] as an [[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF3 tornado]] moved through the city limits causing significant damage to more than 200 homes, as well as the [[Monroe Regional Airport (Louisiana)|Monroe Regional Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.magnoliareporter.com/news_and_business/regional_news/article_4f3bcd2e-7ce3-11ea-8412-1b0152c3f85d.html|title=Magnolia Reporter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Tornado Emergency for Monroe Louisiana and Northeast Ouachita Parish |url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=SVSSHV&e=202004121644 |website=Iowa Environmental Mesonet |publisher=National Weather Service Forecast Office in Shreveport, Louisiana |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SteveWAFB/status/1249799061898760192?s=20|title=Steve Caparotta of WAFB on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At 3:30 p.m. CDT, two back-to-back supercells began to produce three intense long-tracked tornadoes, including two rated EF4, that would move across southern Mississippi, prompting the [[National Weather Service]] in [[Jackson, Mississippi]] to issue multiple tornado emergencies for numerous towns including [[Prentiss, Mississippi|Prentiss]], [[Bassfield, Mississippi|Bassfield]], [[Collins, Mississippi|Collins]], and [[Soso, Mississippi|Soso]]. At 4:40 p.m. CDT, a second [[Particularly Dangerous Situation|PDS watch]] was issued affecting extreme southeast Mississippi and most of [[Alabama]], including the cities of [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]], [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]], [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]], and [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0110.html|title=Storm Prediction Center - PDS Watch 110|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As the system progressed northeastward into the nighttime hours, another tornado emergency was issued, this time at 11:28 p.m. EDT for the towns of [[Ooltewah, Tennessee|Ooltewah]] and [[Collegedale, Tennessee|Collegedale]] as a deadly EF3 tornado struck the eastern suburbs of [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]], killing three and injuring 19.<ref>https://twitter.com/NWSMorristown/status/1249735208460419073?s=20</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMRX&e=202004151915|title=NWS Morristown Damage Survey|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, the storms that formed the day before congealed into a strong [[squall line]] as they advanced into eastern [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] and the [[Carolinas]]. At 6:55 a.m. EDT, an embedded supercell within a [[Squall line|QLCS]] prompted yet another tornado emergency as [[Walterboro, South Carolina]] took a direct hit from a confirmed tornado.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSCharlestonSC/status/1249652455073370113?s=20|title=NWS Charleston SC on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> <ref>https://twitter.com/StuOstro/status/1250057470669721602</ref> Nine EF3 tornadoes occurred on day two of the outbreak, including seven in [[South Carolina]] that resulted in a combined eight deaths, most notably the 3/4-mile wide EF3 in [[Hampton County, South Carolina|Hampton County]] that took the lives of five people near the towns of [[Estill, South Carolina|Estill]] and Nixville.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSCHS&e=202004152035|title=NWS Charleston Damage Survey|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nWith 38 fatalities reported, it is the deadliest outbreak since March 2\u20133, 2012. .<ref>{{cite web |title=At Least 41 People Have Died After a Tornado Outbreak Ravaged the South |url=https://time.com/5820741/deadly-tornadoes-storms-south/ |website=TIME USA |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Tornado]]\n** [[Tornadoes by year]]\n** [[Tornado records]]\n** [[Tornado climatology]]\n** [[Tornado myths]]\n* [[List of tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of F5 and EF5 tornadoes]]\n** [[List of North American tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of 21st-century Canadian tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of European tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of tornadoes and tornado outbreaks in Asia]]\n** [[List of Southern Hemisphere tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of tornadoes striking downtown areas]]\n* [[Tornado intensity]]\n** [[Fujita scale]]\n** [[Enhanced Fujita scale]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2020 tornado months}}\n{{2020 tornado outbreaks}}\n{{Tornadoes by year}}\n\n[[Category:2020 meteorology]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes of 2020]]\n[[Category:Tornado-related lists by year]]\n[[Category:Tornado-related lists]]\n[[Category:2020 natural disasters]]\n[[Category:2020-related lists|Torn]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Notable tornadoes and tornado outbreaks in 2020}}\n{{Infobox tornado year\n|name          = Tornadoes of 2020\n|image         = 2020 United States tornado count.png\n|caption       = A chart of the 2020 United States tornado count estimated from the number of preliminary reports\n|timespan      = January 3 - ongoing\n|max_EF        = EF4\n|max_location  = [[Cookeville, Tennessee]]\n|max_date      = March 3\n|max_location2  = [[Jayess, Mississippi]]\n|max_date2      = April 12\n|max_location3  = [[Bassfield, Mississippi]]\n|max_date3      = April 12\n|tornadoes_usa = 368\n|total_damages_usa = >$4.4&nbsp;billion total economic losses\n|total_fatalities_world = 72\n|total_fatalities_usa = 72\n|year = 2020\n}}\n\nThis page documents notable [[tornado]]es and [[tornado outbreak]]s worldwide in '''2020'''. Strong and destructive tornadoes form most frequently in the [[United States]], [[Argentina]], [[Brazil]], [[Bangladesh]], and [[East India|Eastern India]], but can occur almost anywhere under the right conditions. Tornadoes also develop occasionally in southern [[Canada]] during the [[Northern Hemisphere]]'s summer and somewhat regularly at other times of the year across [[Europe]], [[Asia]], [[Argentina]], [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]]. Tornadic events are often accompanied by other forms of [[severe weather]], including strong [[thunderstorm]]s, strong [[winds]], and [[hail]].\n\nThere have been 456 preliminary filtered reports of tornadoes in the United States in 2020,<ref>{{cite web |title=Annual Severe Weather Report Summary 2020 |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/online/monthly/2020_annual_summary.html |publisher=Storm Prediction Center |accessdate=January 8, 2020}}</ref> of which at least 368 have been confirmed. Worldwide, 72 tornado-related deaths have been confirmed, all in the United States.\n\n==Events==\n{{Tornadoes of 2020/Deadly}}\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020}}\n\n===United States yearly total===\n<!-- This section is transcluded to other articles; modify with caution. -->\n<onlyinclude>\n{{Tornado Chart\n|Total = 368\n|FU = 7\n|F0 = 110\n|F1 = 174\n|F2 = 54\n|F3 = 14\n|F4 = 3\n|F5 = 0\n| Enhanced=yes\n}}\n</onlyinclude>\n\n==January==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#January}}\nThere were 90 tornadoes reported in the United States in January, of which 87 were confirmed. Overall, January was an active month, with over twice the national average of 35 tornadoes.\n\n===January 3 (South Africa)===\nOn January 3, severe thunderstorms developed over the [[Mpumalanga]] province of [[South Africa]]. One thunderstorm developed into a supercell which produced an EF3 tornado that caused significant damage to a farm, destroyed the houses of seven families, and destroyed about {{convert|200|hectare|acre|sigfig=1}} of pine forest.<ref>{{cite web |title=Media Release: Panbult tornado (Mpumalanga) on the 3rd of January 2020. |url=https://twitter.com/SAWeatherServic/status/1214087467692941312?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1214087467692941312&ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.news24.com%2FSouthAfrica%2FNews%2Fwatch-tornado-lasting-about-40-minutes-destroyed-farm-and-7-houses-in-mpumalanga-saws-confirms-20200106 |website=Twitter |publisher=South African Weather Service |accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===January 10\u201311===\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of January 10\u201311, 2020}}\n{{stack begin}}{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 25|EF1= 41|EF2= 13|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU=0}}{{stack end}}\n[[File:Carollton EF2 damage1.jpg|thumb||float|left|High-end EF2 damage to a house near Carrollton, Alabama.]]\nOn January 10, the Storm Prediction Center issues a moderate risk of severe weather for much of the Southern United States, including a 15% hatched risk of tornadoes. A squall line of severe thunderstorms with numerous embedded circulations and semi-discrete supercell structures moved from [[Texas]] and [[Oklahoma]] to the [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]], producing numerous tornadoes. A high-end EF2 tornado near [[Carrollton, Alabama]] destroyed multiple homes and mobile homes, and resulted in three fatalities.<ref>{{cite web |title=Three people killed in Pickens Co. tornado |url=https://www.wbrc.com/2020/01/11/three-people-killed-pickens-co-tornado/ |publisher=WBRC |accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> Three people were fatally injured when a long-tracked EF2 tornado destroyed two mobile homes south of [[Haughton, Louisiana]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Enfinger |first1=Emily |title=87-year-old dies from injuries from Haughton tornado |url=https://eu.shreveporttimes.com/story/news/local/2020/01/15/third-death-confimred-haughton-tornado/4480014002/ |publisher=Shreveport Times |accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref> and an EF1 tornado killed one person near [[Nacogdoches, Texas]] when a large tree fell onto a mobile home.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brackett |first1=Ron |last2=Wesner Childs |first2=Jan |title=Tornadoes, Severe Storms Kill 8; More Than 300,000 Lose Power |url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-01-11-severe-storms-tornadoes-impact-texas-louisiana-tennessee-arkansas-mississippi |website=weather.com |publisher=The Weather Channel |accessdate=January 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Houston, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey for January 10 Burleson County Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSHGX&e=202001112109|date=January 11, 2020|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> An EF2 tornado struck [[Rome, Mississippi]], causing significant damage and destroying the local post office. An EF2 tornado also struck [[Union Grove, Alabama]], significantly damaging a school building in the community. Another school also sustained major damage near [[Kershaw, South Carolina]], as a result of another EF2 tornado. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 79 tornadoes, and resulted in 7 fatalities. Total damage from the event reached $1.1&nbsp;billion according to the [[National Centers for Environmental Information]].<ref name=\"NCEI_billion\">{{cite web|publisher=National Centers for Environmental Information|year=2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Billion-Dollar Weather and Climate Disasters: Events|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/billions/events}}</ref>\n\n==February==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#February}}\nThere were 51 tornadoes reported in the United States in February, of which 42 were confirmed. February was also an active month, besting the national average of 29 tornadoes.\n\n===February 5\u20137===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 9|EF1= 21|EF2= 6|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU=1}}\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of February 5\u20137, 2020}}\n[[File:KannapolisNCEF2-2020.jpg|thumb||float|left|EF2 damage to a house near Kannapolis, North Carolina.]]\nBeginning on February 5, a moderate tornado outbreak affected the Deep South and Eastern United States. On the first day of the outbreak, an EF2 tornado caused significant tree and outbuilding damage near [[Pickens, Mississippi]], and injured four people. A long-tracked EF2 tornado touched down near [[Bay Springs, Mississippi]] and passed though the town of [[Enterprise, Clarke County, Mississippi|Enterprise]], downing numerous trees and power poles and toppling a metal fire tower. This tornado tore large sections of roofing off of multiple homes in rural areas as well. On February 6, one person was killed in [[Marengo County, Alabama]] when an EF1 tornado destroyed a mobile home near [[Demopolis, Alabama|Demopolis]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Birmingham, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey for 02/06/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=202002070055|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Jackson, Mississippi|title=NWS Damage Survey for 02/05/2020 - 02/06/2020 Tornado Event - Update #1|url=http://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSJAN&e=202002070252|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=February 6, 2020|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref> An EF2 tornado also touched down near [[Kannapolis, North Carolina]], to the north of [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]]. No injuries were reported, though multiple homes were damaged, including one that lost its roof and some exterior walls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/02/06/tornado-touches-down-kannapolis/|title=Tornado touches down in Kannapolis|website=WBTV|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wcnc.com/article/weather/confirmed-tornado-damages-homes-in-kannapolis/275-3a51f749-53cd-490f-bf2c-3fd08c8c793c|title=Confirmed tornado damages homes in the Kannapolis area|website=WCNC|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Tornado rips roof off home in Kannapolis, North Carolina|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gE8N-dBHI7k|language=en|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> Another EF2 downed metal truss transmission towers near [[Kings Mountain, North Carolina|Kings Mountain]], and an EF1 tornado caused damage in the southern suburbs of Charlotte.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://salisburypost.com/2020/02/08/three-rescued-from-flood-waters-weather-service-confirms-tornado-in-rowan-county/|title=As flooding, damage lingers, 3 rescued from Third Creek, weather service confirms tornadoes in Rowan|last=Walker|first=Shavonne|work=[[Salisbury Post]]|date=2020-02-08|accessdate=2020-02-08}}</ref><ref name=WBTV>{{cite news|url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/02/07/nws-confirms-ef-tornado-near-pineville/|title=NWS confirms EF-1 tornado near Pineville|last=Myers|first=Jason|work=[[WBTV]]|date=2020-02-07|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wcnc.com/article/weather/tornado-stanly-albemarle-damage-storm/275-227d0b28-9341-4b91-a7a0-057602e4a803|title=EF-1 tornado confirmed near Albemarle|work=[[WCNC-TV]]|date=2020-02-07|accessdate=2020-02-13}}</ref> A high-end EF1 tornado moved directly through [[Spartanburg, South Carolina]] as well, causing considerable damage to homes and businesses.<ref name=WBTV/> On February 7, five tornadoes touched down in Maryland, including an EF1 that struck [[Westminster, Maryland|Westminster]] and [[Manchester, Maryland|Manchester]], causing moderate damage. An EF0 tornado also caused minor damage in [[Leesburg, Virginia]]. Along with the tornadic storms, a widespread amount of flooding has also occurred throughout the southern states. Total economic losses from the event exceeded $925&nbsp;million. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 37 tornadoes, and resulted in one fatality.<ref>{{cite report|publisher=Aon|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Global Catastrophe Recap: February 2020|url=http://thoughtleadership.aonbenfield.com/Documents/20200309_analytics-if-february-global-recap.pdf|page=4|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n==March==\n{{See also|List of United States tornadoes from January to March 2020#March}}\nThere were 106 tornadoes reported in the United States in March, of which 77 were confirmed. Although March was slightly below average in number of tornadoes, the series of severe weather outbreaks and tornadoes throughout March inflicted widespread damage across the country. Combined economic losses reached approximately $2.4&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|author=Matt Sheehan|publisher=Reinsurance News|date=April 14, 2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020|title=Separate billion-dollar events mark active month for US tornadoes: Aon|url=https://www.reinsurancene.ws/separate-billion-dollar-events-mark-active-month-for-us-tornadoes-aon/}}</ref>\n\n===March 2\u20133===\n{{Main|Tornado outbreak of March 2\u20133, 2020}}\n[[File:CookevilleTNEF4rubbleanddamage.jpg|thumb||float|left|EF4 damage in a residential area of Cookeville, Tennessee.]]\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 5|EF1= 3|EF2= 4|EF3= 1|EF4= 1|EF5= 0|EFU= 1}}\nA small but devastating tornado outbreak affected parts of the Southern United States on the evening of March 2 into the early morning hours of March 3, with the most severe damage and all fatalities occurring in Tennessee. [[Nashville, Tennessee]] was directly struck by a high-end EF3 tornado just after 12:30&nbsp;a.m. CDT on March 3. Major structural damage and six fatalities occurred as the tornado passed just north of downtown Nashville and through [[Mount Juliet, Tennessee|Mount Juliet]] to the east. Additional tornadoes were reported in [[Missouri]], [[Alabama]], [[Tennessee]], and [[Kentucky]]. An EF2 tornado killed one person and caused significant damage to homes, mobile homes, and outbuildings near [[Camden, Tennessee]] as well. The majority of the deaths occurred in Putnam County, where a violent EF4 tornado touched down near [[Baxter, Tennessee|Baxter]] shortly before 2:00&nbsp;a.m. and moved into western [[Cookeville, Tennessee|Cookeville]]. Many homes and other buildings were completely leveled or swept away in residential areas of Cookeville, and 19 people were killed in town.<ref name=\"OHX\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Nashville, Tennessee|title=March 2-3, 2020 Tornadoes and Severe Weather|url=https://www.weather.gov/ohx/20200303|publisher=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date=March 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=21 killed, 221 hospitalized after tornadoes rip through Nashville, surrounding areas|url=https://www.abcactionnews.com/news/national/six-killed-at-least-20-hurt-after-tornadoes-rip-through-nashville-surrounding-areas|publisher=ABC Action News|date=March 3, 2020|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref> In addition, two EF2 tornadoes also downed numerous trees in forested areas near [[Alvaton, Kentucky]] and [[Clarkrange, Tennessee]] as well. A lone, long-tracked [[supercell]] thunderstorm was responsible for all nine of the tornadoes in Tennessee as it moved from near [[Dyersburg, Tennessee|Dyersburg]] in West Tennessee to near [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]] in East Tennessee. Overall, this outbreak produced a total of 15 tornadoes, and resulted in 26 fatalities.<ref name=\"OHX\"/>\n\n===March 18\u201319===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 5|EF1= 11|EF2= 5|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nDuring the evenings of March 18 and 19, rounds of severe storms impacted a large area from [[West Texas]] to [[Ohio]], spawning several tornadoes. On March 18, an intense [[supercell thunderstorm]] spawned numerous weak tornadoes as it tracked through [[Jack County, Texas|Jack]], [[Stephens County, Texas|Stephens]], [[Wise County, Texas|Wise]], and [[Young County, Texas|Young counties]] in [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Fort Worth, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/18/2020 Tornado Event - Update #2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSFWD&e=202003201858|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> Overnight, an EF2 tornado damaged a farm southwest of [[Merkel, Texas]], and another EF2 debarked trees and damaged a home nearby (these two tracks may have been the same tornado).<ref name=\"SJT0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in San Angelo, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event - Update #1|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSSJT&e=202003201627|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> The thunderstorm responsible for those tornadoes went on to produce an EF1 and an EF2 tornado that damaged a large building and over 100 cars northeast of [[Abilene, Texas|Abilene]].<ref name=\"SJT0319\"/>\n\nOn March 19, a large portion of the southern [[Great Plains]] was in line for severe storms.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Darrow|title=Mar 19, 2020 0100 UTC Day 1 Convective Outlook|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/outlook/archive/2020/day1otlk_20200319_0100.html|publisher=Storm Prediction Center|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> During the afternoon, a squall line with several embedded supercells formed from [[Oklahoma]] to [[Indiana]], producing tornadoes in [[Oklahoma]], [[Illinois]], and [[Arkansas]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tulsa, Oklahoma|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTSA&e=202003210250|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PAH0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003202132|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"LZK0319\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 3/19/2020 Tornadoes Update #2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLZK&e=202003212158|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 21, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref> A large EF2 tornado touched down near [[Everton, Arkansas]], removing the top floor from one house and tossing an exercise bike into the side window of a [[Chevrolet Suburban|Chevy suburban]].<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/> Three EF1 tornadoes touched down in Arkansas, one of which caused damage between [[Gassville, Arkansas|Gassville]] and [[Mountain Home, Arkansas|Mountain Home]], destroying one home and tearing the roof off of another.<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/> One person was injured in Illinois,<ref name=\"PAH0319\"/> and another in Arkansas.<ref name=\"LZK0319\"/>\n\n===March 28\u201329===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 3|EF1= 11|EF2= 2|EF3= 1|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 3}}\nAn EF3 tornado struck the city of [[Jonesboro, Arkansas]], while being streamed live on local news stations, producing major damage and causing 22 injuries.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tornado flattens buildings in Jonesboro, Arkansas, as severe weather moves across the Midwest, Lower Mississippi River Valley |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/28/weather/tornadoes-severe-storms-forecast-saturday/index.html |website=CNN |publisher=CNN |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Damage Reported in Northeastern Arkansas as Tornado Strikes Jonesboro |url=https://weather.com/news/news/2020-03-28-severe-weather-tornado-impacts-plains-south-midwest |website=Weather.com |publisher=The Weather Channel |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"20200328 reports\">{{cite web |title=Today's Storm Reports (20200328 1200 UTC - 20200329 1159 UTC) (Print Version) |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200328_rpts.html|website=NOAA |publisher=NOAA |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MEG0328\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Memphis, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMEG&e=202003292239|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Damage from Jonesboro shows numerous cars lofted and mangled in a shopping mall parking lot, with missile debris embedded into the ground. A train was also derailed, while the municipal airport sustained major damage, with hangars demolished and at least one plane flipped.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zoellner |first1=Danielle |title=Tornado rips through Arkansas town, injuring six people |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/arkansas-tornado-jonesboro-weather-injured-a9432511.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\nThe same storm that produced this tornado also produced two EF1 tornadoes, one before and one after it moved over Jonesboro.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Little Rock, Arkansas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLZK&e=202003292104|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"MEG0328\"/>\nInto the evening, numerous weak tornadoes touched down in [[Iowa]] and [[Illinois]], and another in southwest [[Wisconsin]].<ref name=\"20200328 reports\"/>\nAn EF2 tornado was on the ground for 17 miles southwest of [[Henderson, Kentucky]], destroying a barn and damaging dozens of homes and outbuildings.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Henderson County KY Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003300139|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\nAnother EF2 touched down concurrently in [[Newburgh, Indiana]], removing portions of roofs or walls on five homes and damaging several others. Two people were injured.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Paducah, Kentucky|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/28/20 Newburgh Indiana Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSPAH&e=202003300138|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 29, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nEarly in the morning of March 29, the same storm system produced an EF0 tornado that mainly damaged trees near [[Sparta, Tennessee]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Nashville, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/29/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSOHX&e=202003311858|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March 30\u201331 ===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 9|EF1= 3|EF2= 1|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 2}}\nOn the evening of March 30, isolated supercells developed across Texas and Oklahoma, producing two weak tornadoes. One of these was given an EFU rating, and the other, which was a [[landspout]] or non-mesocylonic tornado, was given an EF0 rating.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Amarillo, Texas|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/30/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSAMA&e=202003312336|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref> \nOn March 31, multiple supercells and embedded mesocyclones formed along and just ahead of a convective line, with 15 preliminary tornado reports in the [[southeastern United States]].<ref name=\"SPC 3/31\">{{cite web |title=SPC Storm reports for03/31/20 |url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/climo/reports/200331_rpts.html |publisher=Storm Prediction |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\nAn EF2 tornado caused significant damage in [[Eufaula, Alabama]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fuentes |first1=Carmen |title=Eufaula tornado runs through neighborhood |url=https://www.wtvy.com/content/news/Eufaula-tornado-runs-through-neighborhood-569268011.html |accessdate=1 April 2020 |agency=WTVY |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BMX0331\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Birmingham, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/31/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=202004020401|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref> and several weaker ones were reported in southeast [[Mississippi]], southern [[Alabama]], and northern [[Florida]].<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee, Florida|title=NWS Damage Survey For 03/31/20 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTAE&e=202004032145|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=April 3, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"BMX0331\"/> Another tornado was caught on video around 2:30&nbsp;p.m. PDT in [[Washington (state)|Washington state]].<ref name=\"SPC 3/31\"/>\n\n==April==\n{{see also|List of United States tornadoes in April 2020}}\nThere have been 162 tornadoes confirmed in the United States in April.\n\n===April 7\u20139===\n{{Tornado chart small|EF0= 20|EF1= 10|EF2= 1|EF3= 0|EF4= 0|EF5= 0|EFU= 0}}\nSeveral tornadoes touched down across [[Ohio]] and [[Pennsylvania]] late on April 7 and into the early morning of April 8. Later in the afternoon on April 8, an EF0 tornado briefly touched down west-southwest of [[Jonesboro, Arkansas]] near the town of [[Cash, Arkansas|Cash]], followed by an EF2 tornado in the vicinity of [[Weiner, Arkansas|Weiner]] and [[Harrisburg, Arkansas]] in [[Poinsett County, Arkansas|Poinsett County]].<ref>https://twitter.com/nwsmemphis/status/1248334194377232384?s=21</ref><ref>https://media.arkansasonline.com/img/photos/2020/04/09/storm1_t800.jpg?90232451fbcadccc64a17de7521d859a8f88077d</ref> In Harrisburg, one home was completely leveled by the tornado, and several homes nearby were also badly damaged as well.<ref>https://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2020/apr/09/forecasters-tornado-touched-down-overnight-northwe/#.Xo9c00N8lmQ.twitter</ref> Numerous homes were heavily damaged and two people were injured in Harrisburg.<ref>https://twitter.com/kwoodallTV/status/1248076374084124673?s=19</ref> More tornadoes, mainly weak and short-lived, occurred across [[Indiana]], [[Kentucky]], and Ohio.\n\n=== April 12\u201313 ===\n{{Tornado chart small|FU = 0|F0 = 29|F1 = 67|F2 = 21|F3 = 12|F4 = 2|F5 = 0|Enhanced=yes}}\n{{main|2020 Easter tornado outbreak}}\nFrom the late morning of April 12 through the early morning of April 13, a major tornado outbreak unfolded across the [[Southeastern United States]], with more than 100 tornadoes touching down in 24 hours over two days. Over a 48 hour period from nighttime on April 11th to the evening of April 13th, 131 tornadoes touched down from Texas to Marylans. his event was well forecasted, with the [[Storm Prediction Center]] issuing severe weather outlooks as early as five days before the outbreak. At 10:40 a.m. CDT on April 12, a [[Particularly Dangerous Situation]] [[Tornado Watch]] was issued by the Storm Prediction Center across northeast [[Louisiana]], southeast [[Arkansas]], and central and northern [[Mississippi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0106.html|title=PDS Watch 106|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At 11:44 a.m. CDT, a [[Tornado emergency|tornado emergency]] was issued for [[Monroe, Louisiana]] as an [[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF3 tornado]] moved through the city limits causing significant damage to more than 200 homes, as well as the [[Monroe Regional Airport (Louisiana)|Monroe Regional Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.magnoliareporter.com/news_and_business/regional_news/article_4f3bcd2e-7ce3-11ea-8412-1b0152c3f85d.html|title=Magnolia Reporter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Tornado Emergency for Monroe Louisiana and Northeast Ouachita Parish |url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=SVSSHV&e=202004121644 |website=Iowa Environmental Mesonet |publisher=National Weather Service Forecast Office in Shreveport, Louisiana |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SteveWAFB/status/1249799061898760192?s=20|title=Steve Caparotta of WAFB on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> At 3:30 p.m. CDT, two back-to-back supercells began to produce three intense long-tracked tornadoes, including two rated EF4, that would move across southern Mississippi, prompting the [[National Weather Service]] in [[Jackson, Mississippi]] to issue multiple tornado emergencies for numerous towns including [[Prentiss, Mississippi|Prentiss]], [[Bassfield, Mississippi|Bassfield]], [[Collins, Mississippi|Collins]], and [[Soso, Mississippi|Soso]]. At 4:40 p.m. CDT, a second [[Particularly Dangerous Situation|PDS watch]] was issued affecting extreme southeast Mississippi and most of [[Alabama]], including the cities of [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]], [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]], [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]], and [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spc.noaa.gov/products/watch/ww0110.html|title=Storm Prediction Center - PDS Watch 110|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As the system progressed northeastward into the nighttime hours, another tornado emergency was issued, this time at 11:28 p.m. EDT for the towns of [[Ooltewah, Tennessee|Ooltewah]] and [[Collegedale, Tennessee|Collegedale]] as a deadly EF3 tornado struck the eastern suburbs of [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]], killing three and injuring 19.<ref>https://twitter.com/NWSMorristown/status/1249735208460419073?s=20</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMRX&e=202004151915|title=NWS Morristown Damage Survey|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, the storms that formed the day before congealed into a strong [[squall line]] as they advanced into eastern [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] and the [[Carolinas]]. At 6:55 a.m. EDT, an embedded supercell within a [[Squall line|QLCS]] prompted yet another tornado emergency as [[Walterboro, South Carolina]] took a direct hit from a confirmed tornado.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NWSCharlestonSC/status/1249652455073370113?s=20|title=NWS Charleston SC on Twitter|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> <ref>https://twitter.com/StuOstro/status/1250057470669721602</ref> Nine EF3 tornadoes occurred on day two of the outbreak, including seven in [[South Carolina]] that resulted in a combined eight deaths, most notably the 3/4-mile wide EF3 in [[Hampton County, South Carolina|Hampton County]] that took the lives of five people near the towns of [[Estill, South Carolina|Estill]] and Nixville.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSCHS&e=202004152035|title=NWS Charleston Damage Survey|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nWith 38 fatalities reported, it is the deadliest outbreak since March 2\u20133, 2012. .<ref>{{cite web |title=At Least 41 People Have Died After a Tornado Outbreak Ravaged the South |url=https://time.com/5820741/deadly-tornadoes-storms-south/ |website=TIME USA |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Tornado]]\n** [[Tornadoes by year]]\n** [[Tornado records]]\n** [[Tornado climatology]]\n** [[Tornado myths]]\n* [[List of tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of F5 and EF5 tornadoes]]\n** [[List of North American tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of 21st-century Canadian tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of European tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of tornadoes and tornado outbreaks in Asia]]\n** [[List of Southern Hemisphere tornadoes and tornado outbreaks]]\n** [[List of tornadoes striking downtown areas]]\n* [[Tornado intensity]]\n** [[Fujita scale]]\n** [[Enhanced Fujita scale]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2020 tornado months}}\n{{2020 tornado outbreaks}}\n{{Tornadoes by year}}\n\n[[Category:2020 meteorology]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes of 2020]]\n[[Category:Tornado-related lists by year]]\n[[Category:Tornado-related lists]]\n[[Category:2020 natural disasters]]\n[[Category:2020-related lists|Torn]]\n", "name_user": "Ionmars10", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tornadoes_of_2020"}
{"title_page": "Action of 31 March 1800", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Action of 31 March 1800\n|partof=the [[French Revolutionary Wars]]\n|image=The capture of the Guillaume Tell.jpg\n|image_size = 300px\n|caption=''Capture of the [[French ship Guillaume Tell (1795)|Guillaume Tell]]'' 31 March 1800, by [[Nicholas Pocock]]\n|date=31 March 1800\n|place=[[Malta Channel]], [[Mediterranean]]\n|coordinates={{coords|36.3660339|14.0182518|display = inline}}\n|result=British victory\n|combatant1={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Great Britain}}\n|combatant2={{flagcountry|French First Republic}}\n|commander1={{flagdeco|Kingdom of Great Britain|naval}} [[Manley Dixon]]\n|commander2={{flagdeco|French First Republic|naval}} [[Denis Decr\u00e8s]]\n|strength1=2 ships of the line <br> 1 frigate <br> 2 brig <br> 1 bomb vessel\n|strength2=1 ship of the line\n|casualties1=18 killed<br> 110 wounded\n|casualties2=200 killed and wounded <br> 1 ship of the line captured\n|campaignbox={{Campaignbox Mediterranean campaign of 1798}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Action of 31 March 1800''' was a naval engagement of the [[French Revolutionary Wars]] fought between a [[Royal Navy]] squadron and a [[French Navy]] [[ship of the line]] off [[Malta]] in the [[Mediterranean Sea]]. By March 1800 [[Valletta]], the Maltese capital, had been [[Siege of Malta (1798-1800)|under siege]] for eighteen months and food supplies were severely depleted, a problem exacerbated by the [[Battle of the Malta Convoy (1800)|interception and defeat]] of a French replenishment convoy in mid-February. In an effort to simultaneously obtain help from France and reduce the number of personnel maintained in the city, the naval commander on the island, Contre-amiral [[Pierre-Charles Villeneuve]], ordered his subordinate Contre-amiral [[Denis Decr\u00e8s]] to put to sea with the large ship of the line [[French ship Guillaume Tell (1795)|''Guillaume Tell'']], which had arrived in the port shortly before the siege began in September 1798. Over 900 men were carried aboard the ship, which was to sail for [[Toulon]] under cover of darkness on 30 March.\n\nThe British had maintained a blockade off Malta since the beginning of the siege, ostensibly led by Rear-Admiral [[Horatio Nelson|Lord Nelson]], who by March 1800 was defying a direct order from his superior officer [[George Elphinstone, 1st Viscount Keith|Lord Keith]] by remaining in [[Palermo]] with his lover [[Emma, Lady Hamilton]]. In his absence the blockade was under the command of Captain [[Manley Dixon]] of [[HMS Lion (1777)|HMS ''Lion'']] and Nelson's flag captain [[Sir Edward Berry]], who were notified of Decr\u00e9s' departure by the patrolling [[frigate]] [[HMS Penelope (1798)|HMS ''Penelope'']] and gave chase. The large ship of the line was initially only attacked by ''Penelope'', which manoeuvered around ''Guillaume Tell''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s stern, causing severe damage and delaying the French ship sufficiently for Berry to bring his squadron into action. Despite being heavily outnumbered, Decr\u00e9s continued to fight for more than three hours, fighting off two British ships but ultimately unable to resist the combined weight of Berry's attacks. Casualties and damage were severe on both sides, and the defiance of the French ship was celebrated in both countries as a brave defence against overwhelming odds.\n\n==Background==\nIn May 1798, a French fleet under General [[Napoleon Bonaparte]] [[Mediterranean campaign of 1798|crossed the]] [[Mediterranean Sea]], sailing for [[Egypt]]. Pausing at [[Malta]] on 9 June, Bonaparte landed soldiers and seized the island leaving a sizeable French garrison at [[Valletta]] under General [[Claude-Henri Belgrand de Vaubois]] while the rest of the fleet continued on to [[Alexandria]].<ref name=\"RLA13\">Adkins, p. 13</ref> After the successful landing in Egypt, Bonaparte marched inland at the head of his army. The fleet anchored in [[Aboukir Bay]] to support the troops ashore and was surprised and almost completely destroyed on 1 August by a British fleet under Rear-Admiral [[Sir Horatio Nelson]]. Only two [[ships of the line]] and two [[frigates]] escaped the [[Battle of the Nile]] from the 17 French ships that participated in the action.<ref name=\"NM272\">Mostert, p. 272</ref> Of the survivors, the ship of the line [[French ship Le G\u00e9n\u00e9reux|''G\u00e9n\u00e9reux'']] sailed for [[Corfu]] while [[French ship Guillaume Tell (1795)|''Guillaume Tell'']], under Contre-amiral [[Pierre-Charles Villeneuve]], reached Malta with the two frigates.<ref name=\"WLC374\">Clowes, p. 374</ref>\n\nWhen Villeneuve arrived at Malta in September 1798, the island was already in turmoil: the dissolution of the [[Roman Catholic Church]] on the island under French rule had been highly unpopular with the [[Maltese people|Maltese population]], who forced the French garrison to retreat into the fortress of Valletta on 2 September.<ref name=\"RG67\">Gardiner, p. 67</ref> By the start of October, British and Portuguese troops had supplemented the Maltese irregulars, while a naval squadron watched Valletta harbour, to prevent any French effort to resupply and reinforce the garrison.<ref name=\"WJ2:189\">James, Vol. 2, p. 189</ref> Although small quantities of material reached Valletta from France in early 1799, by the start of 1800 no ship had arrived for more than seven months, and the garrison was near starvation.<ref name=\"WLC418\">Clowes, p. 418</ref> In an effort to resupply the garrison, the French sent a convoy from [[Toulon]] in February 1800, but the ships were intercepted off Malta by a squadron under Nelson on 17 February and in the [[Battle of the Malta Convoy (1800)|ensuing battle]] the flagship [[French ship Le G\u00e9n\u00e9reux|''G\u00e9n\u00e9reux'']] was captured and Contre-amiral [[Jean-Baptiste Perr\u00e9e]] was killed.<ref name=EB247>Bradford, p. 247</ref>\n\nWithout Perr\u00e9e's supplies, the garrison faced continued food shortages, and by March Vaubois and Villeneuve decided to send an urgent request for support to France. For this operation they chose the 80-gun ''Guillaume Tell'' under Captain Saulnier, partly because the condition and size of the ship enabled Vaubois to embark over 900 men aboard, many of whom were sick or wounded.<ref name=\"RG69\">Gardiner, p. 69</ref> Contre-amiral [[Denis Decr\u00e8s]] had command of the ship and Vaubois and Villeneuve confirmed the date of departure for 30 March. While the French prepared this expedition, the British maintained their blockade, although without their commander. Nelson, in defiance of specific orders from his commanding officer [[George Elphinstone, 1st Viscount Keith|Lord Keith]], had retired to [[Palermo]] on [[Sicily]] to be with [[Emma, Lady Hamilton]], the wife of the British ambassador [[William Hamilton (diplomat)|Sir William Hamilton]] with whom Nelson was conducting an adulterous affair.<ref name=\"NM365\">Mostert, p. 365</ref> In his absence, command had passed to Captain [[Sir Thomas Troubridge, 1st Baronet|Sir Thomas Troubridge]] on [[HMS Culloden (1783)|HMS ''Culloden'']] and then to Captain [[Manley Dixon]] on [[HMS Lion (1777)|HMS ''Lion'']].<ref name=\"WLC420\">Clowes, p. 420</ref>\n\n==Battle==\nAt 23:00 on 30 March, with a strong wind from the south, ''Guillaume Tell'' sailed from Valletta, Decr\u00e9s hoping to use the cover of darkness to escape the British blockade. Dixon had deployed his ships around the island, with Valletta watched by the frigate [[HMS Penelope (1798)|HMS ''Penelope'']] under Captain [[Henry Blackwood]].<ref name=\"RG69\"/> At 23:55, Blackwood's lookouts spotted ''Guillaume Tell'' and the captain gave chase, ordering the [[brig]] [[HMS Minorca (1799)|HMS ''Minorca'']] under Commander [[George Miller (Royal Navy officer)|George Miller]] to convey the message to Dixon, whose ships were just visible in the distance.<ref name=\"WLC421\">Clowes, p. 421</ref> Blackwood also attempted to signal his discovery to his commanding officer as ''Penelope'' gave chase.<ref name=\"WJ3:16\">James, Vol. 3, p. 16</ref>\n\nBlackwood rapidly gained on the ship of the line and by 00:30 the frigate was within range, pulling up under the stern of ''Guillaume Tell'' and beginning a steady fire to which Decr\u00e9s could only respond with his stern-chasers, light cannon situated in the stern of the ship.<ref name=\"WJ3:17\">James, Vol. 3, p. 17</ref> Decr\u00e9s recognised that if he stopped to engage ''Penelope'' then the rest of Berry's squadron, visible on the horizon to the south, would soon overwhelm him. He therefore continued sailing to the northeast, hoping his heavy ship of the line could outrun the light and speedy frigate. However, ''Penelope'' was too fast, and Blackwood handled his ship with considerable skill, managing to pass Decr\u00e9s' stern repeatedly and pour several [[raking fire|raking]] broadsides into the French ship.<ref name=\"RW142\">Woodman, p. 142</ref>\n\nBlackwood's attack was so successful that by dawn on 31 March ''Guillaume Tell'' had lost its main and mizen topmasts and its main yard, considerably reducing the speed at which Decr\u00e9s could travel. The French ship had also suffered heavy casualties in the exchange, but ''Penelope'' had lost only one man killed and three wounded, and was almost undamaged.<ref name=\"WJ3:17\"/> British reinforcements were now arriving from the south: the 64-gun HMS ''Lion'' under Captain Dixon had received ''Minorca''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s warning at 01:00 and immediately sailed in pursuit, sending the brig on to Captain [[Sir Edward Berry]] in [[HMS Foudroyant (1798)|HMS ''Foudroyant'']], who lay some distance to leeward.<ref name=\"WJ3:18\">James, Vol. 3, p. 18</ref> By 05:00, Dixon was close enough to engage, passing between ''Penelope'' and ''Guillaume Tell'' and firing a triple-shotted broadside into the [[port (direction)|port]] side of the French ship. Shooting ahead of the now sluggish ''Guillaume Tell'', ''Lion'' crossed its opponent's bows and shot away the [[jib|jib boom]], allowing Dixon to maintain a position across the bow, raking the French ship from one end while ''Penelope'' did the same to the other.<ref name=\"WLC421\"/> During these manoeuvres, Dixon's ship had briefly become entangled with ''Guillaume Tell''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s rigging, and two determined efforts to board the British ship had been driven off as the ships were disentangled.<ref name=\"NM366\">Mostert, p. 366</ref>\n\nFor half an hour, ''Lion'' continued to fire into the larger ''Guillaume Tell'', but Dixon was unable to keep his ship completely out of range of the French broadsides and by 05:30 the subsequent damage showed an effect, ''Lion'' dropping back and falling behind the French vessel, although remaining within range alongside ''Penelope''.<ref name=\"RW142\"/> At 06:00, ''Guillaume Tell'' came under attack for the third time, when Berry himself caught up with the battling ships in ''Foudroyant'' and pulled along the [[starboard]] broadside of the French ship of the line. Berry hailed Decr\u00e9s to demand his surrender, and accompanied the demand with a triple-shotted broadside, to which Decr\u00e9s responded with fire from his own guns.<ref name=\"RG69\"/> ''Foudroyant'' was flying a full set of sails and therefore suffered severe damage to its rigging in the opening exchange, the additional speed provided by this rig forcing ''Foudroyant'' to move ahead of the French vessel.<ref name=\"WLC421\"/> After working back alongside ''Guillaume Tell'', Berry recommenced fire that rapidly tore away much of the remaining French rigging, allowing ''Lion'' and ''Penelope'' to return to the battle while ''Foudroyant'' dropped back to make urgent repairs.<ref name=\"WJ3:18\">James, Vol. 3, p. 18</ref>\n\nBy 06:30 the badly outnumbered French ship had lost both its main and mizen masts, ''Foudroyant'' returning to the battle in time to collapse the foremast by 08:00. At 08:20, with no means of making sail and with wreckage obscuring most of his gun decks, Decr\u00e9s surrendered to spare any further, fruitless, loss of life.<ref name=\"NM367\">Mostert, p. 367</ref> His ship was in danger: the lack of masts and strong winds caused it to roll so severely that the lower deck gun ports had to be closed to prevent the ship from foundering. Casualties on the French ship numbered more than 200, from a crew of over 900,<ref name=\"WJ3:19\"/> with both Decr\u00e9s and Saulnier badly wounded.<ref name=\"WLC422\">Clowes, p. 422</ref> British losses were lighter, with eight killed and 64 wounded, including Berry, in ''Foudroyant'', eight killed and 38 wounded in ''Lion'' and one killed and three wounded (one fatally) in ''Penelope''. Damage was unevenly spread, ''Foudroyant'' suffering most severely, with the hull and all masts damaged, the mizzenmast so badly that it collapsed at approximately 12:00, wounding five more men. ''Lion'' was badly hit, although not so severely as ''Foudroyant'' while ''Penelope'' was only lightly damaged in the masts and rigging. The battle, which had begun within sight of Malta, had concluded roughly {{convert|21|nmi|km}} south-west of [[Cape Passaro]] on Sicily.<ref name=\"WJ3:18\"/>\n\n==Aftermath==\nBoth ''Foudroyant'' and ''Lion'' were too battered to provide an effective tow to the dismasted French ship, and as a result ''Penelope'' was left to bring the shattered ''Guillaume Tell'' into [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]] on Sicily.<ref name=\"WJ3:19\"/> Eventually the ship was repaired sufficiently for the journey to Britain, and there was added to the Royal Navy under the name HMS ''Malta''. ''Malta'' was, with [[HMS Tonnant (1798)|HMS ''Tonnant'']] captured two years earlier at the Nile, the most powerful [[third rate]] in the British fleet, and served for many years,<ref name=\"RW143\">Woodman, p. 143</ref> participating at the [[Battle of Cape Finisterre (1805)|Battle of Cape Finisterre]] in 1805.\n\nThe British officers were praised for the capture of ''Guillaume Tell'', the last surviving French ship of the line to escape the Battle of the Nile: Nelson, who by his absence had \"missed what would indeed have been the crowning glory to his Mediterranean career\", wrote to Berry that \"Your conduct and character in the late glorious occasion stamps your fame beyond the reach of envy.\"<ref name=\"EB248\">Bradford, p. 248</ref> Despite Nelson's praise however, Berry in particular came in for subsequent criticism, especially from the historian [[William James (naval historian)|William James]], who wrote in his 1827 history of the conflict that:\n\n{{quote|\"Had the Foudroyant, single-handed, met the Guillaume-Tell, the combat would have been between two of the most powerful ships that had ever so met; and, although the Foudroyant's slight inferiority of force, being chiefly in number of men, was not that of which a British captain would complain, still the chances were equal, that the Guillaume-Tell, so gallantly manned, and so ably commanded, came off the conqueror.\"|William James, 1827|<ref name=\"WJ3:19\">James,Vol. 3, p. 19</ref>}}\n\nJames instead attributed most of the praise for the victory to Blackwood and Dixon, whose ships were heavily outmatched by ''Guillaume Tell'', but who successfully pressed their attacks with the intention of delaying the French retreat. He also highly praised Decr\u00e9s for his conduct in the engagement, stating that \"A more heroic defence than that of the Guillaume-Tell is not to be found among the records of naval actions\".<ref name=\"WJ3:19\"/> [[First Consul]] Napoleon Bonaparte reached a similar conclusion, and when Decr\u00e9s was [[prisoner exchange|exchanged]] soon after the battle he was presented with ''armes d'honneur'', later converted to membership of the ''[[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]''. He was also given the position of maritime prefect of the [[Biscay]] port of [[Lorient]].<ref name=\"WLC422\"/>\n\nAboard ''Guillaume Tell'', the British found evidence of the severity of the food shortages in Valletta: \"the only thing found in ''La Guillaume Tell'' was the leg of a [[mule]], hung for safety and his especial use of the admiral's stern-galley\".<ref name=\"RLA69\">Adkins, p. 69</ref> News of the capture of ''Guillaume Tell'' was immediately passed to Vaubois by the British besiegers, along with a demand that he surrender the island. The French general, despite dwindling food supplies, refused, stating ''\"Cette place est en trop bon \u00e9tat, et je suis moi-m\u00eame trop jaloux de bien servir mon pays et de conserver mon honneur, pour \u00e9couter vos propositions.\"'' (\"This place is in too good a situation, and I am too conscious of the service of my country and my honour, to listen to your proposals\"). Despite Vaubois' defiance, the garrison was rapidly starving, and although the French commander resisted until 4 September, he was eventually forced to surrender Valletta and all of its military equipment to the British.<ref name=\"WJ3:20\">James,Vol. 3, p. 20</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book\n | last = Adkins\n | first = Roy & Lesley\n | authorlink =\n | year = 2006\n | chapter =\n | title = The War for All the Oceans\n | publisher = Abacus\n | location =\n | isbn = 0-349-11916-3\n}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Bradford\n | first = Ernle\n | authorlink = Ernle Bradford\n | year = 1999 |origyear=1977\n | chapter =\n | title = Nelson: The Essential Hero\n | publisher = Wordsworth Military Library\n | location =\n | isbn = 1-84022-202-6\n}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Clowes\n | first = William Laird\n | authorlink = William Laird Clowes\n | year = 1997 |origyear=1900\n | chapter =\n | title = The Royal Navy, A History from the Earliest Times to 1900, Volume IV\n | publisher = Chatham Publishing\n | location =\n | isbn = 1-86176-013-2\n}}\n* {{cite book\n | editor =Gardiner, Robert\n | authorlink =\n | year = 2001\n | origyear= 1996\n | chapter =\n | title = Nelson Against Napoleon\n | publisher = Caxton Editions\n | location =\n | isbn = 1-86176-026-4\n}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = James\n | first = William\n | authorlink = William James (naval historian)\n | year = 2002 |origyear=1827\n | chapter =\n | title = The Naval History of Great Britain, Volume 2, 1797\u20131799\n | publisher = Conway Maritime Press\n | location =\n | isbn = 0-85177-906-9\n}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = James\n | first = William\n | authorlink = William James (naval historian)\n | year = 2002 |origyear=1827\n | chapter =\n | title = The Naval History of Great Britain, Volume 3, 1800\u20131805\n | publisher = Conway Maritime Press\n | location =\n | isbn = 0-85177-907-7\n}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Mostert\n | first = Noel\n | authorlink =\n | year = 2007\n | chapter =\n | title = The Line upon a Wind: The Greatest War Fought at Sea Under Sail 1793 \u2013 1815\n | publisher = Vintage Books\n | location =\n | isbn = 978-0-7126-0927-2\n}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Woodman\n | first = Richard\n | authorlink = Richard Woodman\n | year = 2001\n | chapter =\n | title = The Sea Warriors\n | publisher = Constable Publishers\n | location =\n | isbn = 1-84119-183-3\n}}\n\n{{French occupation of Malta}}\n\n[[Category:Naval battles involving France]]\n[[Category:Naval battles of the French Revolutionary Wars]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1800]]\n[[Category:Naval battles involving Great Britain]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Action of 31 March 1800\n|partof=the [[French Revolutionary Wars]]\n|image=Guillaume Tell PU5634.jpg\n|image_size = 300px\n|caption=''Capture of the William Tell'', by [[Robert Dodd (artist)|Robert Dodd]], October 1800\n|date=31 March 1800\n|place=[[Malta Channel]], [[Mediterranean]]\n|coordinates={{coords|36.3660339|14.0182518|display = inline}}\n|result=British victory\n|combatant1={{flagcountry|Kingdom of Great Britain}}\n|combatant2={{flagcountry|French First Republic}}\n|commander1=Captain [[Manley Dixon]]\n|commander2=Contre-amiral [[Denis Decr\u00e8s]]\n|strength1=[[Ships of the line]] {{HMS|Foudroyant|1798|2}} and {{HMS|Lion|1777|2}}, [[frigate]] {{HMS|Penelope|1798|2}}, brigs [[French brig Alerte (1787)|''Minorca'']] and {{HMS|Vincejo|1799|2}}, and [[bomb vessel]] {{HMS|Strombolo|1797|2}}\n|strength2=[[Ship of the line]] [[French ship Guillaume Tell (1795)|''Guillaume Tell'']]\n|casualties1=18 killed, 110 wounded\n|casualties2=Over 200 casualties, ''Guillaume Tell'' captured\n|campaignbox={{Campaignbox Mediterranean campaign of 1798}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Action of 31 March 1800''' was a naval engagement of the [[French Revolutionary Wars]] fought between a [[Royal Navy]] squadron and a [[French Navy]] [[ship of the line]] off [[Malta]] in the [[Mediterranean Sea]]. By March 1800 [[Valletta]], the Maltese capital, had been [[Siege of Malta (1798-1800)|under siege]] for eighteen months and food supplies were severely depleted, a problem exacerbated by the [[Battle of the Malta Convoy (1800)|interception and defeat]] of a French replenishment convoy in mid-February. In an effort to simultaneously obtain help from France and reduce the number of personnel maintained in the city, the naval commander on the island, Contre-amiral [[Pierre-Charles Villeneuve]], ordered his subordinate Contre-amiral [[Denis Decr\u00e8s]] to put to sea with the large ship of the line [[French ship Guillaume Tell (1795)|''Guillaume Tell'']], which had arrived in the port shortly before the siege began in September 1798. Over 900 men were carried aboard the ship, which was to sail for [[Toulon]] under cover of darkness on 30 March.\n\nThe British had maintained a blockade off Malta since the beginning of the siege, ostensibly led by Rear-Admiral [[Horatio Nelson|Lord Nelson]], who by March 1800 was defying a direct order from his superior officer [[George Elphinstone, 1st Viscount Keith|Lord Keith]] by remaining in [[Palermo]] with his lover [[Emma, Lady Hamilton]]. In his absence the blockade was under the command of Captain [[Manley Dixon]] of [[HMS Lion (1777)|HMS ''Lion'']] and Nelson's flag captain [[Sir Edward Berry]], who were notified of Decr\u00e9s' departure by the patrolling [[frigate]] [[HMS Penelope (1798)|HMS ''Penelope'']] and gave chase. The large ship of the line was initially only attacked by ''Penelope'', which manoeuvered around ''Guillaume Tell''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s stern, causing severe damage and delaying the French ship sufficiently for Berry to bring his squadron into action. Despite being heavily outnumbered, Decr\u00e9s continued to fight for more than three hours, fighting off two British ships but ultimately unable to resist the combined weight of Berry's attacks. Casualties and damage were severe on both sides, and the defiance of the French ship was celebrated in both countries as a brave defence against overwhelming odds.\n\n==Background==\nIn May 1798, a French fleet under General [[Napoleon Bonaparte]] [[Mediterranean campaign of 1798|crossed the]] [[Mediterranean Sea]], sailing for [[Egypt]]. Pausing at [[Malta]] on 9 June, Bonaparte landed soldiers and seized the island leaving a sizeable French garrison at [[Valletta]] under General [[Claude-Henri Belgrand de Vaubois]] while the rest of the fleet continued on to [[Alexandria]].<ref name=\"RLA13\">Adkins, p. 13</ref> After the successful landing in Egypt, Bonaparte marched inland at the head of his army. The fleet anchored in [[Aboukir Bay]] to support the troops ashore and was surprised and almost completely destroyed on 1 August by a British fleet under Rear-Admiral [[Sir Horatio Nelson]]. Only two [[ships of the line]] and two [[frigates]] escaped the [[Battle of the Nile]] from the 17 French ships that participated in the action.<ref name=\"NM272\">Mostert, p. 272</ref> Of the survivors, the ship of the line [[French ship Le G\u00e9n\u00e9reux|''G\u00e9n\u00e9reux'']] sailed for [[Corfu]] while [[French ship Guillaume Tell (1795)|''Guillaume Tell'']], under Contre-amiral [[Pierre-Charles Villeneuve]], reached Malta with the two frigates.<ref name=\"WLC374\">Clowes, p. 374</ref>\n\nWhen Villeneuve arrived at Malta in September 1798, the island was already in turmoil: the dissolution of the [[Roman Catholic Church]] on the island under French rule had been highly unpopular with the [[Maltese people|Maltese population]], who forced the French garrison to retreat into the fortress of Valletta on 2 September.<ref name=\"RG67\">Gardiner, p. 67</ref> By the start of October, British and Portuguese troops had supplemented the Maltese irregulars, while a naval squadron watched Valletta harbour, to prevent any French effort to resupply and reinforce the garrison.<ref name=\"WJ2:189\">James, Vol. 2, p. 189</ref> Although small quantities of material reached Valletta from France in early 1799, by the start of 1800 no ship had arrived for more than seven months, and the garrison was near starvation.<ref name=\"WLC418\">Clowes, p. 418</ref> In an effort to resupply the garrison, the French sent a convoy from [[Toulon]] in February 1800, but the ships were intercepted off Malta by a squadron under Nelson on 17 February and in the [[Battle of the Malta Convoy (1800)|ensuing battle]] the flagship [[French ship Le G\u00e9n\u00e9reux|''G\u00e9n\u00e9reux'']] was captured and Contre-amiral [[Jean-Baptiste Perr\u00e9e]] was killed.<ref name=EB247>Bradford, p. 247</ref>\n\nWithout Perr\u00e9e's supplies, the garrison faced continued food shortages, and by March Vaubois and Villeneuve decided to send an urgent request for support to France. For this operation they chose the 80-gun ''Guillaume Tell'' under Captain Saulnier, partly because the condition and size of the ship enabled Vaubois to embark over 900 men aboard, many of whom were sick or wounded.<ref name=\"RG69\">Gardiner, p. 69</ref> Contre-amiral [[Denis Decr\u00e8s]] had command of the ship and Vaubois and Villeneuve confirmed the date of departure for 30 March. While the French prepared this expedition, the British maintained their blockade, although without their commander. Nelson, in defiance of specific orders from his commanding officer [[George Elphinstone, 1st Viscount Keith|Lord Keith]], had retired to [[Palermo]] on [[Sicily]] to be with [[Emma, Lady Hamilton]], the wife of the British ambassador [[William Hamilton (diplomat)|Sir William Hamilton]] with whom Nelson was conducting an adulterous affair.<ref name=\"NM365\">Mostert, p. 365</ref> In his absence, command had passed to Captain [[Sir Thomas Troubridge, 1st Baronet|Sir Thomas Troubridge]] on [[HMS Culloden (1783)|HMS ''Culloden'']] and then to Captain [[Manley Dixon]] on [[HMS Lion (1777)|HMS ''Lion'']].<ref name=\"WLC420\">Clowes, p. 420</ref>\n\n==Battle==\nAt 23:00 on 30 March, with a strong wind from the south, ''Guillaume Tell'' sailed from Valletta, Decr\u00e9s hoping to use the cover of darkness to escape the British blockade. Dixon had deployed his ships around the island, with Valletta watched by the frigate [[HMS Penelope (1798)|HMS ''Penelope'']] under Captain [[Henry Blackwood]].<ref name=\"RG69\"/> At 23:55, Blackwood's lookouts spotted ''Guillaume Tell'' and the captain gave chase, ordering the [[brig]] [[HMS Minorca (1799)|HMS ''Minorca'']] under Commander [[George Miller (Royal Navy officer)|George Miller]] to convey the message to Dixon, whose ships were just visible in the distance.<ref name=\"WLC421\">Clowes, p. 421</ref> Blackwood also attempted to signal his discovery to his commanding officer as ''Penelope'' gave chase.<ref name=\"WJ3:16\">James, Vol. 3, p. 16</ref>\n\nBlackwood rapidly gained on the ship of the line and by 00:30 the frigate was within range, pulling up under the stern of ''Guillaume Tell'' and beginning a steady fire to which Decr\u00e9s could only respond with his stern-chasers, light cannon situated in the stern of the ship.<ref name=\"WJ3:17\">James, Vol. 3, p. 17</ref> Decr\u00e9s recognised that if he stopped to engage ''Penelope'' then the rest of Berry's squadron, visible on the horizon to the south, would soon overwhelm him. He therefore continued sailing to the northeast, hoping his heavy ship of the line could outrun the light and speedy frigate. However, ''Penelope'' was too fast, and Blackwood handled his ship with considerable skill, managing to pass Decr\u00e9s' stern repeatedly and pour several [[raking fire|raking]] broadsides into the French ship.<ref name=\"RW142\">Woodman, p. 142</ref>\n\nBlackwood's attack was so successful that by dawn on 31 March ''Guillaume Tell'' had lost its main and mizen topmasts and its main yard, considerably reducing the speed at which Decr\u00e9s could travel. The French ship had also suffered heavy casualties in the exchange, but ''Penelope'' had lost only one man killed and three wounded, and was almost undamaged.<ref name=\"WJ3:17\"/> British reinforcements were now arriving from the south: the 64-gun HMS ''Lion'' under Captain Dixon had received ''Minorca''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s warning at 01:00 and immediately sailed in pursuit, sending the brig on to Captain [[Sir Edward Berry]] in [[HMS Foudroyant (1798)|HMS ''Foudroyant'']], who lay some distance to leeward.<ref name=\"WJ3:18\">James, Vol. 3, p. 18</ref> By 05:00, Dixon was close enough to engage, passing between ''Penelope'' and ''Guillaume Tell'' and firing a triple-shotted broadside into the [[port (direction)|port]] side of the French ship. Shooting ahead of the now sluggish ''Guillaume Tell'', ''Lion'' crossed its opponent's bows and shot away the [[jib|jib boom]], allowing Dixon to maintain a position across the bow, raking the French ship from one end while ''Penelope'' did the same to the other.<ref name=\"WLC421\"/> During these manoeuvres, Dixon's ship had briefly become entangled with ''Guillaume Tell''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s rigging, and two determined efforts to board the British ship had been driven off as the ships were disentangled.<ref name=\"NM366\">Mostert, p. 366</ref>\n\nFor half an hour, ''Lion'' continued to fire into the larger ''Guillaume Tell'', but Dixon was unable to keep his ship completely out of range of the French broadsides and by 05:30 the subsequent damage showed an effect, ''Lion'' dropping back and falling behind the French vessel, although remaining within range alongside ''Penelope''.<ref name=\"RW142\"/> At 06:00, ''Guillaume Tell'' came under attack for the third time, when Berry himself caught up with the battling ships in ''Foudroyant'' and pulled along the [[starboard]] broadside of the French ship of the line. Berry hailed Decr\u00e9s to demand his surrender, and accompanied the demand with a triple-shotted broadside, to which Decr\u00e9s responded with fire from his own guns.<ref name=\"RG69\"/> ''Foudroyant'' was flying a full set of sails and therefore suffered severe damage to its rigging in the opening exchange, the additional speed provided by this rig forcing ''Foudroyant'' to move ahead of the French vessel.<ref name=\"WLC421\"/> After working back alongside ''Guillaume Tell'', Berry recommenced fire that rapidly tore away much of the remaining French rigging, allowing ''Lion'' and ''Penelope'' to return to the battle while ''Foudroyant'' dropped back to make urgent repairs.<ref name=\"WJ3:18\">James, Vol. 3, p. 18</ref>\n\nBy 06:30 the badly outnumbered French ship had lost both its main and mizen masts, ''Foudroyant'' returning to the battle in time to collapse the foremast by 08:00. At 08:20, with no means of making sail and with wreckage obscuring most of his gun decks, Decr\u00e9s surrendered to spare any further, fruitless, loss of life.<ref name=\"NM367\">Mostert, p. 367</ref> His ship was in danger: the lack of masts and strong winds caused it to roll so severely that the lower deck gun ports had to be closed to prevent the ship from foundering. Casualties on the French ship numbered more than 200, from a crew of over 900,<ref name=\"WJ3:19\"/> with both Decr\u00e9s and Saulnier badly wounded.<ref name=\"WLC422\">Clowes, p. 422</ref> British losses were lighter, with eight killed and 64 wounded, including Berry, in ''Foudroyant'', eight killed and 38 wounded in ''Lion'' and one killed and three wounded (one fatally) in ''Penelope''. Damage was unevenly spread, ''Foudroyant'' suffering most severely, with the hull and all masts damaged, the mizzenmast so badly that it collapsed at approximately 12:00, wounding five more men. ''Lion'' was badly hit, although not so severely as ''Foudroyant'' while ''Penelope'' was only lightly damaged in the masts and rigging. The battle, which had begun within sight of Malta, had concluded roughly {{convert|21|nmi|km}} south-west of [[Cape Passaro]] on Sicily.<ref name=\"WJ3:18\"/>\n\n==Aftermath==\nBoth ''Foudroyant'' and ''Lion'' were too battered to provide an effective tow to the dismasted French ship, and as a result ''Penelope'' was left to bring the shattered ''Guillaume Tell'' into [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]] on Sicily.<ref name=\"WJ3:19\"/> Eventually the ship was repaired sufficiently for the journey to Britain, and there was added to the Royal Navy under the name HMS ''Malta''. ''Malta'' was, with [[HMS Tonnant (1798)|HMS ''Tonnant'']] captured two years earlier at the Nile, the most powerful [[third rate]] in the British fleet, and served for many years,<ref name=\"RW143\">Woodman, p. 143</ref> participating at the [[Battle of Cape Finisterre (1805)|Battle of Cape Finisterre]] in 1805.\n\nThe British officers were praised for the capture of ''Guillaume Tell'', the last surviving French ship of the line to escape the Battle of the Nile: Nelson, who by his absence had \"missed what would indeed have been the crowning glory to his Mediterranean career\", wrote to Berry that \"Your conduct and character in the late glorious occasion stamps your fame beyond the reach of envy.\"<ref name=\"EB248\">Bradford, p. 248</ref> Despite Nelson's praise however, Berry in particular came in for subsequent criticism, especially from the historian [[William James (naval historian)|William James]], who wrote in his 1827 history of the conflict that:\n\n{{quote|\"Had the Foudroyant, single-handed, met the Guillaume-Tell, the combat would have been between two of the most powerful ships that had ever so met; and, although the Foudroyant's slight inferiority of force, being chiefly in number of men, was not that of which a British captain would complain, still the chances were equal, that the Guillaume-Tell, so gallantly manned, and so ably commanded, came off the conqueror.\"|William James, 1827|<ref name=\"WJ3:19\">James,Vol. 3, p. 19</ref>}}\n\nJames instead attributed most of the praise for the victory to Blackwood and Dixon, whose ships were heavily outmatched by ''Guillaume Tell'', but who successfully pressed their attacks with the intention of delaying the French retreat. He also highly praised Decr\u00e9s for his conduct in the engagement, stating that \"A more heroic defence than that of the Guillaume-Tell is not to be found among the records of naval actions\".<ref name=\"WJ3:19\"/> [[First Consul]] Napoleon Bonaparte reached a similar conclusion, and when Decr\u00e9s was [[prisoner exchange|exchanged]] soon after the battle he was presented with ''armes d'honneur'', later converted to membership of the ''[[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]''. He was also given the position of maritime prefect of the [[Biscay]] port of [[Lorient]].<ref name=\"WLC422\"/>\n\nAboard ''Guillaume Tell'', the British found evidence of the severity of the food shortages in Valletta: \"the only thing found in ''La Guillaume Tell'' was the leg of a [[mule]], hung for safety and his especial use of the admiral's stern-galley\".<ref name=\"RLA69\">Adkins, p. 69</ref> News of the capture of ''Guillaume Tell'' was immediately passed to Vaubois by the British besiegers, along with a demand that he surrender the island. The French general, despite dwindling food supplies, refused, stating ''\"Cette place est en trop bon \u00e9tat, et je suis moi-m\u00eame trop jaloux de bien servir mon pays et de conserver mon honneur, pour \u00e9couter vos propositions.\"'' (\"This place is in too good a situation, and I am too conscious of the service of my country and my honour, to listen to your proposals\"). Despite Vaubois' defiance, the garrison was rapidly starving, and although the French commander resisted until 4 September, he was eventually forced to surrender Valletta and all of its military equipment to the British.<ref name=\"WJ3:20\">James,Vol. 3, p. 20</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book\n | last = Adkins\n | first = Roy & Lesley\n | authorlink =\n | year = 2006\n | chapter =\n | title = The War for All the Oceans\n | publisher = Abacus\n | location =\n | isbn = 0-349-11916-3\n}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Bradford\n | first = Ernle\n | authorlink = Ernle Bradford\n | year = 1999 |origyear=1977\n | chapter =\n | title = Nelson: The Essential Hero\n | publisher = Wordsworth Military Library\n | location =\n | isbn = 1-84022-202-6\n}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Clowes\n | first = William Laird\n | authorlink = William Laird Clowes\n | year = 1997 |origyear=1900\n | chapter =\n | title = The Royal Navy, A History from the Earliest Times to 1900, Volume IV\n | publisher = Chatham Publishing\n | location =\n | isbn = 1-86176-013-2\n}}\n* {{cite book\n | editor =Gardiner, Robert\n | authorlink =\n | year = 2001\n | origyear= 1996\n | chapter =\n | title = Nelson Against Napoleon\n | publisher = Caxton Editions\n | location =\n | isbn = 1-86176-026-4\n}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = James\n | first = William\n | authorlink = William James (naval historian)\n | year = 2002 |origyear=1827\n | chapter =\n | title = The Naval History of Great Britain, Volume 2, 1797\u20131799\n | publisher = Conway Maritime Press\n | location =\n | isbn = 0-85177-906-9\n}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = James\n | first = William\n | authorlink = William James (naval historian)\n | year = 2002 |origyear=1827\n | chapter =\n | title = The Naval History of Great Britain, Volume 3, 1800\u20131805\n | publisher = Conway Maritime Press\n | location =\n | isbn = 0-85177-907-7\n}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Mostert\n | first = Noel\n | authorlink =\n | year = 2007\n | chapter =\n | title = The Line upon a Wind: The Greatest War Fought at Sea Under Sail 1793 \u2013 1815\n | publisher = Vintage Books\n | location =\n | isbn = 978-0-7126-0927-2\n}}\n* {{cite book\n | last = Woodman\n | first = Richard\n | authorlink = Richard Woodman\n | year = 2001\n | chapter =\n | title = The Sea Warriors\n | publisher = Constable Publishers\n | location =\n | isbn = 1-84119-183-3\n}}\n\n{{French occupation of Malta}}\n\n[[Category:Naval battles involving France]]\n[[Category:Naval battles of the French Revolutionary Wars]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1800]]\n[[Category:Naval battles involving Great Britain]]\n", "name_user": "Snagemit", "label": "safe", "comment": "Photo change", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Action_of_31_March_1800"}
{"title_page": "Timothy Leighton", "text_new": "{{short description|Professor of Ultrasonics and Underwater Acoustics}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Timothy Leighton\n| honorific_suffix  = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRS|FREng|FMedSci|size=100%}}\n| birth_name        = Timothy Grant Leighton\n| image             = Professor Timothy Leighton FREng FRS.jpg\n| image_size        = 250x250px\n| alt               =\n| caption           = Timothy Leighton at the [[Royal Society]] admissions day in London, July 2014\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1963|10|16}}<ref name=\"whoswho\">{{Who's Who | surname = Leighton | othernames = Prof. Timothy Grant | id = U257715 | year = 2014 | edition = online [[Oxford University Press]]|doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.257715|author=Anon}}</ref>\n| birth_place       = [[Blackburn]], Lancashire\n| other_names       =\n| residence         =\n| citizenship       =\n| nationality       =\n| fields            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ultrasound|Ultrasonics]]\n* [[Acoustics]]<ref>https://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/about/staff/tgl.page</ref>}}\n| workplaces        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Cavendish Laboratory]]\n* [[University of Cambridge]]\n* [[University of Southampton]]}}\n| patrons           =\n| education         = [[Dallam School|Heversham Grammar School, Cumbria]]\n| alma_mater        = [[University of Cambridge]] (MA, PhD)\n| thesis_title      = Image intensifier studies of sonoluminescence, with application to the safe use of medical ultrasound\n| thesis_url        = http://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?uin=uk.bl.ethos.279713\n| thesis_year       = 1988\n| doctoral_advisor  =\n| academic_advisors =\n| doctoral_students =\n| notable_students  =\n| known_for         =''The Acoustic Bubble''<ref name=abubble>The Acoustic Bubble. By Timothy G. Leighton Academic Press, 1994. 613 pp. {{ISBN|0124124984}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1006/jsvi.1994.1305| title = Review of the {{sic|Acc|oustic|nolink=yes|expected=Acoustic}} Bubble, by T. G. Leighton| journal = Journal of Sound and Vibration| volume = 174| issue = 5| pages = 709\u2013710| year = 1994| last1 = Crum | first1 = L. A. }}</ref>\n| influences        =\n| influenced        =\n| awards  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Rayleigh Medal]] (2014)\n* [[Clifford Paterson Lecture]] (2018)}}\n| website           = {{URL|southampton.ac.uk/engineering/about/staff/tgl.page}}\n| footnotes         =\n| spouse            =\n| children          =\n}}\n'''Timothy Grant Leighton'''  {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRS|FREng|FMedSci}}<ref name=TripleCrown>{{cite web|title=TripleCrown |url=https://www.southampton.ac.uk/news/2018/05/tim-leighton-fellowship.page| year=2019}}</ref><ref name=frs>{{cite web|title=Professor Timothy Leighton FREng FRS |url=https://royalsociety.org/people/timothy-leighton-11808/ |publisher=royalsociety.org |location=London |year=2014 |author=Anon |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306143507/https://royalsociety.org/people/timothy-leighton-11808/ |archivedate=2016-03-06 |url-status=dead }} One or more of the preceding sentences incorporates text from the royalsociety.org website where: {{quote|\"All text published under the heading 'Biography' on Fellow profile pages is available under [[Creative Commons license|Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License]].\" --{{cite web|url=https://royalsociety.org/about-us/terms-conditions-policies/ |title=Royal Society Terms, conditions and policies |accessdate=2016-03-09 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161111170346/https://royalsociety.org/about-us/terms-conditions-policies/ |archivedate=2016-11-11 }}}}</ref><ref name=\"FRS_Uni_soton\">{{cite web |title=FRS award|url= https://www.southampton.ac.uk/news/2017/07/leighton-royal-society-award.page|publisher=University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-09-04}}</ref><ref name=\"List of Fellows\">{{cite web |url=http://www.raeng.org.uk/about-us/people-council-committees/the-fellowship/list-of-fellows |title=List of Fellows |website=raeng.org.uk}}</ref> (born 16 October 1963)<ref name=\"whoswho\"/><ref name=abubble/> is the Professor of [[Ultrasound|Ultrasonics]] and [[Underwater Acoustics]] at the [[University of Southampton]].<ref name=\"what_is_ultrasound\">{{Cite journal| pmid = 17045633| year = 2007| last1 = Leighton| first1 = T. G.| authorlink1 = Timothy Leighton| title = What is ultrasound?| journal = Progress in Biophysics and Molecular Biology| volume = 93| issue = 1\u20133| pages = 3\u201383| doi = 10.1016/j.pbiomolbio.2006.07.026}}</ref><ref name=\"scopus\">{{Scopus id}}</ref><ref name=epmc>{{EuropePMC|ORCID=0000-0002-1649-8750}}</ref><ref name=accoubub>{{YouTube|id=5H4toaWU_IY|title=Professor Tim Leighton, University of Southampton, 'The Acoustic Bubble'}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/1350-4177(95)00021-W| title = Bubble population phenomena in acoustic cavitation| journal = Ultrasonics Sonochemistry| volume = 2| issue = 2| pages = S123\u2013S136| year = 1995| last1 = Leighton | first1 = T. G. }}</ref><ref name=\"radarclutter\"/> He is the inventor-in-chief of [[#Sloan Water Technology Ltd.|Sloan Water Technology Ltd.]],<ref name=\"Sloan Water Technology Ltd. homepage\"/> a company founded around his inventions. \nHe is an academician of three national academies.<ref name=\"TripleCrown\"/> Trained in physics and theoretical physics, he works across physical, medical, biological, social and ocean sciences, fluid dynamics and engineering. He joined the Institute of Sound and Vibration Research (ISVR) at the [[University of Southampton]] in 1992 as a lecturer in underwater acoustics, and completed the monograph ''The Acoustic Bubble''<ref name=abubble/> in the same year. He was awarded a [[Professor|personal chair]] at the age of 35 and has authored over 400 publications.<ref name=\"scopus\" /><ref name=\"soton\"/><ref name=\"University of Southampton\">{{cite web|last1=Published papers|title=ISVR, Ultrasonics, underwater acoustics|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/pubs90.htm|publisher=University of Southampton|accessdate=2014-08-30}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nHe was educated at [[Dallam School|Heversham Grammar School, Cumbria]] and [[Magdalene College, Cambridge]] where he studied the [[Natural Sciences Tripos]] and awarded a [[British undergraduate degree classification|double first class]] Bachelor of Arts degree with honours in [[physics]] and [[theoretical Physics]] in 1985, obtaining a [[PhD]] in 1988 at the [[Cavendish Laboratory]], University of Cambridge.<ref name=\"whoswho\"/><ref name=\"phd\">{{cite thesis |degree=PhD |first=Timothy Grant|last=Leighton |title= Image intensifier studies of sonoluminescence, with application to the safe use of medical ultrasound |publisher=University of Cambridge |year=1988 |id={{EThOS|uk.bl.ethos.279713}}|oclc=60020372|authorlink=Timothy Leighton|url=https://idiscover.lib.cam.ac.uk/primo-explore/fulldisplay?docid=44CAM_ALMA21428173570003606&context=L&vid=44CAM_PROD&search_scope=SCOP_CAM_ALL&tab=cam_lib_coll&lang=en_US|website=lib.cam.ac.uk}}</ref><ref name=\"Ingenia_biography\">{{cite web|title=A talent for bursting bubbles (Ingenia_biography) |url=https://www.ingenia.org.uk/getattachment/Ingenia/Issue-73/Profile/Profile-Timonthy-Leighton-Freng.pdf|accessdate=2018-11-10}}</ref><ref name=\"New_Scientist_biography\">{{cite web|title= New Scientist biography |url= https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg22930662-500-resistance-fighter-takes-the-battle-to-microbes/ |accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref>\nFollowing his PhD, he was awarded senior and advanced [[research fellow]]ships at Magdalene College, Cambridge funded by the [[Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council]] (EPSRC).<ref name=\"University of Southampton career history\">{{cite web|last1=Published papers|title=University of Southampton career history|url=https://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/about/staff/tgl.page#career_history|publisher=University of Southampton|accessdate=2018-10-03}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nHe joined the Institute of Sound and Vibration Research (ISVR) at the [[University of Southampton]] in 1992 as a lecturer in underwater acoustics, and completed the monograph ''The Acoustic Bubble''<ref name=abubble/> in the same year. He was awarded a [[Professor|personal chair]] at the age of 35.\n\n==Research==\n\nHe founded and leads two research organisations he founded ([[#NAMRIP and Global-NAMRIP|Global-NAMRIP]] and [[#Health Effects of Ultrasound in Air|HEFUA]]), is a director and inventor-in-chief of [[#Sloan Water Technology Ltd.|Sloan Water Technology Ltd.]],<ref name=\"Sloan Water Technology Ltd. homepage\"/> and talks extensively to schoolchildren, the public,<ref name=\"multidisciplinary_lecture_1\">{{cite web|title=T.G. Leighton, lecture, multidisciplinary research|url=https://podcasts.ox.ac.uk/bubble-acoustics-listening-ocean-cleaning-medical-devices-and-fighting-antimicrobial-and|accessdate=2018-10-01}}</ref> and on radio and video.<ref name=\"TGL_media_1\">{{cite web|title=T.G.Leighton Outreach|url=http://www.soton.ac.uk/engineering/about/staff/tgl.page#stories_in_the_media|accessdate=2016-08-30}}</ref>\n\nHis research covers medical, humanitarian and environmental sciences, beginning with the fundamental mathematics and ending with engineering applications. His research interests cover [[acoustical oceanography]], [[antimicrobial resistance]],<ref name=\"NAMRIP_index\"/><ref name=\"NAMRIP_Global-NAMRIP\"/> [[medical ultrasonography|biomedical ultrasound]],<ref name=\"WFUMB1998\"/> [[carbon capture and storage]],<ref name=\":0\"/><ref name=\":1\"/><ref name=\"Berges1\"/> [[climate change]],<ref name=\":1\"/><ref name=\"Brooks2009a\"/><ref name=\"Brooks2009b\"/><ref name=\"sparbuoy\"/> [[decontamination]],<ref name=\"IOP2017\"/> [[hospital acquired infections]],<ref name=\"SS2015a\"/> [[marine zoology]],<ref name=\"Solan2016\"/><ref name=Cav&Cet2007>{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G., Finfer, D.C. and White, P.R. |title=Cavitation and cetacean|journal=Revista de Acustica|year=2007|volume=38|pages=37\u201381|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub9767.pdf|doi=}}</ref> [[fluid dynamics]], [[ultrasound]] and [[underwater acoustics]]. \nSuch fields as cold water cleaning,<ref name=\"SS2015a\"/> sound in space,<ref name=\"space_editorial\"/><ref name=\"icarus\"/><ref name=\"Music in Space\"/><ref name=\"planetaria\"/> ultrasound in air,<ref name=HEFUA+PRS16>{{Cite journal|last=Leighton |first=Timothy | authorlink1 = Timothy Leighton|year=2016 |title=Are some people suffering as a result of increasing mass exposure of the public to ultrasound in air? |journal= Proceedings of the Royal Society A |volume=472|issue=2185 |pages= 20150624|doi=10.1098/rspa.2015.0624|pmid=26997897 |pmc=4786042 |bibcode=2016RSPSA.47250624L }}</ref><ref name=HEFUA+PRS17>{{Cite journal|last=Leighton |first=Timothy | authorlink1 = Timothy Leighton|year=2016 |title=Comment on: 'Are some people suffering as a result of increasing mass exposure of the public to ultrasound in air?' |journal= Proceedings of the Royal Society A |volume=473|issue=2199 |pages= 20160828|doi=10.1098/rspa.2016.0828|pmid=28413349 |pmc=5378247 }}</ref> BiaPSS,<ref name=\"dolphins\"/> TWIPR,<ref name=\"radarclutter\"/> and passive acoustic lithortripsy monitoring,<ref name=Coleman92>{{cite journal|last1= Coleman, A.J., Choi, M.J., Saunders, J.E. and Leighton, T.G. |title=  Acoustic emission and sonoluminescence due to cavitation at the beam focus of an electrohydraulic shock wave lithotripter|journal= Ultrasound in Medicine and Biology|year=1992|volume=18|issue=  3|pages= 267\u2013281|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2517.pdf|doi=10.1016/0301-5629(92)90096-s|pmid= 1595133}}</ref><ref name=Coleman93>{{cite journal|last1= Coleman, A.J., Whitlock, M., Leighton, T.G. and Saunders, J.E.|title=The spatial distribution of cavitation induced acoustic emission, sonoluminescence and cell lysis in the field of a shock wave lithotriptor|journal= Physics in Medicine and Biology|year=1993|volume=38|issue=11|pages= 1545\u20131560|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2518.pdf|doi=10.1088/0031-9155/38/11/001|pmid=8272431|bibcode=1993PMB....38.1545C}}</ref><ref name=\"umb2008\"/><ref name=\"umb2008\"/><ref name=\"PRS2012_litho\"/> pushed pioneering research into game-changing technology.<ref name=\"Deep Dive\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.southampton.ac.uk/publicpolicy/what-we-do/with-whom-we-work/current-projects/apocalypse-pessimism.page|title=Deep dive: Should we be more pessimistic about the apocalypse?}}</ref><ref name=\"Evidence to Policy\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.southampton.ac.uk/publicpolicy/what-we-do/blogs/evidence-to-policy-blog/timleighton.page|title=Evidence to Policy: Are you sufficiently worried about superbugs?}}</ref><ref name=\"Conversation2015\"/><ref name=\"NewScientistNAMRIP\"/><ref name=\"Ingenia_biography\"/>  as opposed to incremental research that is published but falls short of societal benefit:\n{{centred pull quote|...We need to work with rigour, imagination, and wonder, unconstrained by the artificial boundaries set in place by discipline names, or the history of projects in which we have previously worked, or the tendency of sponsors to believe they can pick winners, or above all by the belief that we must jump to solutions when we have not yet perceived the real problem. Then, when we eventually do find a solution, we must have the will to push it through all the way to help others, and not simply publish in the expectation that someone will finish the job for us.<ref name=\"soton\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/about/staff/tgl.page#research|title=Professor Timothy Leighton |publisher=University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref>}}\n\nHe worked as part of the team investigating whether man-made sounds can adversely affect benthic species (marine life that inhabits the seabed).<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Solan, M., Hauton, C., Godbold, J.A., Wood, C., Leighton, T.G. and White, P.|title=  Anthropogenic sources of underwater sound can modify how sediment-dwelling invertebrates mediate ecosystems properties|journal=[[Scientific Reports]] |year=2016|volume=6|pages=20540, DOI: 10.1038/srep20540|doi=10.1038/srep20540|pmid=26847483|pmc=4742813|bibcode= 2016NatSR...620540S}}</ref><ref name=\"Benthic_web_2016\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/research/projects/man-made-underwater-sound.page|title=Man-made underwater sound may have wider ecosystem effects than previously thought|publisher=University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref> Such species have been overlooked in studies on how man-made sounds affect whales, dolphins and fish: benthic species find it far harder to relocate away from adverse sounds than do these other more mobile species. Furthermore, benthic species play a key role in the health of the marine sediment, turning it over and preventing it stagnating, and are key to the health of coastal marine environments.<ref name=Solan2016>{{Cite journal|last=Solan|first=Martin|last2=Hauton|first2=Chris|last3=Godbold|first3=Jasmin A.|last4=Wood|first4=Christina L.|last5=Leighton|first5=Timothy G.|last6=White|first6=Paul|date=5 February 2016|title=Anthropogenic sources of underwater sound can modify how sediment-dwelling invertebrates mediate ecosystem properties|journal=Scientific Reports|language=en|volume=6|issue=1|pages=20540|doi=10.1038/srep20540|issn=2045-2322|pmc=4742813|pmid=26847483|bibcode=2016NatSR...620540S}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/research/projects/man-made-underwater-sound.page|title=Man-made underwater sound may have wider ecosystem effects than previously thought {{!}} Engineering and the Environment {{!}} University of Southampton|publisher=University of Southampton|language=en|access-date=2017-04-09}}</ref>\n\nWith other teams he developed methods to assess which fish species are most at-risk from man-made noise in the oceans,<ref name=\"Neenan_AIS_2016\">{{cite book |chapter-url=  http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2016%20-%20Neenan%20et%20al%20(Modeling%20vessel%20noise%20emissions%20-%20AIS)%20POA.pdf|doi= 10.1121/2.0000338|chapter=Modeling vessel noise emissions through the accumulation and propagation of Automatic Identification System data |series=Proceedings of Meetings on Acoustics |pages= 070017|year= 2016|last1= Neenan|first1= Sarah T. V.|last2= White|first2= Paul R.|last3= Leighton|first3= Timothy G.|last4= Shaw|first4= Peter J.|url= https://eprints.soton.ac.uk/415944/1/2.pdf}}</ref> and quantified such noise from shipping.<ref name=\"Li_Hydrofoil_2019\">{{cite journal|last1= Li, J., White, P.R., Roche, B., Davis, J. W. and Leighton, T. G. |title=  Underwater radiated noise from hydrofoils in coastal water|journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America|year=2019 |volume=146  | issue = 5| pages= 3552\u20133561 | doi= 10.1121/1.5134779|pmid= 31795704|bibcode= 2019ASAJ..146.3552L}}</ref> Turning the problem on its head, he worked with other teams on how to use sound as 'underwater acoustic scarecrows' to guide fish away from regions of man-made danger. These might occurs, for example, where industry exacts cooling water from rivers used as migration paths of endangered species (the young of European eel are slim enough for the flow to pull them through grills placed over such extraction points).<ref name=\"Deleau_Fish_Manag_2019\">{{cite journal|last1=   Deleau, M. J. C., White, P. R., Peirson, G. Leighton, T. G. and Kemp, P. S. (2019)|title=  Use of acoustics to enhance the efficiency of physical screens designed to protect downstream moving European eel (Anguilla anguilla)|journal= Fisheries Management and Ecology|volume= 27|year=2019 | pages=1\u20139| doi= 10.1111/fme.12362|url=  http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2019_Deleau-et-al-2019.pdf }}</ref><ref name=\"Piper_2019\">{{cite journal|last1= Piper, A.T., White, P.R., Wright, R.M., Leighton, T. G., and Kemp, P.S. |title=  Response of seaward-migrating European eel (Anguilla anguilla) to an infrasound deterrent|journal= Ecological Engineering|year=2019 |volume=127 | pages= 480\u2013486| doi= 10.1016/j.ecoleng.2018.12.001|url=  http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2019_Piper-White-Wright-Leighton-Kemp(Response_of_eel_to_infrasound)Ecological_Engineering.pdf}}</ref>  (key collaborator: Paul White<ref name=\"southampton.ac.uk\"/>)\n\n===NAMRIP and Global-NAMRIP===\nThe Global Network for AntiMicrobial Resistance and Infection Prevention (Global-NAMRIP),<ref name=\"NAMRIP_index\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/index.page?|title=NAMRIP homepage|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref> is a multidisciplinary research team of hundreds researchers and end users, across four continents, including engineers, chemists, microbiologists, environmental scientists, veterinary and human medics, clinicians who contribute to international and national antibiotic guidelines for specified conditions, experts in food, ethics and law, crucially networked with economists, geographers, health scientists and experts from other social science disciplines to provide a truly joined up approach to antimicrobial resistance (AMR) and infection prevention (offsetting the loss of diversity in pharmaceutical industry research teams). As Leighton said at NAMRIP's 2016 conference:\n \n{{centred pull quote|...Unless preventative measures are found (and no-one in the world currently knows what those will be), AMR will (through the colloquial 'rise of superbugs') by 2050 be killing more people than cancer, and cost the world economy more than the current size of the global economy. We will not be able to feed the world unless we wean our food production industry off its dependence on antibiotics; common medical procedures (minor surgery, childbirth) will become significantly more hazardous; and advances in treatments (such as those for childhood leukaemia) will become reversed.}}\n\nGlobal-NAMRIP was set up to search for such solutions and mitigations, with particular emphasis to finding alternatives to the oft-cited route of simply funding drug companies to produce more antibiotics. According to the New Scientist,:<ref name=\"NewScientistNAMRIP\"/>\n{{centred pull quote|...I looked at all this and realised that even if there was a billion-dollar fund for new antibiotics, it would not sort out the problem; it might just buy us an extra decade. We need a new approach \u2013 a step change like the one antibiotics gave us when they first came in.<ref name=\"NewScientistNAMRIP\"/>}}\n\n{{centred pull quote|...In many parts of the world, climate change and flooding, war, corruption, politics, received wisdom, traditions and religious practices, and the supply of fuel and money, play a far greater role in food, water, waste treatment, healthcare and the transport of microbes from one host to another, than do the outputs of the drug companies. The twin potential catastrophes are global, and so are the causes. The solutions lie with scientists and engineers to develop new technologies and embed new practices in the public and workforce; they lie with farmers, plumbers, office workers, water and sewage workers, medical practitioners, food retailers, innovators in business \u2026 indeed most of us. And they lie with those who are responsible for shaping behaviour across the world \u2013 not just the pharmaceutical companies.<ref name=Conversation2015>{{Cite journal|last=Leighton |first=Timothy | authorlink1 = Timothy Leighton|year=2015 |title=We need more than just new antibiotics to fight superbugs |journal= The Conversation |issue=15 July 2015 | url = https://theconversation.com/we-need-more-than-just-new-antibiotics-to-fight-superbugs-44054}}</ref>}}\n\nGlobal-NAMRIP creates new research teams,<ref name=\"NAMRIP_news\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/news/latest.page?|title=NAMRIP news|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref> commissions new research,<ref name=\"NAMRIP_research\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/research/index.page?|title=NAMRIP research|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref> engaging with industry<ref name=\"NAMRIP_industry\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/industry/index.page?|title=NAMRIP industry|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref> to roll out solutions to society, and engaging with the public and policymakers to conduct outreach, education and dialogue.<ref name=\"NAMRIP_outreach\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/publicengagment/index.page?|title=NAMRIP outreach|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref> The award-winning Public Engagement<ref name=\"NAMRIP_outreach\"/> and Policymaker Engagement<ref name=\"NAMRIP_Policymaker_outreach\">{{cite web|url= https://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/publicpolicy/index.page |title=NAMRIP Policymaker Engagement Programme|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2018-11-11}}</ref> programmes that Leighton devised and leads have been mentioned in Parliament by the Under-Secretary of State for Health on 16 November 2017.<ref name=\"Brine_Nov17\">{{cite web|url= https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2017-11-16/debates/141BEBCB-C1F8-4BA7-ABF5-9186CAAC49F9/WorldAntibioticsAwarenessWeek|title= House of Commons Hansard (16 Nov 2017 Volume 631, 2.31 pm) |publisher=House of Commons, UK |accessdate=2017-11-16}}</ref><ref name=\"Brine_TV_Nov17\">{{cite web|url= https://parliamentlive.tv/event/index/0dbfadce-2829-4ed1-b45a-82bb41c4ed70?in=14:34:58&out=14:35:56|title= Parliament Live TV (16 Nov 2017) |publisher=House of Commons, UK |accessdate=2017-11-16}}</ref> and Leighton has addressed the Parliamentary and Scientific Committee on his approach to addressing the threat of AMR.<ref name=\"POST2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/news/2018/06/parliamentary-committee.page|title=Prof Leighton addresses Parliamentary and Scientific Committee|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2018-11-10}}</ref><ref name=POST_Journal2018>{{Cite journal|last=Leighton |first=Timothy | authorlink1 = Timothy Leighton|year=2018 |title= Can we end the threat of Anti-Microbial Resistance once and for all? |journal= Science in Parliament |volume=74 |issue=3 |pages= 29\u201332 }}</ref>\n\nGlobal-NAMRIP particularly supports Low/Middle Income Countries with not-for-profit interventions,<ref name=\"NAMRIP_Global-NAMRIP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/about/globalnamrip.page|title=Global-NAMRIP|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref> for example with initiatives in urban<ref name=\"NAMRIP2018_Accra\">{{cite web|url=https://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/news/2018/03/ghana-workshop.page|title=Global-NAMRIP 2018 conference|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2018-11-10}}</ref> and rural Ghana (infection being the primary cause of death in rural Ghana).<ref name=\"Navrongo2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/news/2018/03/navrongo-starhealer2018.page|title=Africa's first StarStream heads to Navrongo in northern Ghana|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2018-11-10}}</ref> In Uganda in 2019, Global-NAMRIP members from Uganda, Liberia, Malawi, Kenya, Ghana, Ethiopia and the UK met to compare, for the first time, the national AMR strategies of their respective countries, to share best practice. The meeting also produced significant impact in education, support for young innovators, and responded to a request from the Ugandan Minister for Health to write for him the 'Kampala Declaration on AMR'.<ref name=\"Uganda2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/news/2019/03/global-namrip-conf.page?|title=Successful Global-NAMRIP conference in Uganda|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2019-04-14}}</ref>\n\n===Health Effects of Ultrasound in Air===\nHealth Effects of Ultrasound in Air (HEFUA)<ref name=\"HEFUA_USRG\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/populationhealth/partners/HEFUA.page|title=HEFUA, Population Health, University of Southampton|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref><ref name=\"HEFUA_project\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/research/projects/are-some-people-suffering.page|title=Ultrasound in Air, University of Southampton|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref><ref name=hefua>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/site/hefua2|title=HEFUA-2|website=sites.google.com}}</ref> was founded to map the increasing use of ultrasound in public places, and to investigate whether or not this increase is having adverse effects on some humans (following an investigation which revealed that the use of ultrasound in public places is increasing, and that guidelines were inadequate prior to the 2016 report).\n\nThe 2016 report<ref name=\"HEFUA+PRS16\"/> that first raised the issues was, in the first 2 years, downloaded over 20,000 times from the Royal Society website, leading to requests for a follow-up,<ref name=\"HEFUA+PRS17\"/> a journal special issue,<ref name=\"JASA2018_Table_of_Contents\">{{cite web|title=JASA 2018 Ultrasound in Air Special Issue |url=https://asa.scitation.org/toc/jas/144/4?tocSection=SPECIAL+ISSUE+ON+ULTRASOUND+IN+AIR&expanded=144|accessdate=2018-11-10}}</ref><ref name=\"JASA2018_Editorial\"/><ref name=\"JASA2018_Effects_on_Humans_Part_1\">{{Cite journal|last1= Fletcher, M.D., Lloyd Jones, S.D., White, P.R., Dolder, C.N., Leighton, T.G. and Lineton, B.| title= Effects of very high-frequency sound and ultrasound on humans. Part I: Adverse symptoms after exposure to audible very-high frequency sound |journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America |year=2018|volume=144|issue=4|pages=2511\u20132520 |doi=10.1121/1.5063819 | pmid= 30404512 | url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2018_Fletcher_et_al_(Effects_of_VHFS+US_on_humans_Part1_Audible)_JASA_144(4)2511_1.pdf| bibcode= 2018ASAJ..144.2511F }}</ref><ref name=\"JASA2018_Effects_on_Humans_Part_2\">{{Cite journal|last1= Fletcher, M.D., Lloyd Jones, S.D., White, P.R., Dolder, C.N., Leighton, T.G. and Lineton, B.| title= Effects of very high-frequency sound and ultrasound on humans. Part II: A double-blind randomized provocation study of inaudible 20-kHz ultrasound |journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America | year=2018|volume=144|issue=4|pages=2521\u20132531 |doi=10.1121/1.5063818| pmid= 30404504 |url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2018_Fletcher_et_al_(JASA)_Effects_of_VHF+US_on_humans_Part2_Inaudible_Ultrasound.pdf| bibcode= 2018ASAJ..144.2521F }}</ref><ref name=\"JASA2018_Public_Exposure_Field_Measurements\">{{Cite journal|last1= Fletcher, M.D., Lloyd Jones, S.D., White, P.R., Dolder, C.N., Lineton, B. and Leighton, T.G.| title= Public exposure to ultrasound and very high-frequency sound in air |journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America | year=2018| volume=144|issue=4|pages=2554\u20132564 |doi=10.1121/1.5063817 | pmid= 30404460 | url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2018_%20Fletcher_et_al_(Public_exposure_to_ultrasound)_JASA_144(4)2554_1.pdf| bibcode= 2018ASAJ..144.2554F }}</ref><ref name=\"JASA2018_Deterrents+Hairdryer\">{{Cite journal|last1= Dolder, C.N., Fletcher, M.D., Lloyd Jones, S., Lineton, B., Dennison, S.R., Symmonds, M., White, P.R. and Leighton, T.G.| title= Measurements of ultrasonic deterrents and an acoustically branded hairdryer: Ambiguities in guideline compliance |journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America |year=2018| volume=144|issue=4|pages=2565\u20132574 |doi=10.1121/1.5064279  | pmid= 30404457 | url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2018_Dolder_et_al_(Measurements_of_deterrents%20+hairdrier)_JASA_144(4)2565_1.pdf | bibcode= 2018ASAJ..144.2565D }}</ref><ref name=\"JASA2018_Duck+Leighton\">{{Cite journal|last1= Duck, F. and Leighton, T.G.| title= Frequency bands for ultrasound, suitable for the consideration of its health effects |journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America| year=2018| volume=144|issue=4|pages=2490\u20132500 |doi=10.1121/1.5063987 | pmid= 30404517 |url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2018_Duck_and_Leighton_(Frequency_bands_for_ultrasound)_JASA_144(4)2490_1.pdf}}</ref> and numerous conference sessions worldwide as the importance of this topic was realised.<ref name=\"Aachen_2019_Leighton\">{{Cite journal|last1= Leighton, T. G.| title= Ultrasound-in-Air: New applications need improved measurement methods and procedures, and appreciation of any adverse effects on humans|series= Proceedings of the 23rd International Congress on Acoustics (9 to 13 September 2019, Aachen, Germany)|year=2019|volume=paper 000434| pages=6363\u20136367 |url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2019-Leighton-ICA-Aachen(Human-effects-ultrasound-in-air).pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"Aachen_2019_Dolder+Leighton\">{{Cite journal|last1= Dolder, C.N., Fletcher, M.D., Lloyd Jones, S., Lineton, B., and Leighton, T. G.| title=  Exposure levels for parametric arrays in light of guideline ambiguities|series= Proceedings of the 23rd International Congress on Acoustics (9 to 13 September 2019, Aachen, Germany)|year=2019|volume=paper 000724| pages=6394\u20136397|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2019-ICA-Aachen-Dolder-Leighton-ultrasound-in-air-000472.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"ASA2018_Minneaspolic+streaming\">{{cite web|title=Minneapolis 2018 Acoustical Society of America streamed sessions |url= https://acousticalsociety.org/minneapolis-meeting-streamed-sessions/|accessdate=2018-12-12}}</ref> Scientists, engineers and the public around the world are now logging the location and type of device that emits ultrasound.<ref name=\"Martin_HEFUA_Japan_MAP\">{{Cite web|last1= Martin, H.| title=  Open map of ultrasonic sources in air in Japan|website= Google maps|year=2019|url= https://www.google.com/maps/d/u/0/edit?mid=1kzKTd4LtuiczGnCZ029k8KSjJonWY8Rd&ll=35.696377281403514%2C139.70292565&z=13}}</ref><ref name=\"JASA2018_Public_Exposure_Field_Measurements\"/> Leighton became an acknowledged world expert<ref name=\"Chan_NYT\">{{cite web|url= https://twitter.com/melissakchan/status/1009081601509281792|title=M. Chan (New York Times)|publisher=Twitter |accessdate=2018-06-19}}</ref> on such public exposures, and on the claims of 'sonic attacks' on US Embassy staff in Cuba and China.<ref name=\"JASA2018_Editorial\">{{Cite journal|last=Leighton|first=T. G.| title= Ultrasound in air\u2014Guidelines, applications, public exposures, and claims of attacks in Cuba and China |journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America | year=2018|volume=144|issue=4|pages=2473\u20132489 |doi=10.1121/1.5063351 |pmid=30404502|bibcode=2018ASAJ..144.2473L|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\"Asia+Pacific_blog_2018\">{{Cite journal|last=Leighton|first=T. G.|date=19 June 2018|title=Hearing things? A process of elimination casts doubt on reports of 'sonic attacks' in Cuba and China|url=https://www.policyforum.net/hearing-things/|journal=Asia & the Pacific Policy Society}}</ref><ref name=\"TheNewsLens_2018\">{{Cite journal|last=Leighton|first=T. G.|date=22 June 2018|title=Talk of 'Sonic Attacks' at US Embassies Rings Hollow|url=https://international.thenewslens.com/article/98394}}</ref><ref name=\"ScienceNews\">{{Cite journal|last=Saey|first=T.|date=1 June 2018|title=Here's why scientists are questioning whether 'sonic attacks' are real|url=https://www.sciencenews.org/article/scientists-are-questioning-whether-sonic-attacks-are-real}}</ref><ref name=\"NewYorkTimes_2018\">{{Cite journal| last1 = Kessel| first1 = J. M.| last2 = Chan | first2 = M.| last3 = Woo | first3 = J.|date=May 2018|title=How an Alleged Sonic Attack Shaped U.S. Policy on Cuba (Leighton interview is from 4.15-4.40 and 5.15-5.40 )|url=https://www.nytimes.com/video/world/americas/100000005848783/how-an-alleged-sonic-attack-shaped-us-policy-on-cuba.html?smid=pl-share}}</ref><ref name=\"Voice_of_America_2018\">{{Cite journal| last=Voice of America |date=May 2018|title=International Edition 2330 EDT (Leighton interview is from 12.24 until 17.25)|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/4392555.html}}</ref> His expertise on the effect on humans of ultrasound in air provided the scientific basis that was cited by Giles Watling MP (Clacton, Conservative) in the Motion for leave to bring in a Bill (Standing Order No. 23) on \"Anti-loitering Devices (Regulation)\" (17 July 2018 Volume 645, 2.06 pm).<ref name=\"Watling_July18\">{{cite web|url= https://parliamentlive.tv/event/index/09a35fb7-1fba-4eca-bfc8-1f6aa1067970?in=14:06:23|title= Parliament live TV (17 July 2018 Volume 645, 2.06 pm - Leighton's work mentioned 14:10:47) |publisher=House of Commons, UK |accessdate=2018-07-17}}</ref><ref name=\"Watling_Hansard_July18\">{{cite web|url= https://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2018-07-17/debates/6CFBF631-E484-4605-B6C8-6F54F47FDA92/Anti-LoiteringDevices(Regulation)|title= House of Commons Hansard (17 July 2018 Volume 645) |publisher=House of Commons, UK |accessdate=2018-07-17}}</ref>\n\n===Extraterrestrial acoustics===\n* Predicting the soundscapes of other worlds<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G. and White, P.R.|title=The Sound of Titan: A role for acoustics in space exploration|journal=Acoustics Bulletin|year=2004|volume=29|issue=4|pages=16\u201323}}</ref><ref name=\"Music in Space\">{{cite journal|last1=Leighton|first1=Timothy G.|last2=Petculescu|first2=Andi|title=The Sound of Music and Voices in Space Part 1: Theory|journal=Acoustics Today|volume=5|issue=3|year=2009|pages=17\u201326|issn=1557-0215|doi=10.1121/1.3238123}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite journal|last1=Leighton|first1=Timothy G.|last2=Petculescu|first2=Andi|title=The Sound of Music and Voices in Space Part 2: Modeling and Simulation|journal=Acoustics Today|volume=5|issue=3|year=2009|pages=27\u201329|issn=1557-0215|doi=10.1121/1.3238123}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G., White, P.R. and Finfer, D.C.|title=The opportunities and challenges in the use of extra-terrestrial acoustics in the exploration of the oceans of icy planetary bodies|journal=Earth, Moon, and Planets|year=2012|volume=109|issue=1\u20134|pages=99\u2013116|doi=10.1007/s11038-012-9399-6|bibcode=2012EM&P..109...91L}}</ref> and how these could best be exploited using acoustic devices, led to devices for planetaria to use when teaching about other worlds,<ref name=\"Music in Space\"/><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=planetaria>{{Cite journal|last=Leighton|first=T|last2=Banda|first2=N|last3=Berges|first3=B|last4=Joseph|first4=P|last5=White|first5=P|date=1 August 2016|title=Extraterrestrial sound for planetaria: A pedagogical study|journal=The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America|volume=140|issue=2|pages=1469\u20131480|doi=10.1121/1.4960785|pmid=27586771|issn=0001-4966|bibcode=2016ASAJ..140.1469L|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=space_editorial>{{Cite journal|last=Leighton|first=T|last2=Petculescu|first2=A|date=1 August 2016|title=Guest editorial: Acoustic and related waves in extraterrestrial environments|journal=The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America|volume=140|issue=2|pages=1397\u20131399|doi=10.1121/1.4961539|pmid=27586765|issn=0001-4966|bibcode=2016ASAJ..140.1397L|doi-access=free}}</ref> and showed how careful calculation was needed to avoid mistakes when using acoustic sensors on other worlds.<ref name=icarus>{{cite journal |last1=Leighton, T.G., Finfer, D.C. and White, P.R. |title=The problems with acoustics on a small planet |journal=Icarus|year=2008 |volume=193 |issue=2 |pages=649\u2013652 |doi= 10.1016/j.icarus.2007.10.008 |bibcode=2008Icar..193..649L }}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite journal| pmid = 21877784| year = 2011| last1 = Jiang | first1 = J| title = Acoustic attenuation, phase and group velocities in liquid-filled pipes II: Simulation for Spallation Neutron Sources and planetary exploration| journal = The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America| volume = 130| issue = 2| pages = 695\u2013706| last2 = Baik | first2 = K| last3 = Leighton | first3 = T.G.| doi = 10.1121/1.3598463| bibcode = 2011ASAJ..130..695J| url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/a915a5e41c92ae1f740d85154f832eddb40ca16c}}</ref><ref name=\"Fluid_loading\">{{Cite journal |doi= 10.1121/1.3104628 |pmid=19425625 |title= Fluid loading effects for acoustical sensors in the atmospheres of Mars, Venus, Titan, and Jupiter| journal = The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America| volume = 125| issue=5 |pages= EL214\u20139 |year=2009 |last1= Leighton |first1=T.G.|bibcode=2009ASAJ..125L.214L |doi-access= free }}</ref><ref name=nearesonant>{{Cite journal| pmid = 19894796| year = 2009| last1 = Ainslie | first1 = M. A.| title = Near resonant bubble acoustic cross-section corrections, including examples from oceanography, volcanology, and biomedical ultrasound| journal = The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America| volume = 126| issue = 5| pages = 2163\u201375| last2 = Leighton| first2 = T. G.| doi = 10.1121/1.3180130| bibcode = 2009ASAJ..126.2163A}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Ainslie | first1 = M. A. | last2 = Leighton | first2 = T. G. | year = 2016 | title = Sonar equations for planetary exploration | url = | journal = The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America | volume = 140 | issue = 2| pages = 1400\u20131419 | doi=10.1121/1.4960786| pmid = 27586766 | bibcode = 2016ASAJ..140.1400A | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n\n===Marine mammal acoustics===\nLeighton's explanation of how humpback whales use sound when feeding in bubble nets is now a staple explanation on whale tour boats.<ref name=\"eprints.soton.ac.uk\"/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G., Finfer, D., Grover, E. and White, P.R.|title=An acoustical hypothesis for the spiral bubble nets of humpback whales and the implications for whale feeding|journal=Acoustics Bulletin|year=2007|volume=22|issue=1|pages=17\u201321}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G., Richards, S.D. and White, P.R.|title=Trapped within a 'wall of sound': A possible mechanism for the bubble nets of the humpback whales|journal=Acoustics Bulletin|year=2004|volume=29|issue=1|pages=24\u201329}}</ref><ref name=\"Qing_JASA2019\">{{cite journal|last1= Qing, X., White, P. R., Leighton, T. G., Liu, S., Qiao, G. and Zhang, Y. |title=  Three-dimensional finite element simulation of acoustic propagation in spiral bubble net of humpback whale|journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America|year=2019|volume=146  |issue=3| pages= 1982\u20131995 | url=  http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2019-Qing-White-Leighton(Spiral-nets)JASAvol_146iss_31982_1.pdf|doi= 10.1121/1.5126003|pmid= 31590519|bibcode= 2019ASAJ..146.1982Q}}</ref> He explained how dolphins can echolocate while producing bubble nets to hunt, a process that should blind their sonar.<ref name=radarclutter/><ref name=\"ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\"/><ref name=\"eprints.soton.ac.uk\"/>\n\n==Inventions==\n===Medical and healthcare===\nLeighton invented systems for: \n* detecting bone disease (including osteoporosis).<ref name=\"Leighton_osteoporosis\">{{cite web|title=Osteoporosis breakthrough|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Leighton_osteoporosis.pdf|accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid10414898|noedit\">{{Cite journal | pmid = 10414898| year = 1999| last1 = Hughes| first1 = E. R.| title = Ultrasonic propagation in cancellous bone: A new stratified model| journal = Ultrasound in Medicine and Biology| volume = 25| issue = 5| pages = 811\u201321| last2 = Leighton| first2 = T. G.| last3 = Petley| first3 = G. W.| last4 = White| first4 = P. R.|doi=10.1016/s0301-5629(99)00034-4}}</ref><ref name=\"Hughes_et_al_2017\">{{Cite journal | pmid = 17297810| year = 2007| last1 = Hughes| first1 = E. R.| title = Investigation of an anisotropic tortuosity in a biot model of ultrasonic propagation in cancellous bone| journal = The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America| volume = 121| issue = 1| pages = 568\u201374| last2 = Leighton| first2 = T. G.| last3 = White| first3 = P. R.| last4 = Petley| first4 = G. W. | doi=10.1121/1.2387132| bibcode = 2007ASAJ..121..568H}}</ref><ref name=\"Lee_etal2007\">{{Cite journal| pmid = 17183128| year = 2007| last1 = Lee| first1 = K. I.| title = Empirical angle-dependent Biot and MBA models for acoustic anisotropy in cancellous bone| journal = Physics in Medicine and Biology| volume = 52| issue = 1| pages = 59\u201373| last2 = Hughes| first2 = E. R.| last3 = Humphrey| first3 = V. F.| last4 = Leighton| first4 = T. G.| last5 = Choi| first5 = M. J.| doi = 10.1088/0031-9155/52/1/005| bibcode = 2007PMB....52...59L}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid12788218|noedit\">{{Cite journal | pmid = 12788218| year = 2003| last1 = Hughes| first1 = E. R.| title = Estimation of critical and viscous frequencies for Biot theory in cancellous bone| journal = Ultrasonics| volume = 41| issue = 5| pages = 365\u20138| last2 = Leighton| first2 = T. G.| last3 = Petley| first3 = G. W.| last4 = White| first4 = P. R.| last5 = Chivers| first5 = R. C.| doi=10.1016/s0041-624x(03)00107-0| citeseerx = 10.1.1.621.4532}}</ref><ref name=\"Osteo_EPSRC\">{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G, Petley, G.W., White, P.R. and Hughes, E.R.|title=A sound diagnosis|journal=EPSRC Newsline|year=2002|volume=21|pages=18\u201319|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2896.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"Hughes_etalAcBull\">{{cite journal|last1=Hughes, E.R., Leighton, T.G., Petley, G.W. and White, P.R. |title=Ultrasonic assessment of bone health|journal=Acoustics Bulletin|ye