, D.G. and Sharpe, D.A.|title=Comparison of the abilities of eight acoustic techniques to detect and size a single bubble |journal=Ultrasonics |year=1996 |volume=34 |issue=6 |pages=661\u2013667 |doi= 10.1016/0041-624X(96)00053-4 |url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2525.pdf}}</ref><ref name=jasa1997>{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G., Ramble, D.G. and Phelps, A.D |title=The detection of tethered and rising bubbles using multiple acoustic techniques |journal=Journal of the Acoustical Society of America |year=1997 |volume=101|issue=5 |pages=2626\u20132635|doi= 10.1121/1.418503 |url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2530.pdf|bibcode=1997ASAJ..101.2626L }}</ref> that he identified as due to surface waves on the walls of gas bubbles in liquids.<ref name=jasa1996>{{cite journal|last1=Phelps, A.D. and Leighton, T.G.|title=High-resolution bubble sizing through detection of the subharmonic response with a two frequency excitation technique |journal=Journal of the Acoustical Society of America |year=1996 |volume=99 |issue=4 |pages=1985\u20131992 |url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2524.pdf|doi=10.1121/1.415385 |bibcode=1996ASAJ...99.1985P }}</ref><ref name= Acustica_1997>{{cite journal|last1= Phelps, A.D. and Leighton, T.G. |title=The subharmonic oscillations and combination-frequency emissions from a resonant bubble: their properties and generation mechanisms |journal= Acta Acustica |year=1997 |volume=83 |pages=59\u201366 |url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2526.pdf}}</ref><ref name= Acustica_1998>{{cite journal|last1= Ramble D.G., Phelps, A.D. and Leighton, T.G. |title=On the relation between surface waves on a bubble and the subharmonic combination-frequency emission|journal= Acustica with Acta Acustica |year=1998 |volume=84 |issue=5 |pages=986\u2013988|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub185.pdf \n}}</ref> Multidisciplinary research in the following ten parallel streams of work turned this discovery into Sloan Water Technology Ltd:\n# Theory of how to stimulate these surface waves;<ref name= Makasimov+Leighton_2001>{{cite journal|last1= Maksimov, A.O. and Leighton, T.G. |title=Transient processes near the threshold of acoustically driven bubble shape oscillations |journal= Acta Acustica |year=2001 |volume=87 |issue=3 |pages=322\u2013332 |url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub1295.pdf}}</ref><ref name= Makasimov+Leighton_2012>{{cite journal|last1= Maksimov, A.O. and Leighton, T.G. |title=Pattern formation on the surface of a bubble driven by an acoustic field |journal= Proceedings of the Royal Society A |year=2012 |volume=468 |issue=2137 | pages=57\u201375 |doi=10.1098/rspa.2011.0366|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2012%20Maksimov%20and%20Leighton%20(PRS)%20Pattern%20formation.pdf|bibcode=2012RSPSA.468...57M }}</ref>\n# measurement of the liquid convection and shear they generate;<ref name=\"eprints.soton.ac.uk\"/><ref name=abubble/><ref name=what_is_ultrasound/><ref name=POMA_2016/><ref name=IOP2017/> theory on how sound causes the bubbles to generate cracks;<ref name=abubble/><ref name=\"Primary_Bjerknes_1990\">{{cite journal|last1= Leighton, T.G., Walton, A.J. and Pickworth, M.J.W. |title=Primary Bjerknes forces|journal= European Journal of Physics |year=1990|volume=11|issue=1|pages=47\u201350|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2513.pdf |doi=10.1088/0143-0807/11/1/009|bibcode=1990EJPh...11...47L}}</ref><ref name=\"Makasimov+Leighton_2018\">{{cite journal|last1= Maksimov, A.O. and Leighton, T.G. |title= Acoustic radiation force on a parametrically distorted bubble |journal= J. Acoust. Soc. Am.|year=2018 |volume=143 |issue= 1 |pages=296\u2013305 |doi= 10.1121/1.5020786|pmid= 29390754 |bibcode= 2018ASAJ..143..296M |url= https://eprints.soton.ac.uk/416536/1/JASA_02137_R1_accepted_version_.pdf }}</ref> \n# theory for acoustics in porous materials (leading to the first theory to show why passing ultrasound through different directions in the human ankle could monitor osteoporosis);<ref name=\"Leighton_osteoporosis\"/><ref name=\"Osteo_EPSRC\"/><ref name=\"Hughes_etalAcBull\"/><ref name=\"pmid10414898|noedit\"/><ref name=\"pmid12788218|noedit\"/><ref name=\"Hughes_et_al_2017\"/><ref name=\"Lee_etal2007\"/> \n# the world's first measurements of the bubble size distribution for industry and in the ocean surf zone,<ref name=JASA_1997_surf>{{cite journal|last1= Phelps, A.D., Ramble, D.G. and Leighton, T.G.  |title=The use of a combination frequency technique to measure the surf zone bubble population|journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America  |year=1997 |volume=101 |issue=4 |pages=1981\u20131989 |doi= 10.1121/1.418199 |url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2529.pdf|bibcode=1997ASAJ..101.1981P}}</ref><ref name= IEEE_1998>{{cite journal|last1= Phelps, A.D. and Leighton, T.G. |title=Oceanic bubble population measurements using a buoy-deployed combination frequency technique|journal= IEEE Journal of Oceanic Engineering |year=1998 |volume=23 |issue=4 |pages=400\u2013410|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub183.pdf|doi=10.1109/48.725234|bibcode=1998IJOE...23..400P}}</ref> leading to ocean measurements necessary to predict the climatological significance of the transfer of carbon dioxide between atmosphere and ocean.<ref name= CO2_Nature_2018/> It also provided techniques for measurement in industrial pipelines<ref name= Leighton_Pipe_1998>{{cite journal|last1= Leighton, T.G., Ramble, D.G., Phelps, A.D., Morfey, C.L. and Harris, P.P.|title=Acoustic detection of gas bubbles in a pipe|journal= Acustica with Acta Acustica |year=1998 |volume=84 |issue=5 |pages=801\u2013814|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub184.pdf}}</ref><ref name= JASA_2002_reverb>{{cite journal|last1= Leighton, T.G., White, P.R., Morfey, C.L., Clarke, J.W.L., Heald, G.J., Dumbrell, H.A. and Holland, K.R. |title=The effect of reverberation on the damping of bubbles |journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America  |year=2002 |volume=112 |issue=4 |pages=1366\u20131376 |url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub1612.pdf|doi=10.1121/1.1501895 |pmid=12398444 |bibcode=2002ASAJ..112.1366L }}</ref> which led to sensors for the oil and gas,<ref name=\":0\"/> carbon capture and storage,<ref name=\":0\"/><ref name=\":1\"/><ref name=\"Berges1\"/> ceramics<ref name=\"Yim+Leighton\">{{cite journal|last1= Yim, G.-T. and Leighton, T.G. |title= Real-time on-line monitoring of ceramic \"slip\" in pottery pipe-lines using ultrasound |journal= Ultrasonics |year=2010 |volume=50 |issue=1 |pages=60\u201367|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub11434.pdf|doi= 10.1016/j.ultras.2009.07.008 |pmid= 19709710 }}</ref> and nuclear<ref name=\"inversion\"/><ref name=\"Baik2014\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> industries.\n# measurement of the liquid convection and shear from these surface waves;<ref name=\"eprints.soton.ac.uk\"/><ref name=abubble/><ref name=what_is_ultrasound/><ref name=POMA_2016/><ref name=IOP2017/> theory on how sound causes the bubbles to generate cracks;<ref name=abubble/><ref name=\"Primary_Bjerknes_1990\"/><ref name=\"Makasimov+Leighton_2018\"/>\n# acoustic losses in water surrounded on all sides by air and containing microscopic natural particles;<ref name=\"Richards+Leighton_PRS2003\">{{cite journal|last1=   Richards, S.D., Leighton, T.G. and Brown, N.R. |title= Visco-inertial absorption in dilute suspensions of irregular particles|journal= Proceedings of the Royal Society A|year=2003 |volume=459  |issue= 2038|pages= 2153\u20132167|url=  http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2003%20Richards%20Leighton%20Brown%20(PRS)%20Visco-inertial%20absorption.pdf|doi= 10.1098/rspa.2003.1126|bibcode= 2003RSPSA.459.2153R}}</ref><ref name=\"Richards+Leighton_JASA2003\">{{cite journal|last1=   Richards, S.D., Leighton, T.G. and Brown, N.R. |title=  Sound absorption by suspensions of nonspherical particles: Measurements compared with predictions using various particle sizing techniques|journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America|year=2003 |volume=114  |issue= 4|pages= 1841\u20131850|url=  http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2538.pdf|doi= 10.1121/1.1610449|pmid= 14587585|bibcode= 2003ASAJ..114.1841R}}</ref><ref name=\"Brown+Leighton_JASA1998\">{{cite journal|last1=   Brown, N.R., Leighton, T.G., Richards, S.D. and Heathershaw, A.D.|title= Measurement of viscous sound absorption at 50-150 kHz in a model turbid environment|journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America |year=1998 |volume=104  |issue= 4|pages= 2114\u20132120 |url=  http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub182.pdf|doi= 10.1121/1.423725|bibcode= 1998ASAJ..104.2114B}}</ref> \n# acoustic propagation down curved columns of fluid, and how horns could facilitate this;<ref name=\"Music in Space\"/><ref name=\":2\"/><ref name=planetaria/><ref name=\"Fluid_loading\"/><ref name=\"multidisciplinary_lecture_2\">{{cite web|title=T.G. Leighton, lecture, University of Southampton Multidisciplinary Research Week 2013|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5H4toaWU_IY&t=2791s |accessdate=2018-10-01}}</ref>\n# use of acoustic pulses to enhance bubble activity;<ref name=abubble/><ref name=\"Leighton+Pickworth1\">{{cite journal|last1= Leighton, T.G., Pickworth, M.J.W., Walton, A.J. and Dendy, P.P.|title=  Studies of the cavitational effects of clinical ultrasound by sonoluminescence: 1 correlation of sonoluminescence with the standing-wave pattern in an acoustic field produced by a therapeutic unit|journal= Physics in Medicine and Biology|year=1988 |volume=33 |issue=11 |pages=1239\u20131248|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2492.pdf|doi= 10.1088/0031-9155/33/11/002|bibcode= 1988PMB....33.1239L}}</ref><ref name=\"Leighton+Pickworth2\">{{cite journal|last1=  Pickworth, M.J.W., Dendy, P.P., Leighton, T.G. and Walton, A.J. |title=   Studies of the cavitational effects of clinical ultrasound by sonoluminescence: 2 Thresholds for sonoluminescence from a therapeutic ultrasound beam and the effect of temperature and duty cycle|journal= Physics in Medicine and Biology|year=1988 |volume=33 |issue=11 |pages=1249\u20131260|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2493.pdf|doi= 10.1088/0031-9155/33/11/003|bibcode= 1988PMB....33.1249P}}</ref><ref name=\"Leighton_Transient_Excitation1\">{{cite journal|last1=   Leighton, T.G. |title=  Transient excitation of insonated bubbles|journal= Ultrasonics|year=1989 |volume=27 |issue=1 |pages=50\u201353|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2511.pdf|doi= 10.1016/0041-624X(89)90009-7}}</ref><ref name=\"Leighton_Transient_Excitation2\">{{cite journal|last1=   Leighton, T.G., Walton, A.J. and Field, J.E. |title=   High-speed photography of transient excitation|journal= Ultrasonics|year=1989 |volume=27  |issue= 6|pages=370\u2013373|url=  http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2512.pdf|doi= 10.1016/0041-624X(89)90036-X}}</ref><ref name=\"Leighton+Pickworth3\">{{cite journal|last1= Pickworth, M.J.W., Dendy, P.P., Leighton, T.G., Worpe, E. and Chivers, R.C. |title=  Studies of the cavitational effects of clinical ultrasound by sonoluminescence: 3 Cavitation from pulses a few microseconds in length |journal= Physics in Medicine and Biology|year=1989 |volume=34 |issue=9 |pages=1139\u20131151|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2507.pdf|doi= 10.1088/0031-9155/34/9/001 |bibcode= 1989PMB....34.1139P }}</ref>\n# controlled bubble generation;<ref name=\"swarm\"/>\n# how these bubbles affect living cells<ref name=abubble/><ref name=\"Leighton_cheek\">{{cite journal|last1= Leighton, T.G., Pickworth M.J.W., Tudor, J. and Dendy, P.P.|title=   Search for sonoluminescence in vivo in the human cheek|journal= Ultrasonics|year=1990 |volume=28 |issue= 3|pages=181\u2013184|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2510.pdf|doi= 10.1016/0041-624X(90)90083-Z|pmid= 2339477}}</ref> and surfaces.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Howlin R.P., Fabbri S., Offin D.G., Symonds N., Kiang K.S., Knee R.J., Yoganantham D.C., Webb J.S., Birkin P.R., Leighton T.G., Stoodley P. |title=Removal of dental biofilms with a novel ultrasonically-activated water stream |journal=Journal of Dental Research |year=2015 |volume=94|issue=9 |pages=1303\u20131309 |url=http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/377560/ |postscript= (electronic supplement at url: http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/377535/). |doi=10.1177/0022034515589284|pmid=26056055 }}</ref><ref name=SS2015a>{{cite journal|last1=Birkin P.R., Offin D.G., Vian C.J.B., Howlin R.P., Dawson J.I., Secker T.J., Herve R.C., Stoodley P., Oreffo R.O.C., Keevil C.W. and Leighton T.G. |title=Cold water cleaning of brain proteins, biofilm and bone \u2013 harnessing an ultrasonically activated stream |journal=Physical Chemistry Chemical Physics |year=2015 |volume=17 |issue=32 |pages=20574\u201320579 |doi= 10.1039/C5CP02406D |pmid=26200694 |url=http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/378564/|bibcode=2015PCCP...1720574B }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Birkin, P.R., Offin, D.G., and Leighton, T.G. |title=An activated fluid stream - new techniques for cold water cleaning |journal=UltrasonicsSonochemistry |year=2016 |volume=29 |pages=612\u2013618 |doi= 10.1016/j.ultsonch.2015.10.001 |pmid=26522990 |url=http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/382666/}}</ref><ref name=\"swarm\">{{cite journal |last1=Birkin, P.R., Offin, D.G., Vian, C.J.B. and Leighton, T.G. |title=Electrochemical 'bubble swarm' enhancement of ultrasonic surface cleaning |journal= Physical Chemistry Chemical Physics |year=2015 |volume=17 |issue=33 |pages=21709\u201321715 |doi= 10.1039/c5cp02933c | pmid=26234563 |url= http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/381291/|bibcode=2015PCCP...1721709B }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Salta|first=M|last2=Goodes|first2=L R|last3=Maas|first3=B J|last4=Dennington|first4=S P|last5=Secker|first5=T J|last6=Leighton|first6=T G|title=Bubbles versus biofilms: a novel method for the removal of marine biofilms attached on antifouling coatings using an ultrasonically activated water stream|journal=Surface Topography: Metrology and Properties|volume=4|issue=3|doi=10.1088/2051-672x/4/3/034009|year=2016|page=034009|bibcode=2016SuTMP...4c4009S|url=https://eprints.soton.ac.uk/399242/1/Manuscript_GT_Salta_2ndResubmission_v5.docx}}</ref><ref name=\"Goodes_2016\">{{cite journal |last1=Goodes, L., Harvey, T., Symonds, N. and Leighton, T.G. |title=A comparison of ultrasonically activated stream and ultrasonic bath immersion cleaning of railhead leaf-film contaminant|journal= Surface Topography: Metrology and Properties|year=2016 |volume=4 |issue=3 |pages=034003|doi= 10.1088/2051-672X/4/3/034003| url= http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/394497/}}</ref> \nThese 10 streams of fundamental research represented the knowledge on which Sloan Water Technology Ltd. was founded.<ref name=\"Sloan Water Technology Ltd. homepage\"/> It is currently producing technology for cleaning and changing surfaces using only cold water, air bubbles and sound (without chemicals or drugs).<ref name=Rayleigh_Medal_paper>{{Cite journal|last=Leighton |first=Timothy | authorlink1 = Timothy Leighton|year=2014 |title=Bubble Acoustics: From whales to other worlds |journal= Proceedings of the Institute of Acoustics |volume=36|issue=3 |pages= 58\u201386|doi=}}</ref><ref name=\"Baking_Europe_2018\">{{Cite journal|last=Leighton |first=Timothy | authorlink1 = Timothy Leighton|year=2018 |title= Cold water cleaning in the preparation of food and beverages: The power of shimmering bubbles|journal= Baking Europe |volume=Summer 2018|issue= |pages= 8\u201312|url= http://www.bakingeurope.eu/previews/2018/BakingEurope-Summer-2018.pdf|accessdate=2018-08-18}}</ref><ref name=IOP2017>{{Cite journal|last=Leighton|first=T. G.|date=1 January 2017|title=The acoustic bubble: Ocean, cetacean and extraterrestrial acoustics, and cold water cleaning|journal=Journal of Physics: Conference Series|language=en|volume=797|issue=1|pages=012001|doi=10.1088/1742-6596/797/1/012001|issn=1742-6596|bibcode=2017JPhCS.797a2001L|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\"POMA_2016\">{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G.|title=The acoustic bubble: Oceanic bubble acoustics and ultrasonic cleaning|journal= Proceedings of Meetings on Acoustics|year=2016|volume=24|pages=070006|doi=10.1121/2.0000121|doi-access=free}}</ref> This reduces the use of water and electricity,<ref name=ICSV17>{{Cite journal|last=Leighton |first=Timothy | authorlink1 = Timothy Leighton|year=2017 |title= Climate change, dolphins, spaceships and anti-microbial resistance - The impact of bubble acoustics |journal= Proceedings of the International Congress on Sound and Vibration |volume=24|issue= |pages= 1\u201316|doi=}}</ref> reduces pollution and has run-off that is easier to convert back to drinking water, and reduces the threat of \u2018superbugs\u2019.<ref name=\"NewScientistNAMRIP\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg22930662-500-resistance-fighter-takes-the-battle-to-microbes/ |title=Resistance fighter takes the battle to the microbes|publisher=Author: J. Webb, New Scientist (26 March 2016, pp. 32\u201333) published online entitled \"I\u2019m finding new ways to beat antibiotic resistance\"|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref><ref name=POST_Journal2018/>\n\n==Awards and honours==\nLeighton has been awarded the following medals and distinctions:\n\n===Medals===\n{{div col|colwidth=35em}}\n* the 2017 [[Clifford Paterson Lecture]] and Medal of the Royal Society<ref name=\"RS_Paterson\">{{cite web|title=Engineering professor honoured with Royal Society award|url=https://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/news/2017/07/19-scientist-honoured-with-award.page|accessdate=2017-07-31}}</ref><ref name=\"RS_Paterson_storify\">{{cite web |title=Royal Society medal awarded to T G Leighton (18 July 2017)|url= https://www.southampton.ac.uk/news/2017/07/leighton-royal-society-award.page|publisher=University of Southampton|accessdate=2017-07-31}}</ref> (video of Lecture here<ref name=\"RS_Paterson_Lecture_video\">{{cite web|title=Royal Society Paterson Medal Lecture (5 September 2018)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DhCRI_CsIP4|accessdate=2018-10-31}}</ref>)\n* the 2014 [[Rayleigh Medal]] of the [[Institute of Acoustics (United Kingdom)|Institute of Acoustics]]<ref name=\"UOS_IOA_Rayleigh\">{{cite web|title=Prestigious acoustics medal for Southampton Professor|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/mediacentre/features/timleighton_ioaaward.shtml|accessdate=2014-09-26}}</ref><ref name=\"IOA_Rayleigh_storify\">{{cite web |title=FRS award|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Acoustics_Bulletin_Jan-Feb_2015_0_page28.pdf|publisher=Institute of Acoustics|accessdate=2016-09-04}}</ref>\n* the 2013 Helmholtz-Rayleigh Interdisciplinary Silver Medal of the [[Acoustical Society of America]]<ref name=\"ASA_Citation_Rayleigh\">{{cite web|title=Citation for the Helmholtz-Rayleigh Interdisciplinary Silver Medal (Acoustical Society of America)|url= http://www.southampton.ac.uk/assets/sharepoint/groupsite/Administration/SitePublisher-document-store/Documents/passlvrhelm_ray.pdf |accessdate=2016-09-04}}</ref><ref name=\"ASA_Silver_Rayleigh\">{{cite web|title=The Helmholtz-Rayleigh Interdisciplinary Silver Medal (Acoustical Society of America)|url= http://www.southampton.ac.uk/sites/engineering/research/projects/media/rayleigh_medal/tim_leighton_awarded_the_helmholtz_rayleigh.page |accessdate=2016-09-04}}</ref>\n* the 2009 R W B Stephens Medal of the Institute of Acoustics<ref>{{cite web|title=The RWB Stephens Medal awarded to Professor T G Leighton|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Stephens_Medal_Acoustics_Bulletin_Mar-Apr_2009.pdf|accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref>\n* the 2006 Paterson Medal of the Institute of Physics<ref name=Paterson_1/><ref>{{cite web|title=The Clifford Paterson Medal awarded to Professor T G Leighton|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2006_v2.pdf|accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref>\n* the inaugural 2004 Early Career Medal and Award of the [[International Commission for Acoustics]]\n* the 2002 Tyndall Medal of the Institute of Acoustics\n* the 1994 A. B. Wood Medal of the Institute of Acoustics<ref>{{cite web|title=1994 A B Wood Medal|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/A_B_Wood.pdf|accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\nThe citation of the 2006 Paterson Medal of the [[Institute of Physics]] states that: {{centred pull quote|Timothy Leighton's contribution is outstanding in both breadth and depth. He is an acknowledged world leader in four fields... He has delivered over 70 pioneering advances, from devices now used in hospitals to the world's first count of bubbles in the surf zone (crucial to our understanding of atmosphere-ocean gas flux, coastal erosion and the optimisation of military [[sonar]]). Behind these advances lies rigorous physics.<ref name=\"Paterson_1\">{{cite web|title=The Paterson Medal awarded to Professor T G Leighton|url= http://www.southampton.ac.uk/news/2005/10/physics-prize-for-professor.page |accessdate=2016-09-04}}</ref>}}\n\n===Awards===\n{{div col|colwidth=35em}}\n* 2019 Doctor of Science, University of Cambridge<ref name=\"ScD_Eng_Jan2019\">{{cite web|title= Southampton professor Tim Leighton honoured as Doctor of Science |url= https://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/news/2019/01/tim-leighton-doctor-of-science.page |accessdate=2019-01-26}}</ref>\n* 2018 Royal Society's Lord Leonard and Lady Estelle Wolfson Foundation Translation Award for the StarHealer<ref name=\"Wolfson_StarHealer_2018\">{{cite web|title= Royal Society Award to NAMRIP team for StarHealer|url= https://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/news/2018/03/royal-society-prince-andrew-award.page |accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref>\n* the 2014 'Best new product of the year' award for StarStream<ref name=\"S-lab_storify\">{{cite web |title=Best New Product|url= https://www.labmate-online.com/news/news-and-views/5/university_of_southampton/product_of_the_year_award_for_cleaning_device/31844 |publisher=LabMate|accessdate=2016-09-04}}</ref><ref name=\"New_Product_1\">{{cite web|title=Southampton 'StarStream' cleaning technology wins prestigious award|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DTSgCvdnGfc|publisher=University of southampton, chemistry|accessdate=2014-09-26}}</ref><ref name=\"New_Product_2\">{{cite web|title=Ultrasonic device which enhances water's ability to clean wins 'Product of the Year'|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/mediacentre/news/2014/sep/14_162.shtml|accessdate=2014-09-26}}</ref><ref name=\"New_Product_ITV\">{{cite web|title= ITV News - University demonstrates pioneering device for cleaning medical instruments\n|url= https://www.itv.com/news/meridian/2015-09-17/university-demonstrates-pioneering-device-for-cleaning-medical-instruments/|accessdate=2016-09-26}}</ref>\n* the 2012 Institute of Chemical Engineering Award for Water Management and Supply<ref name=\"IChemE-Storify\">{{cite web|title= The 2012 Institute of Chemical Engineering Award for 'Water Management and Supply'  |url= http://www.discoversouthampton.co.uk/living/news/2015/09/16/using-ultrasound-to-clean-medical-instruments |accessdate=2016-09-04}}</ref>\n* the 2011 Royal Society [[Frank Brian Mercer|Brian Mercer Award]] for Innovation<ref name=\"RS_Mercer_video\">{{cite web|title= Royal Society Brian Mercer Award video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I__tsXsYbQA|accessdate=2016-09-04}}</ref><ref name=\"RS_Mercer_1\">{{cite web|title= Royal Society Brian Mercer Award clippings|url= http://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/research/projects/media/starstream_media_coverage/part_one_royal_society_premier_award.page |accessdate=2016-09-04}}</ref>\n* the 2008 'Medical & Healthcare' award from '[[The Engineer (UK magazine)|The Engineer]]'<ref name=Litho_1/><ref name=\"Litho_2\">{{cite web|title=The Engneer Magazine 2008 Technology and innovation awards 2008|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/litho_the_engineer_2008.pdf|accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref>\n* the inaugural 2001 International Medwin Prize for Acoustical Oceanography from the [[Acoustical Society of America]]<ref name=\"Medwin_1\">{{cite web|title=Inaugural Medwin Prize in Acoustical Oceanography awarded to Professor T G Leighton|url= http://www.southampton.ac.uk/assets/sharepoint/groupsite/Administration/SitePublisher-document-store/Documents/timothy_leighton_awarded_medwin_prize.pdf |accessdate=2016-09-04}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Fellowships===\nLeighton is an Academician of three National Academies.<ref name=\"TripleCrown\"/> He was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] (FRS) in 2014.<ref name=\"FRS_WorldwideUniversitiesNetwork\">{{cite web|title= Worldwide Universities Network - Southampton professor receives prestigious Fellowship of the Royal Society|url= https://wun.ac.uk/article/southampton-professor-receives-prestigious-fellowship-royal-society |accessdate=2016-09-26}}</ref><ref name=frs/><ref name=\"FRS_AcousticsToday\">{{cite web|title= Acoustics Today - ASA fellow Timothy G. Leighton \u2013 Radar System TWIPR|url=https://acousticstoday.org/fellowship-royal-society/|accessdate=2016-09-26}}</ref> His nomination reads: {{centred pull quote|Timothy Leighton is distinguished for his research on the [[Acoustics|acoustical physics]] of bubbles, especially their [[Nonlinear system|nonlinear behaviour]]; for his inventions and discoveries including bubble measurements in the [[surf zone]], pipelines and [[Cold seep|methane seeps]]; for [[shock wave]] [[lithotripsy]] monitoring, disease detection in [[cancellous bone]] and needle free injection; for [[sonar]] systems that overcome bubble masking and numerous industrial applications. His seminal monograph The Acoustic Bubble has become the primary reference on bubble physical acoustics.<ref name=frs/>}}\n\nIn 2018 he was elected to Fellowship of the Academy of Medical Sciences, the citation reading for 'harnessing the physical sciences for the benefit of patients' as: {{centred pull quote|an outstanding academic inventor whose leadership in acoustical physics of bubbles has led to the development of new medical devices and procedures. His research has dominated the field of acoustic bubbles since the appearance of his monograph in 1994, \u2018The Acoustic Bubble\u2019, which was published at the age of 29. In this, he laid out the mathematical foundation upon which much of the recent cutting edge research on ultrasonic contrast agents, drug delivery, and focused ultrasound surgery has been based. He has exceptional ability to deliver engineering solutions to real world problems from conceptualisation to product development embracing an advanced practical knowledge of IP strategy.<ref name=\"TripleCrown\"/>}}\n\nLeighton was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering]] (FREng)<ref name=\"List of Fellows\"/> in 2012<ref name=\"whoswho\"/> for his services to Engineering and society.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Univ. of South Hampton |date=20 July 2012 |title=Major honor for Professor Leighton |url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/news/2012/07/19_major_honour.page}}</ref> He was elected a [[Fellow of the Institute of Physics]] (FInstP) in 2000,<ref name=\"FInstP2000\">{{cite web|title=Fellowship of the Institute of Physics|url= https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Category:Fellows_of_the_Institute_of_Physics|accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref>{{Circular reference|date=July 2019}} Fellowship of [[Institute of Acoustics (United Kingdom)|Institute of Acoustics]] in 1999,<ref name=\"ISVR50_interview\">{{cite web|title= ISVR50_interview |url= http://www.isvr50.soton.ac.uk/interviews/Tim-Leighton-interview.htm|accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref> Fellowship of the [[Acoustical Society of America]] in 1998,<ref name=\"FASA1998\">{{cite web|title=Fellowship of the Acoustical Society of America|url= http://acousticstoday.org/fellowship-royal-society/|accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref> and Fellowship of the Cambridge Philosophical Society in 1988.<ref name=\"cambridgephilosophicalsociety\">{{cite web|title=Cambridge Philosophical Society |url= http://www.cambridgephilosophicalsociety.org/history.shtml|accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref> He is a Visiting Fellow of the Institute of Advanced Studies of Loughborough University.<ref name=\"IAS_Loughborough\">{{cite web|title=Fellowship of the Institute of Advanced Studies of Loughborough University|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/%20Institute%20of%20Advanced%20Studies%20Sound%20Theme%20Summit.pdf|accessdate=2019-11-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 the International Institute of Acoustics and Vibration (IIAV), of which he had not been a member, undertook a change to its Bylaws, and vote of all IIAV members, to create new rank of Distinguished Fellow. It is the highest rank for individual IIAV members of this international body, and Professor Leighton was the recipient in its inaugural year.<ref>{{cite web|title=IIAV Distinguished Fellow |url= https://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/news/2018/11/tim-leighton-honour.page?|accessdate=2018-11-10}}</ref>\n\n==Outreach, TV and radio work==\nLeighton has developed and conducted multiply-award-winning outreach activities to the public, and to encourage of young men and women to engage, and possibly follow careers in, science and engineering, with school visits, science fairs, exhibits, games, and appearances on TV and radio.<ref name=accoubub/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Leighton|first1=Timothy|title=Home Page soton uni|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/about/staff/tgl.page#tab1|accessdate=2014-08-25}}</ref><ref name=\"TV+radio\">{{cite web|title=Downloads of Video and audio appearances of Professor Leighton|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/TV_and_radio_appearances_Leighton.htm|accessdate=2018-07-03}}</ref>\nHis public engagement work regarding his invention, \u201cThe most dangerous game in the world\u201d, which he designed to communicate with the public on the issue of superbugs and how they can protect themselves and society, was mentioned by Steve Brine MP, the Under-Secretary of State for Health on 16 November 2017.<ref name=\"Brine_Nov17\"/><ref name=\"Brine_TV_Nov17\"/> The IMDb and \"Who's Who\" have collated entries for Professor Leighton.<ref name=\"IMDB_Leighton\">{{Cite journal| last1= IMDb | title=  IMDb |series= IMDb database of movie and TV content |year=2011|volume=Record for T. G. Leighton|url= https://www.imdb.com/name/nm4575762/?ref_=ttfc_fc_cl_t62}}</ref><ref name=\"whoswho\"/> In his 2014 book 'Sonic Wonderland', the broadcaster Trevor Cox described Professor Leighton as 'a middle-aged Harry Potter'.<ref name=\"Cox1\">{{cite journal|last1=Cox, T.|title=Sonic Wonderland| publisher= Bodley Head |year=2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{CC-notice|cc=by4|url=https://royalsociety.org/people/timothy-leighton-11808/}}\n\n{{FRS 2014}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leighton, Timothy Grant}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Academy of Engineering]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Institute of Physics]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Professor of Ultrasonics and Underwater Acoustics}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Timothy Leighton\n| honorific_suffix  = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRS|FREng|FMedSci|size=100%}}\n| birth_name        = Timothy Grant Leighton\n| image             = Professor Timothy Leighton FREng FRS.jpg\n| image_size        = 250x250px\n| alt               =\n| caption           = Timothy Leighton at the [[Royal Society]] admissions day in London, July 2014\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1963|10|16}}<ref name=\"whoswho\">{{Who's Who | surname = Leighton | othernames = Prof. Timothy Grant | id = U257715 | year = 2014 | edition = online [[Oxford University Press]]|doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.257715|author=Anon}}</ref>\n| birth_place       = [[Blackburn]], Lancashire\n| other_names       =\n| residence         =\n| citizenship       =\n| nationality       =\n| fields            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ultrasound|Ultrasonics]]\n* [[Acoustics]]<ref>https://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/about/staff/tgl.page</ref>}}\n| workplaces        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Cavendish Laboratory]]\n* [[University of Cambridge]]\n* [[University of Southampton]]}}\n| patrons           =\n| education         = [[Dallam School|Heversham Grammar School, Cumbria]]\n| alma_mater        = [[University of Cambridge]] (MA, PhD)\n| thesis_title      = Image intensifier studies of sonoluminescence, with application to the safe use of medical ultrasound\n| thesis_url        = http://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?uin=uk.bl.ethos.279713\n| thesis_year       = 1988\n| doctoral_advisor  =\n| academic_advisors =\n| doctoral_students =\n| notable_students  =\n| known_for         =''The Acoustic Bubble''<ref name=abubble>The Acoustic Bubble. By Timothy G. Leighton Academic Press, 1994. 613 pp. {{ISBN|0124124984}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1006/jsvi.1994.1305| title = Review of the {{sic|Acc|oustic|nolink=yes|expected=Acoustic}} Bubble, by T. G. Leighton| journal = Journal of Sound and Vibration| volume = 174| issue = 5| pages = 709\u2013710| year = 1994| last1 = Crum | first1 = L. A. }}</ref>\n| influences        =\n| influenced        =\n| awards  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Rayleigh Medal]] (2014)\n* [[Clifford Paterson Lecture]] (2018)}}\n| website           = {{URL|southampton.ac.uk/engineering/about/staff/tgl.page}}\n| footnotes         =\n| spouse            =\n| children          =\n}}\n'''Timothy Grant Leighton'''  {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRS|FREng|FMedSci}}<ref name=TripleCrown>{{cite web|title=TripleCrown |url=https://www.southampton.ac.uk/news/2018/05/tim-leighton-fellowship.page| year=2019}}</ref><ref name=frs>{{cite web|title=Professor Timothy Leighton FREng FRS |url=https://royalsociety.org/people/timothy-leighton-11808/ |publisher=royalsociety.org |location=London |year=2014 |author=Anon |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306143507/https://royalsociety.org/people/timothy-leighton-11808/ |archivedate=2016-03-06 |url-status=dead }} One or more of the preceding sentences incorporates text from the royalsociety.org website where: {{quote|\"All text published under the heading 'Biography' on Fellow profile pages is available under [[Creative Commons license|Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License]].\" --{{cite web|url=https://royalsociety.org/about-us/terms-conditions-policies/ |title=Royal Society Terms, conditions and policies |accessdate=2016-03-09 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161111170346/https://royalsociety.org/about-us/terms-conditions-policies/ |archivedate=2016-11-11 }}}}</ref><ref name=\"FRS_Uni_soton\">{{cite web |title=FRS award|url= https://www.southampton.ac.uk/news/2017/07/leighton-royal-society-award.page|publisher=University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-09-04}}</ref><ref name=\"List of Fellows\">{{cite web |url=http://www.raeng.org.uk/about-us/people-council-committees/the-fellowship/list-of-fellows |title=List of Fellows |website=raeng.org.uk}}</ref> (born 16 October 1963)<ref name=\"whoswho\"/><ref name=abubble/> is the Professor of [[Ultrasound|Ultrasonics]] and [[Underwater Acoustics]] at the [[University of Southampton]].<ref name=\"what_is_ultrasound\">{{Cite journal| pmid = 17045633| year = 2007| last1 = Leighton| first1 = T. G.| authorlink1 = Timothy Leighton| title = What is ultrasound?| journal = Progress in Biophysics and Molecular Biology| volume = 93| issue = 1\u20133| pages = 3\u201383| doi = 10.1016/j.pbiomolbio.2006.07.026}}</ref><ref name=\"scopus\">{{Scopus id}}</ref><ref name=epmc>{{EuropePMC|ORCID=0000-0002-1649-8750}}</ref><ref name=accoubub>{{YouTube|id=5H4toaWU_IY|title=Professor Tim Leighton, University of Southampton, 'The Acoustic Bubble'}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/1350-4177(95)00021-W| title = Bubble population phenomena in acoustic cavitation| journal = Ultrasonics Sonochemistry| volume = 2| issue = 2| pages = S123\u2013S136| year = 1995| last1 = Leighton | first1 = T. G. }}</ref><ref name=\"radarclutter\"/> He is the inventor-in-chief of [[#Sloan Water Technology Ltd.|Sloan Water Technology Ltd.]],<ref name=\"Sloan Water Technology Ltd. homepage\"/> a company founded around his inventions. \nHe is an academician of three national academies.<ref name=\"TripleCrown\"/> Trained in physics and theoretical physics, he works across physical, medical, biological, social and ocean sciences, fluid dynamics and engineering. He joined the Institute of Sound and Vibration Research (ISVR) at the [[University of Southampton]] in 1992 as a lecturer in underwater acoustics, and completed the monograph ''The Acoustic Bubble''<ref name=abubble/> in the same year. He was awarded a [[Professor|personal chair]] at the age of 35 and has authored over 400 publications.<ref name=\"scopus\" /><ref name=\"soton\"/><ref name=\"University of Southampton\">{{cite web|last1=Published papers|title=ISVR, Ultrasonics, underwater acoustics|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/pubs90.htm|publisher=University of Southampton|accessdate=2014-08-30}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nHe was educated at [[Dallam School|Heversham Grammar School, Cumbria]] and [[Magdalene College, Cambridge]] where he studied the [[Natural Sciences Tripos]] and awarded a [[British undergraduate degree classification|double first class]] Bachelor of Arts degree with honours in [[physics]] and [[theoretical Physics]] in 1985, obtaining a [[PhD]] in 1988 at the [[Cavendish Laboratory]], University of Cambridge.<ref name=\"whoswho\"/><ref name=\"phd\">{{cite thesis |degree=PhD |first=Timothy Grant|last=Leighton |title= Image intensifier studies of sonoluminescence, with application to the safe use of medical ultrasound |publisher=University of Cambridge |year=1988 |id={{EThOS|uk.bl.ethos.279713}}|oclc=60020372|authorlink=Timothy Leighton|url=https://idiscover.lib.cam.ac.uk/primo-explore/fulldisplay?docid=44CAM_ALMA21428173570003606&context=L&vid=44CAM_PROD&search_scope=SCOP_CAM_ALL&tab=cam_lib_coll&lang=en_US|website=lib.cam.ac.uk}}</ref><ref name=\"Ingenia_biography\">{{cite web|title=A talent for bursting bubbles (Ingenia_biography) |url=https://www.ingenia.org.uk/getattachment/Ingenia/Issue-73/Profile/Profile-Timonthy-Leighton-Freng.pdf|accessdate=2018-11-10}}</ref><ref name=\"New_Scientist_biography\">{{cite web|title= New Scientist biography |url= https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg22930662-500-resistance-fighter-takes-the-battle-to-microbes/ |accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref>\nFollowing his PhD, he was awarded senior and advanced [[research fellow]]ships at Magdalene College, Cambridge funded by the [[Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council]] (EPSRC).<ref name=\"University of Southampton career history\">{{cite web|last1=Published papers|title=University of Southampton career history|url=https://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/about/staff/tgl.page#career_history|publisher=University of Southampton|accessdate=2018-10-03}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nHe joined the Institute of Sound and Vibration Research (ISVR) at the [[University of Southampton]] in 1992 as a lecturer in underwater acoustics, and completed the monograph ''The Acoustic Bubble''<ref name=abubble/> in the same year. He was awarded a [[Professor|personal chair]] at the age of 35.\n\n==Research==\n\nHe founded and leads two research organisations he founded ([[#NAMRIP and Global-NAMRIP|Global-NAMRIP]] and [[#Health Effects of Ultrasound in Air|HEFUA]]), is a director and inventor-in-chief of [[#Sloan Water Technology Ltd.|Sloan Water Technology Ltd.]],<ref name=\"Sloan Water Technology Ltd. homepage\"/> and talks extensively to schoolchildren, the public,<ref name=\"multidisciplinary_lecture_1\">{{cite web|title=T.G. Leighton, lecture, multidisciplinary research|url=https://podcasts.ox.ac.uk/bubble-acoustics-listening-ocean-cleaning-medical-devices-and-fighting-antimicrobial-and|accessdate=2018-10-01}}</ref> and on radio and video.<ref name=\"TGL_media_1\">{{cite web|title=T.G.Leighton Outreach|url=http://www.soton.ac.uk/engineering/about/staff/tgl.page#stories_in_the_media|accessdate=2016-08-30}}</ref>\n\nHis research covers medical, humanitarian and environmental sciences, beginning with the fundamental mathematics and ending with engineering applications. His research interests cover [[acoustical oceanography]], [[antimicrobial resistance]],<ref name=\"NAMRIP_index\"/><ref name=\"NAMRIP_Global-NAMRIP\"/> [[medical ultrasonography|biomedical ultrasound]],<ref name=\"WFUMB1998\"/> [[carbon capture and storage]],<ref name=\":0\"/><ref name=\":1\"/><ref name=\"Berges1\"/> [[climate change]],<ref name=\":1\"/><ref name=\"Brooks2009a\"/><ref name=\"Brooks2009b\"/><ref name=\"sparbuoy\"/> [[decontamination]],<ref name=\"IOP2017\"/> [[hospital acquired infections]],<ref name=\"SS2015a\"/> [[marine zoology]],<ref name=\"Solan2016\"/><ref name=Cav&Cet2007>{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G., Finfer, D.C. and White, P.R. |title=Cavitation and cetacean|journal=Revista de Acustica|year=2007|volume=38|pages=37\u201381|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub9767.pdf|doi=}}</ref> [[fluid dynamics]], [[ultrasound]] and [[underwater acoustics]]. \nSuch fields as cold water cleaning,<ref name=\"SS2015a\"/> sound in space,<ref name=\"space_editorial\"/><ref name=\"icarus\"/><ref name=\"Music in Space\"/><ref name=\"planetaria\"/> ultrasound in air,<ref name=HEFUA+PRS16>{{Cite journal|last=Leighton |first=Timothy | authorlink1 = Timothy Leighton|year=2016 |title=Are some people suffering as a result of increasing mass exposure of the public to ultrasound in air? |journal= Proceedings of the Royal Society A |volume=472|issue=2185 |pages= 20150624|doi=10.1098/rspa.2015.0624|pmid=26997897 |pmc=4786042 |bibcode=2016RSPSA.47250624L }}</ref><ref name=HEFUA+PRS17>{{Cite journal|last=Leighton |first=Timothy | authorlink1 = Timothy Leighton|year=2016 |title=Comment on: 'Are some people suffering as a result of increasing mass exposure of the public to ultrasound in air?' |journal= Proceedings of the Royal Society A |volume=473|issue=2199 |pages= 20160828|doi=10.1098/rspa.2016.0828|pmid=28413349 |pmc=5378247 }}</ref> BiaPSS,<ref name=\"dolphins\"/> TWIPR,<ref name=\"radarclutter\"/> and passive acoustic lithortripsy monitoring,<ref name=Coleman92>{{cite journal|last1= Coleman, A.J., Choi, M.J., Saunders, J.E. and Leighton, T.G. |title=  Acoustic emission and sonoluminescence due to cavitation at the beam focus of an electrohydraulic shock wave lithotripter|journal= Ultrasound in Medicine and Biology|year=1992|volume=18|issue=  3|pages= 267\u2013281|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2517.pdf|doi=10.1016/0301-5629(92)90096-s|pmid= 1595133}}</ref><ref name=Coleman93>{{cite journal|last1= Coleman, A.J., Whitlock, M., Leighton, T.G. and Saunders, J.E.|title=The spatial distribution of cavitation induced acoustic emission, sonoluminescence and cell lysis in the field of a shock wave lithotriptor|journal= Physics in Medicine and Biology|year=1993|volume=38|issue=11|pages= 1545\u20131560|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2518.pdf|doi=10.1088/0031-9155/38/11/001|pmid=8272431|bibcode=1993PMB....38.1545C}}</ref><ref name=\"umb2008\"/><ref name=\"umb2008\"/><ref name=\"PRS2012_litho\"/> pushed pioneering research into game-changing technology.<ref name=\"Deep Dive\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.southampton.ac.uk/publicpolicy/what-we-do/with-whom-we-work/current-projects/apocalypse-pessimism.page|title=Deep dive: Should we be more pessimistic about the apocalypse?}}</ref><ref name=\"Evidence to Policy\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.southampton.ac.uk/publicpolicy/what-we-do/blogs/evidence-to-policy-blog/timleighton.page|title=Evidence to Policy: Are you sufficiently worried about superbugs?}}</ref><ref name=\"Conversation2015\"/><ref name=\"NewScientistNAMRIP\"/><ref name=\"Ingenia_biography\"/>  as opposed to incremental research that is published but falls short of societal benefit:\n{{centred pull quote|...We need to work with rigour, imagination, and wonder, unconstrained by the artificial boundaries set in place by discipline names, or the history of projects in which we have previously worked, or the tendency of sponsors to believe they can pick winners, or above all by the belief that we must jump to solutions when we have not yet perceived the real problem. Then, when we eventually do find a solution, we must have the will to push it through all the way to help others, and not simply publish in the expectation that someone will finish the job for us.<ref name=\"soton\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/about/staff/tgl.page#research|title=Professor Timothy Leighton |publisher=University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref>}}\n\nHe worked as part of the team investigating whether man-made sounds can adversely affect benthic species (marine life that inhabits the seabed).<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Solan, M., Hauton, C., Godbold, J.A., Wood, C., Leighton, T.G. and White, P.|title=  Anthropogenic sources of underwater sound can modify how sediment-dwelling invertebrates mediate ecosystems properties|journal=[[Scientific Reports]] |year=2016|volume=6|pages=20540, DOI: 10.1038/srep20540|doi=10.1038/srep20540|pmid=26847483|pmc=4742813|bibcode= 2016NatSR...620540S}}</ref><ref name=\"Benthic_web_2016\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/research/projects/man-made-underwater-sound.page|title=Man-made underwater sound may have wider ecosystem effects than previously thought|publisher=University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref> Such species have been overlooked in studies on how man-made sounds affect whales, dolphins and fish: benthic species find it far harder to relocate away from adverse sounds than do these other more mobile species. Furthermore, benthic species play a key role in the health of the marine sediment, turning it over and preventing it stagnating, and are key to the health of coastal marine environments.<ref name=Solan2016>{{Cite journal|last=Solan|first=Martin|last2=Hauton|first2=Chris|last3=Godbold|first3=Jasmin A.|last4=Wood|first4=Christina L.|last5=Leighton|first5=Timothy G.|last6=White|first6=Paul|date=5 February 2016|title=Anthropogenic sources of underwater sound can modify how sediment-dwelling invertebrates mediate ecosystem properties|journal=Scientific Reports|language=en|volume=6|issue=1|pages=20540|doi=10.1038/srep20540|issn=2045-2322|pmc=4742813|pmid=26847483|bibcode=2016NatSR...620540S}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/research/projects/man-made-underwater-sound.page|title=Man-made underwater sound may have wider ecosystem effects than previously thought {{!}} Engineering and the Environment {{!}} University of Southampton|publisher=University of Southampton|language=en|access-date=2017-04-09}}</ref>\n\nWith other teams he developed methods to assess which fish species are most at-risk from man-made noise in the oceans,<ref name=\"Neenan_AIS_2016\">{{cite book |chapter-url=  http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2016%20-%20Neenan%20et%20al%20(Modeling%20vessel%20noise%20emissions%20-%20AIS)%20POA.pdf|doi= 10.1121/2.0000338|chapter=Modeling vessel noise emissions through the accumulation and propagation of Automatic Identification System data |series=Proceedings of Meetings on Acoustics |pages= 070017|year= 2016|last1= Neenan|first1= Sarah T. V.|last2= White|first2= Paul R.|last3= Leighton|first3= Timothy G.|last4= Shaw|first4= Peter J.|url= https://eprints.soton.ac.uk/415944/1/2.pdf}}</ref> and quantified such noise from shipping.<ref name=\"Li_Hydrofoil_2019\">{{cite journal|last1= Li, J., White, P.R., Roche, B., Davis, J. W. and Leighton, T. G. |title=  Underwater radiated noise from hydrofoils in coastal water|journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America|year=2019 |volume=146  | issue = 5| pages= 3552\u20133561 | doi= 10.1121/1.5134779|pmid= 31795704|bibcode= 2019ASAJ..146.3552L}}</ref> Turning the problem on its head, he worked with other teams on how to use sound as 'underwater acoustic scarecrows' to guide fish away from regions of man-made danger. These might occurs, for example, where industry exacts cooling water from rivers used as migration paths of endangered species (the young of European eel are slim enough for the flow to pull them through grills placed over such extraction points).<ref name=\"Deleau_Fish_Manag_2019\">{{cite journal|last1=   Deleau, M. J. C., White, P. R., Peirson, G. Leighton, T. G. and Kemp, P. S. (2019)|title=  Use of acoustics to enhance the efficiency of physical screens designed to protect downstream moving European eel (Anguilla anguilla)|journal= Fisheries Management and Ecology|volume= 27|year=2019 | pages=1\u20139| doi= 10.1111/fme.12362|url=  http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2019_Deleau-et-al-2019.pdf }}</ref><ref name=\"Piper_2019\">{{cite journal|last1= Piper, A.T., White, P.R., Wright, R.M., Leighton, T. G., and Kemp, P.S. |title=  Response of seaward-migrating European eel (Anguilla anguilla) to an infrasound deterrent|journal= Ecological Engineering|year=2019 |volume=127 | pages= 480\u2013486| doi= 10.1016/j.ecoleng.2018.12.001|url=  http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2019_Piper-White-Wright-Leighton-Kemp(Response_of_eel_to_infrasound)Ecological_Engineering.pdf}}</ref>  (key collaborator: Paul White<ref name=\"southampton.ac.uk\"/>)\n\n===NAMRIP and Global-NAMRIP===\nThe Global Network for AntiMicrobial Resistance and Infection Prevention (Global-NAMRIP),<ref name=\"NAMRIP_index\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/index.page?|title=NAMRIP homepage|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref> is a multidisciplinary research team of hundreds researchers and end users, across four continents, including engineers, chemists, microbiologists, environmental scientists, veterinary and human medics, clinicians who contribute to international and national antibiotic guidelines for specified conditions, experts in food, ethics and law, crucially networked with economists, geographers, health scientists and experts from other social science disciplines to provide a truly joined up approach to antimicrobial resistance (AMR) and infection prevention (offsetting the loss of diversity in pharmaceutical industry research teams). As Leighton said at NAMRIP's 2016 conference:\n \n{{centred pull quote|...Unless preventative measures are found (and no-one in the world currently knows what those will be), AMR will (through the colloquial 'rise of superbugs') by 2050 be killing more people than cancer, and cost the world economy more than the current size of the global economy. We will not be able to feed the world unless we wean our food production industry off its dependence on antibiotics; common medical procedures (minor surgery, childbirth) will become significantly more hazardous; and advances in treatments (such as those for childhood leukaemia) will become reversed.}}\n\nGlobal-NAMRIP was set up to search for such solutions and mitigations, with particular emphasis to finding alternatives to the oft-cited route of simply funding drug companies to produce more antibiotics. According to the New Scientist,:<ref name=\"NewScientistNAMRIP\"/>\n{{centred pull quote|...I looked at all this and realised that even if there was a billion-dollar fund for new antibiotics, it would not sort out the problem; it might just buy us an extra decade. We need a new approach \u2013 a step change like the one antibiotics gave us when they first came in.<ref name=\"NewScientistNAMRIP\"/>}}\n\n{{centred pull quote|...In many parts of the world, climate change and flooding, war, corruption, politics, received wisdom, traditions and religious practices, and the supply of fuel and money, play a far greater role in food, water, waste treatment, healthcare and the transport of microbes from one host to another, than do the outputs of the drug companies. The twin potential catastrophes are global, and so are the causes. The solutions lie with scientists and engineers to develop new technologies and embed new practices in the public and workforce; they lie with farmers, plumbers, office workers, water and sewage workers, medical practitioners, food retailers, innovators in business \u2026 indeed most of us. And they lie with those who are responsible for shaping behaviour across the world \u2013 not just the pharmaceutical companies.<ref name=Conversation2015>{{Cite journal|last=Leighton |first=Timothy | authorlink1 = Timothy Leighton|year=2015 |title=We need more than just new antibiotics to fight superbugs |journal= The Conversation |issue=15 July 2015 | url = https://theconversation.com/we-need-more-than-just-new-antibiotics-to-fight-superbugs-44054}}</ref>}}\n\nGlobal-NAMRIP creates new research teams,<ref name=\"NAMRIP_news\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/news/latest.page?|title=NAMRIP news|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref> commissions new research,<ref name=\"NAMRIP_research\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/research/index.page?|title=NAMRIP research|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref> engaging with industry<ref name=\"NAMRIP_industry\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/industry/index.page?|title=NAMRIP industry|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref> to roll out solutions to society, and engaging with the public and policymakers to conduct outreach, education and dialogue.<ref name=\"NAMRIP_outreach\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/publicengagment/index.page?|title=NAMRIP outreach|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref> The award-winning Public Engagement<ref name=\"NAMRIP_outreach\"/> and Policymaker Engagement<ref name=\"NAMRIP_Policymaker_outreach\">{{cite web|url= https://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/publicpolicy/index.page |title=NAMRIP Policymaker Engagement Programme|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2018-11-11}}</ref> programmes that Leighton devised and leads have been mentioned in Parliament by the Under-Secretary of State for Health on 16 November 2017.<ref name=\"Brine_Nov17\">{{cite web|url= https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2017-11-16/debates/141BEBCB-C1F8-4BA7-ABF5-9186CAAC49F9/WorldAntibioticsAwarenessWeek|title= House of Commons Hansard (16 Nov 2017 Volume 631, 2.31 pm) |publisher=House of Commons, UK |accessdate=2017-11-16}}</ref><ref name=\"Brine_TV_Nov17\">{{cite web|url= https://parliamentlive.tv/event/index/0dbfadce-2829-4ed1-b45a-82bb41c4ed70?in=14:34:58&out=14:35:56|title= Parliament Live TV (16 Nov 2017) |publisher=House of Commons, UK |accessdate=2017-11-16}}</ref> and Leighton has addressed the Parliamentary and Scientific Committee on his approach to addressing the threat of AMR.<ref name=\"POST2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/news/2018/06/parliamentary-committee.page|title=Prof Leighton addresses Parliamentary and Scientific Committee|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2018-11-10}}</ref><ref name=POST_Journal2018>{{Cite journal|last=Leighton |first=Timothy | authorlink1 = Timothy Leighton|year=2018 |title= Can we end the threat of Anti-Microbial Resistance once and for all? |journal= Science in Parliament |volume=74 |issue=3 |pages= 29\u201332 }}</ref>\n\nGlobal-NAMRIP particularly supports Low/Middle Income Countries with not-for-profit interventions,<ref name=\"NAMRIP_Global-NAMRIP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/about/globalnamrip.page|title=Global-NAMRIP|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref> for example with initiatives in urban<ref name=\"NAMRIP2018_Accra\">{{cite web|url=https://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/news/2018/03/ghana-workshop.page|title=Global-NAMRIP 2018 conference|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2018-11-10}}</ref> and rural Ghana (infection being the primary cause of death in rural Ghana).<ref name=\"Navrongo2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/news/2018/03/navrongo-starhealer2018.page|title=Africa's first StarStream heads to Navrongo in northern Ghana|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2018-11-10}}</ref> In Uganda in 2019, Global-NAMRIP members from Uganda, Liberia, Malawi, Kenya, Ghana, Ethiopia and the UK met to compare, for the first time, the national AMR strategies of their respective countries, to share best practice. The meeting also produced significant impact in education, support for young innovators, and responded to a request from the Ugandan Minister for Health to write for him the 'Kampala Declaration on AMR'.<ref name=\"Uganda2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/news/2019/03/global-namrip-conf.page?|title=Successful Global-NAMRIP conference in Uganda|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2019-04-14}}</ref>\n\n===Health Effects of Ultrasound in Air===\nHealth Effects of Ultrasound in Air (HEFUA)<ref name=\"HEFUA_USRG\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/populationhealth/partners/HEFUA.page|title=HEFUA, Population Health, University of Southampton|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref><ref name=\"HEFUA_project\">{{cite web|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/research/projects/are-some-people-suffering.page|title=Ultrasound in Air, University of Southampton|publisher=The University of Southampton|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref><ref name=hefua>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/site/hefua2|title=HEFUA-2|website=sites.google.com}}</ref> was founded to map the increasing use of ultrasound in public places, and to investigate whether or not this increase is having adverse effects on some humans (following an investigation which revealed that the use of ultrasound in public places is increasing, and that guidelines were inadequate prior to the 2016 report).\n\nThe 2016 report<ref name=\"HEFUA+PRS16\"/> that first raised the issues was, in the first 2 years, downloaded over 20,000 times from the Royal Society website, leading to requests for a follow-up,<ref name=\"HEFUA+PRS17\"/> a journal special issue,<ref name=\"JASA2018_Table_of_Contents\">{{cite web|title=JASA 2018 Ultrasound in Air Special Issue |url=https://asa.scitation.org/toc/jas/144/4?tocSection=SPECIAL+ISSUE+ON+ULTRASOUND+IN+AIR&expanded=144|accessdate=2018-11-10}}</ref><ref name=\"JASA2018_Editorial\"/><ref name=\"JASA2018_Effects_on_Humans_Part_1\">{{Cite journal|last1= Fletcher, M.D., Lloyd Jones, S.D., White, P.R., Dolder, C.N., Leighton, T.G. and Lineton, B.| title= Effects of very high-frequency sound and ultrasound on humans. Part I: Adverse symptoms after exposure to audible very-high frequency sound |journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America |year=2018|volume=144|issue=4|pages=2511\u20132520 |doi=10.1121/1.5063819 | pmid= 30404512 | url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2018_Fletcher_et_al_(Effects_of_VHFS+US_on_humans_Part1_Audible)_JASA_144(4)2511_1.pdf| bibcode= 2018ASAJ..144.2511F }}</ref><ref name=\"JASA2018_Effects_on_Humans_Part_2\">{{Cite journal|last1= Fletcher, M.D., Lloyd Jones, S.D., White, P.R., Dolder, C.N., Leighton, T.G. and Lineton, B.| title= Effects of very high-frequency sound and ultrasound on humans. Part II: A double-blind randomized provocation study of inaudible 20-kHz ultrasound |journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America | year=2018|volume=144|issue=4|pages=2521\u20132531 |doi=10.1121/1.5063818| pmid= 30404504 |url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2018_Fletcher_et_al_(JASA)_Effects_of_VHF+US_on_humans_Part2_Inaudible_Ultrasound.pdf| bibcode= 2018ASAJ..144.2521F }}</ref><ref name=\"JASA2018_Public_Exposure_Field_Measurements\">{{Cite journal|last1= Fletcher, M.D., Lloyd Jones, S.D., White, P.R., Dolder, C.N., Lineton, B. and Leighton, T.G.| title= Public exposure to ultrasound and very high-frequency sound in air |journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America | year=2018| volume=144|issue=4|pages=2554\u20132564 |doi=10.1121/1.5063817 | pmid= 30404460 | url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2018_%20Fletcher_et_al_(Public_exposure_to_ultrasound)_JASA_144(4)2554_1.pdf| bibcode= 2018ASAJ..144.2554F }}</ref><ref name=\"JASA2018_Deterrents+Hairdryer\">{{Cite journal|last1= Dolder, C.N., Fletcher, M.D., Lloyd Jones, S., Lineton, B., Dennison, S.R., Symmonds, M., White, P.R. and Leighton, T.G.| title= Measurements of ultrasonic deterrents and an acoustically branded hairdryer: Ambiguities in guideline compliance |journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America |year=2018| volume=144|issue=4|pages=2565\u20132574 |doi=10.1121/1.5064279  | pmid= 30404457 | url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2018_Dolder_et_al_(Measurements_of_deterrents%20+hairdrier)_JASA_144(4)2565_1.pdf | bibcode= 2018ASAJ..144.2565D }}</ref><ref name=\"JASA2018_Duck+Leighton\">{{Cite journal|last1= Duck, F. and Leighton, T.G.| title= Frequency bands for ultrasound, suitable for the consideration of its health effects |journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America| year=2018| volume=144|issue=4|pages=2490\u20132500 |doi=10.1121/1.5063987 | pmid= 30404517 |url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2018_Duck_and_Leighton_(Frequency_bands_for_ultrasound)_JASA_144(4)2490_1.pdf}}</ref> and numerous conference sessions worldwide as the importance of this topic was realised.<ref name=\"Aachen_2019_Leighton\">{{Cite journal|last1= Leighton, T. G.| title= Ultrasound-in-Air: New applications need improved measurement methods and procedures, and appreciation of any adverse effects on humans|series= Proceedings of the 23rd International Congress on Acoustics (9 to 13 September 2019, Aachen, Germany)|year=2019|volume=paper 000434| pages=6363\u20136367 |url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2019-Leighton-ICA-Aachen(Human-effects-ultrasound-in-air).pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"Aachen_2019_Dolder+Leighton\">{{Cite journal|last1= Dolder, C.N., Fletcher, M.D., Lloyd Jones, S., Lineton, B., and Leighton, T. G.| title=  Exposure levels for parametric arrays in light of guideline ambiguities|series= Proceedings of the 23rd International Congress on Acoustics (9 to 13 September 2019, Aachen, Germany)|year=2019|volume=paper 000724| pages=6394\u20136397|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2019-ICA-Aachen-Dolder-Leighton-ultrasound-in-air-000472.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"ASA2018_Minneaspolic+streaming\">{{cite web|title=Minneapolis 2018 Acoustical Society of America streamed sessions |url= https://acousticalsociety.org/minneapolis-meeting-streamed-sessions/|accessdate=2018-12-12}}</ref> Scientists, engineers and the public around the world are now logging the location and type of device that emits ultrasound.<ref name=\"Martin_HEFUA_Japan_MAP\">{{Cite web|last1= Martin, H.| title=  Open map of ultrasonic sources in air in Japan|website= Google maps|year=2019|url= https://www.google.com/maps/d/u/0/edit?mid=1kzKTd4LtuiczGnCZ029k8KSjJonWY8Rd&ll=35.696377281403514%2C139.70292565&z=13}}</ref><ref name=\"JASA2018_Public_Exposure_Field_Measurements\"/> Leighton became an acknowledged world expert<ref name=\"Chan_NYT\">{{cite web|url= https://twitter.com/melissakchan/status/1009081601509281792|title=M. Chan (New York Times)|publisher=Twitter |accessdate=2018-06-19}}</ref> on such public exposures, and on the claims of 'sonic attacks' on US Embassy staff in Cuba and China.<ref name=\"JASA2018_Editorial\">{{Cite journal|last=Leighton|first=T. G.| title= Ultrasound in air\u2014Guidelines, applications, public exposures, and claims of attacks in Cuba and China |journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America | year=2018|volume=144|issue=4|pages=2473\u20132489 |doi=10.1121/1.5063351 |pmid=30404502|bibcode=2018ASAJ..144.2473L|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\"Asia+Pacific_blog_2018\">{{Cite journal|last=Leighton|first=T. G.|date=19 June 2018|title=Hearing things? A process of elimination casts doubt on reports of 'sonic attacks' in Cuba and China|url=https://www.policyforum.net/hearing-things/|journal=Asia & the Pacific Policy Society}}</ref><ref name=\"TheNewsLens_2018\">{{Cite journal|last=Leighton|first=T. G.|date=22 June 2018|title=Talk of 'Sonic Attacks' at US Embassies Rings Hollow|url=https://international.thenewslens.com/article/98394}}</ref><ref name=\"ScienceNews\">{{Cite journal|last=Saey|first=T.|date=1 June 2018|title=Here's why scientists are questioning whether 'sonic attacks' are real|url=https://www.sciencenews.org/article/scientists-are-questioning-whether-sonic-attacks-are-real}}</ref><ref name=\"NewYorkTimes_2018\">{{Cite journal| last1 = Kessel| first1 = J. M.| last2 = Chan | first2 = M.| last3 = Woo | first3 = J.|date=May 2018|title=How an Alleged Sonic Attack Shaped U.S. Policy on Cuba (Leighton interview is from 4.15-4.40 and 5.15-5.40 )|url=https://www.nytimes.com/video/world/americas/100000005848783/how-an-alleged-sonic-attack-shaped-us-policy-on-cuba.html?smid=pl-share}}</ref><ref name=\"Voice_of_America_2018\">{{Cite journal| last=Voice of America |date=May 2018|title=International Edition 2330 EDT (Leighton interview is from 12.24 until 17.25)|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/4392555.html}}</ref> His expertise on the effect on humans of ultrasound in air provided the scientific basis that was cited by Giles Watling MP (Clacton, Conservative) in the Motion for leave to bring in a Bill (Standing Order No. 23) on \"Anti-loitering Devices (Regulation)\" (17 July 2018 Volume 645, 2.06 pm).<ref name=\"Watling_July18\">{{cite web|url= https://parliamentlive.tv/event/index/09a35fb7-1fba-4eca-bfc8-1f6aa1067970?in=14:06:23|title= Parliament live TV (17 July 2018 Volume 645, 2.06 pm - Leighton's work mentioned 14:10:47) |publisher=House of Commons, UK |accessdate=2018-07-17}}</ref><ref name=\"Watling_Hansard_July18\">{{cite web|url= https://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2018-07-17/debates/6CFBF631-E484-4605-B6C8-6F54F47FDA92/Anti-LoiteringDevices(Regulation)|title= House of Commons Hansard (17 July 2018 Volume 645) |publisher=House of Commons, UK |accessdate=2018-07-17}}</ref>\n\n===Extraterrestrial acoustics===\n* Predicting the soundscapes of other worlds<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G. and White, P.R.|title=The Sound of Titan: A role for acoustics in space exploration|journal=Acoustics Bulletin|year=2004|volume=29|issue=4|pages=16\u201323}}</ref><ref name=\"Music in Space\">{{cite journal|last1=Leighton|first1=Timothy G.|last2=Petculescu|first2=Andi|title=The Sound of Music and Voices in Space Part 1: Theory|journal=Acoustics Today|volume=5|issue=3|year=2009|pages=17\u201326|issn=1557-0215|doi=10.1121/1.3238123}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite journal|last1=Leighton|first1=Timothy G.|last2=Petculescu|first2=Andi|title=The Sound of Music and Voices in Space Part 2: Modeling and Simulation|journal=Acoustics Today|volume=5|issue=3|year=2009|pages=27\u201329|issn=1557-0215|doi=10.1121/1.3238123}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G., White, P.R. and Finfer, D.C.|title=The opportunities and challenges in the use of extra-terrestrial acoustics in the exploration of the oceans of icy planetary bodies|journal=Earth, Moon, and Planets|year=2012|volume=109|issue=1\u20134|pages=99\u2013116|doi=10.1007/s11038-012-9399-6|bibcode=2012EM&P..109...91L}}</ref> and how these could best be exploited using acoustic devices, led to devices for planetaria to use when teaching about other worlds,<ref name=\"Music in Space\"/><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=planetaria>{{Cite journal|last=Leighton|first=T|last2=Banda|first2=N|last3=Berges|first3=B|last4=Joseph|first4=P|last5=White|first5=P|date=1 August 2016|title=Extraterrestrial sound for planetaria: A pedagogical study|journal=The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America|volume=140|issue=2|pages=1469\u20131480|doi=10.1121/1.4960785|pmid=27586771|issn=0001-4966|bibcode=2016ASAJ..140.1469L|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=space_editorial>{{Cite journal|last=Leighton|first=T|last2=Petculescu|first2=A|date=1 August 2016|title=Guest editorial: Acoustic and related waves in extraterrestrial environments|journal=The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America|volume=140|issue=2|pages=1397\u20131399|doi=10.1121/1.4961539|pmid=27586765|issn=0001-4966|bibcode=2016ASAJ..140.1397L|doi-access=free}}</ref> and showed how careful calculation was needed to avoid mistakes when using acoustic sensors on other worlds.<ref name=icarus>{{cite journal |last1=Leighton, T.G., Finfer, D.C. and White, P.R. |title=The problems with acoustics on a small planet |journal=Icarus|year=2008 |volume=193 |issue=2 |pages=649\u2013652 |doi= 10.1016/j.icarus.2007.10.008 |bibcode=2008Icar..193..649L }}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite journal| pmid = 21877784| year = 2011| last1 = Jiang | first1 = J| title = Acoustic attenuation, phase and group velocities in liquid-filled pipes II: Simulation for Spallation Neutron Sources and planetary exploration| journal = The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America| volume = 130| issue = 2| pages = 695\u2013706| last2 = Baik | first2 = K| last3 = Leighton | first3 = T.G.| doi = 10.1121/1.3598463| bibcode = 2011ASAJ..130..695J| url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/a915a5e41c92ae1f740d85154f832eddb40ca16c}}</ref><ref name=\"Fluid_loading\">{{Cite journal |doi= 10.1121/1.3104628 |pmid=19425625 |title= Fluid loading effects for acoustical sensors in the atmospheres of Mars, Venus, Titan, and Jupiter| journal = The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America| volume = 125| issue=5 |pages= EL214\u20139 |year=2009 |last1= Leighton |first1=T.G.|bibcode=2009ASAJ..125L.214L |doi-access= free }}</ref><ref name=nearesonant>{{Cite journal| pmid = 19894796| year = 2009| last1 = Ainslie | first1 = M. A.| title = Near resonant bubble acoustic cross-section corrections, including examples from oceanography, volcanology, and biomedical ultrasound| journal = The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America| volume = 126| issue = 5| pages = 2163\u201375| last2 = Leighton| first2 = T. G.| doi = 10.1121/1.3180130| bibcode = 2009ASAJ..126.2163A}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Ainslie | first1 = M. A. | last2 = Leighton | first2 = T. G. | year = 2016 | title = Sonar equations for planetary exploration | url = | journal = The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America | volume = 140 | issue = 2| pages = 1400\u20131419 | doi=10.1121/1.4960786| pmid = 27586766 | bibcode = 2016ASAJ..140.1400A | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n\n===Marine mammal acoustics===\nLeighton's explanation of how humpback whales use sound when feeding in bubble nets is now a staple explanation on whale tour boats.<ref name=\"eprints.soton.ac.uk\"/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G., Finfer, D., Grover, E. and White, P.R.|title=An acoustical hypothesis for the spiral bubble nets of humpback whales and the implications for whale feeding|journal=Acoustics Bulletin|year=2007|volume=22|issue=1|pages=17\u201321}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G., Richards, S.D. and White, P.R.|title=Trapped within a 'wall of sound': A possible mechanism for the bubble nets of the humpback whales|journal=Acoustics Bulletin|year=2004|volume=29|issue=1|pages=24\u201329}}</ref><ref name=\"Qing_JASA2019\">{{cite journal|last1= Qing, X., White, P. R., Leighton, T. G., Liu, S., Qiao, G. and Zhang, Y. |title=  Three-dimensional finite element simulation of acoustic propagation in spiral bubble net of humpback whale|journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America|year=2019|volume=146  |issue=3| pages= 1982\u20131995 | url=  http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2019-Qing-White-Leighton(Spiral-nets)JASAvol_146iss_31982_1.pdf|doi= 10.1121/1.5126003|pmid= 31590519|bibcode= 2019ASAJ..146.1982Q}}</ref> He explained how dolphins can echolocate while producing bubble nets to hunt, a process that should blind their sonar.<ref name=radarclutter/><ref name=\"ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\"/><ref name=\"eprints.soton.ac.uk\"/>\n\n==Inventions==\n===Medical and healthcare===\nLeighton invented systems for: \n* detecting bone disease (including osteoporosis).<ref name=\"Leighton_osteoporosis\">{{cite web|title=Osteoporosis breakthrough|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Leighton_osteoporosis.pdf|accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid10414898|noedit\">{{Cite journal | pmid = 10414898| year = 1999| last1 = Hughes| first1 = E. R.| title = Ultrasonic propagation in cancellous bone: A new stratified model| journal = Ultrasound in Medicine and Biology| volume = 25| issue = 5| pages = 811\u201321| last2 = Leighton| first2 = T. G.| last3 = Petley| first3 = G. W.| last4 = White| first4 = P. R.|doi=10.1016/s0301-5629(99)00034-4}}</ref><ref name=\"Hughes_et_al_2017\">{{Cite journal | pmid = 17297810| year = 2007| last1 = Hughes| first1 = E. R.| title = Investigation of an anisotropic tortuosity in a biot model of ultrasonic propagation in cancellous bone| journal = The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America| volume = 121| issue = 1| pages = 568\u201374| last2 = Leighton| first2 = T. G.| last3 = White| first3 = P. R.| last4 = Petley| first4 = G. W. | doi=10.1121/1.2387132| bibcode = 2007ASAJ..121..568H}}</ref><ref name=\"Lee_etal2007\">{{Cite journal| pmid = 17183128| year = 2007| last1 = Lee| first1 = K. I.| title = Empirical angle-dependent Biot and MBA models for acoustic anisotropy in cancellous bone| journal = Physics in Medicine and Biology| volume = 52| issue = 1| pages = 59\u201373| last2 = Hughes| first2 = E. R.| last3 = Humphrey| first3 = V. F.| last4 = Leighton| first4 = T. G.| last5 = Choi| first5 = M. J.| doi = 10.1088/0031-9155/52/1/005| bibcode = 2007PMB....52...59L}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid12788218|noedit\">{{Cite journal | pmid = 12788218| year = 2003| last1 = Hughes| first1 = E. R.| title = Estimation of critical and viscous frequencies for Biot theory in cancellous bone| journal = Ultrasonics| volume = 41| issue = 5| pages = 365\u20138| last2 = Leighton| first2 = T. G.| last3 = Petley| first3 = G. W.| last4 = White| first4 = P. R.| last5 = Chivers| first5 = R. C.| doi=10.1016/s0041-624x(03)00107-0| citeseerx = 10.1.1.621.4532}}</ref><ref name=\"Osteo_EPSRC\">{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G, Petley, G.W., White, P.R. and Hughes, E.R.|title=A sound diagnosis|journal=EPSRC Newsline|year=2002|volume=21|pages=18\u201319|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2896.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"Hughes_etalAcBull\">{{cite journal|last1=Hughes, E.R., Leighton, T.G., Petley, G.W. and White, P.R. |title=Ultrasonic assessment of bone health|journal=Acoustics Bulletin|year=2001|volume=26|issue=5|pages=17\u201323|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/FDAG/Cross-faculty%20UAUA%20centre/e-papers/Osteoporosis/Ultrasonic%20assessment%20of%20bone%20health.htm}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hughes, E.R., Leighton, T.G., Petley, G.W., White, P.R.|title=A review of scattering models for ultrasonic propagation in the trabecular bone|journal=ISVR Technical Report|year=2001|issue=293|url=http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/10223/1/Pub2580.pdf}}</ref> \n* monitoring the efficiency of kidney stone therapy (an invention that won the 2008 \u2018Medical & Healthcare\u2019 award from \u2018The Engineer\u2019<ref name=\"Litho_1\">{{cite web|title= The 'Medical & Healthcare' award by 'The Engineer'|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/FDAG/Cross-faculty%20UAUA%20centre/Media%202012/litho/2008%20The%20Engineer%20awards.pdf |accessdate=2016-09-04}}</ref> with key collaborator: [[Guy's and St Thomas' NHS Foundation Trust]]).<ref name=\"worldscientific.com\">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1142/S0218396X11004298| title = Innovation to Impact in a Time of Recession| journal = Journal of Computational Acoustics| volume = 19| pages = 1\u201325| year = 2011| last1 = Leighton | first1 = T. G. }}</ref><ref name=PRS2012_litho>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1098/rspa.2012.0538| title = Prediction of far-field acoustic emissions from cavitation clouds during shock wave lithotripsy for development of a clinical device| journal = Proceedings of the Royal Society A| volume = 469| issue = 2150| pages = 20120538| year = 2012| last1 = Leighton | first1 = T. G.| last2 = Turangan | first2 = C. K.| last3 = Jamaluddin | first3 = A. R.| last4 = Ball | first4 = G. J.| last5 = White | first5 = P. R.| bibcode = 2012RSPSA.46920538L| doi-access = free}}</ref><ref name=umb2008>{{Cite journal| pmid = 18562085| year = 2008| last1 = Leighton| first1 = T. G.| title = A passive acoustic device for real-time monitoring of the efficacy of shockwave lithotripsy treatment| journal = Ultrasound in Medicine & Biology| volume = 34| issue = 10| pages = 1651\u201365| last2 = Fedele| first2 = F| last3 = Coleman| first3 = A. J.| last4 = McCarthy| first4 = C| last5 = Ryves| first5 = S| last6 = Hurrell| first6 = A. M.| last7 = De Stefano| first7 = A| last8 = White| first8 = P. R.| doi = 10.1016/j.ultrasmedbio.2008.03.011}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Jamaluddin, A.R., Ball, G.J., Turangan, C.K. and Leighton, T.G. (|title=The collapse of single bubbles and calculations of the far-field acoustic emissions for cavitation induced by shock wave lithotripsy|journal=Journal of Fluid Mechanics|year=2011|volume=677|pages=305\u2013341|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub12506.pdf|doi=10.1017/jfm.2011.85}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Turangan, C.K., Jamaluddin, A.R., Ball, G.J. and Leighton, T.G.|title=Free-Lagrange simulations of the expansion and jetting collapse of air bubbles in water|journal=Journal of Fluid Mechanics|year=2008|volume=598|pages=1\u201325|doi=10.1017/s0022112007009317|bibcode=2008JFM...598....1T|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/c09292572d99b614b980dc9e2624c76be7da2de2}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G., Fedele, F., Coleman, A., McCarthy, C., Jamaluddin, A.R., Turangan, C.K., Ball, G., Ryves, S., Hurrell, A., De Stefano, A. and White, P.R.|title=The development of a passive acoustic device for monitoring the effectiveness of shockwave lithotripsy in real time|journal=Hydroacoustics|year=2008|volume=11|pages=159\u2013180|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub10428.pdf}}</ref> \n* solutions for needle-free injectors for migraine sufferers (over 1 million sold).<ref name=\"worldscientific.com\"/><ref>{{Cite journal| pmid = 10641626| year = 2000| last1 = Leighton| first1 = T. G.| title = The Rayleigh-like collapse of a conical bubble| journal = The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America| volume = 107| issue = 1| pages = 130\u201342| last2 = Cox| first2 = B. T.| last3 = Phelps| first3 = A. D.| doi=10.1121/1.428296| bibcode = 2000ASAJ..107..130L}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G., Phelps, A.D., Cox, B.T. and Ho, W.L.|title=Theory and preliminary measurements of the Rayleigh-like collapse of a conical bubble|journal=Acustica with ActaAcustica|year=1998|volume=84|issue=6|pages=1014\u20131024}}</ref><ref name=unstablecollapse>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0041-624X(97)00014-0| title = Sonoluminescence from the unstable collapse of a conical bubble| journal = Ultrasonics| volume = 35| issue = 5| pages = 399\u2013405| year = 1997| last1 = Leighton | first1 = T. G. | last2 = Ho | first2 = W. L. | last3 = Flaxman | first3 = R.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Leighton, T.G., Cox, B.T., Birkin, P.R. and Bayliss, T. |title=The Rayleigh-like collapse of a conical bubble: Measurements of meniscus, liquid pressure, and electrochemistry |journal=Proceedings of the 137th Meeting of the Acoustical Society of America and the 2nd Convention of the European Acoustics Association |origyear=Forum Acusticum 99, integrating the 25th German Acoustics DAGA Conference |volume=Berlin, Paper 3APAB_1, 4pp |year=1999}}</ref>\n\nand assisted the Institute of Cancer Research with technology for tumour therapy monitoring (2010).<ref>{{cite journal |last1= McLaughlan, J., Rivens, I., Leighton, T.G. and terHaar, G. |title=A study of bubble activity generated in ex-vivo tissue by high intensity focused ultrasound (HIFU) |journal= Ultrasound in Medicine and Biology |year=2010 |volume=36 |issue=8 |pages=1327\u20131344 |doi= 10.1016/j.ultrasmedbio.2010.05.011 |pmid=20691922 |url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub11965.pdf}}</ref>\n\nTwo billion people have been scanned in the womb under the guidelines he helped co-author for the World Federation for Ultrasound in Medicine and Biology guidelines for foetal ultrasonic scanning.<ref name=WFUMB1998>{{cite journal |last1= Barnett, S., Ziskin, M., Maeda, K., Nyborg, W., ter Harr, G., Rott, H-D., Bang, J., Carstensen, E., Delius, M., Duck, F., Edmonds, P., Frizzell, F., Hogaki, M., Ide, M., Leighton, T., Mille, D., Preston, R., Stratmeyer, M., Takeuchi, H., Takeuchi, Y., Williams, R. |title=World Federation for Ultrasound in Medicine and Biology, Task Group Report for Safety Committee of the WFUMB: Conclusions and recommendations on thermal and non-thermal mechanisms for biological effects of ultrasound |journal= Ultrasound in Medicine and Biology|year=1998|volume=24 Supplement 1|pages=1\u201359|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub12719.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"The extraordinary potential of bubble acoustics\">{{cite web|title=University of Southampton The extraordinary potential of bubble acoustics|url= https://www.southampton.ac.uk/news/2016/09/bubble-acoustics.page |accessdate=2017-11-25}}</ref>\n\nHe served on the [[Government of the United Kingdom]]'s Working Group of the Advisory Committee on Dangerous Pathogens [[Transmissible spongiform encephalopathy|Transmissible Spongiform Encephalopathies]] Sub Group<ref name=CJD2015>{{cite journal|last1= Bryant, G., Hewitt, P., Hope, J., Howard, C., Ironside, J., Knight, R., Manson, J., Mead, S., Medley, G., Minor, P., Ridgway, G., Salmon, R., Ashcroft, P., Bennett, P., Bent, A., Burke, P., Cardigan, R., Connor, N., Riley, A., Cutts, D., Gadd, E., Gauci, E., Gauci, T., Grimley, P., Hidderley, A., Hill, I., Kirby, C., Mitchell, L., Noterman, M., Pride, J., Pryer, D., Singh, J., Stanton, G., Tomlinson, N., Wight, A., Bradley, R., Griffin, G., Jones, P., Jeffries, D., Matthews, D., May, D., McConnell, I., Painter, M., Smith, P., Spellman, R., Taylor, D., Wyatt., T., Adams, R., Allison, M., Archyangelio, A., Barker, J., Barlow, T., Barnass, S., Bedi, R., Bethel, N. Bountiff, L., Bradley, C., Bramble, M., Bruce, M., Caterall, J., Chow, Y., Christie, P., Cobbold, A., Conroy, A., Craig, G., Crawford, P., Crook, P., Cumming, R., Elliot, D., Fraise, A., Gray, R., Griffiths, H., Herve, R., Holmes, S., Holton, J., Langdon, J., Leighton, T., Jones, A., Keevil, W., Latham, B., Lucas, S., Lumley, J., McCardle, L., Marsh, H., Martin, M., Murphy, J., Perrett, D., Richards, K., Reader, N., Revesz, T., Sjogren, G., Smith, A., Smith, G., Stephenson, J., Sutton, M., Treasure, E., Walker, J., Watkins, G., Will, R., Woodhead, K.|title= Minimise transmission risk of CJD and vCJD in healthcare settings. Report on the Prevention of CJD and vCJD by Advisory Committee on Dangerous Pathogens' Transmission Spongiform Encephalopathy (ACDP TSE) Subgroup|journal=Published as Part of the Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (CJD): Guidance, Data and Analysis Reports by the UK Government Department of Health (22 October2015). Crown Copyright 2015.|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub12720.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"Ended\"/> and advised the [[Health Protection Agency]] and the International Commission on Non-Ionizing Radiation Protection <ref name=\"ICNIRP ROME\">{{cite web|title= ICNIRP ROME|url= https://sites.google.com/site/hefua2/home/rome-meeting-of-international-commission-on-non-ionizing-radiation-protection-discusses-hefua-s-work-23-march-2016|accessdate=2017-11-25}}</ref><ref name=\"Ended\">Term over service completed</ref> on the safety of ultrasound.\n\nOther medical and healthcare inventions and breakthroughs are listed below under [[#Sloan Water Technology Ltd.|Sloan Water Technology Ltd.]],<ref name=\"Sloan Water Technology Ltd. homepage\">{{cite web|title=Sloan Water Technology Ltd. homepage|url= https://sites.google.com/view/sloan-wt-landing |accessdate=2019-02-06}}</ref> [[#NAMRIP and Global-NAMRIP|Global-NAMRIP]] and [[#Health Effects of Ultrasound in Air|HEFUA]].\n\n[[File:TWIPS picture 2.png|thumb|Comparison of standard sonar and TWIPS in finding a target in bubbly water. Adapted from <ref name=TWIPS_2010/>]]\n\n===Humanitarian===\n\nLeighton invented:\n* radar for the detection of buried explosives, hidden bugging devices, and for the location of buried catastrophe victims (in avalanches, mudslides, collapsed buildings etc.)<ref name=radarclutter>{{Cite journal|last=Leighton |first=Timothy | authorlink1 = Timothy Leighton|year=2013 |title=Radar clutter suppression and target discrimination using twin inverted pulses |journal= Proceedings of the Royal Society A |volume=469 |issue=2160 |pages= 20130512|doi= 10.1098/rspa.2013.0512| url = http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/359121/|bibcode = 2013RSPSA.46930512L |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n* the world's only sonar system capable of detecting objects in bubbly water (key, for example, to protecting services, cargo and aid shipping in conflict zones).<ref name=dolphins>{{Cite journal | doi= 10.1098/rspa.2012.0247| title = Do dolphins benefit from nonlinear mathematics when processing their sonar returns?| journal = Proceedings of the Royal Society A| volume = 468| issue = 2147| pages = 3517\u20133532| year = 2012| last1 = Leighton | first1 = T. G.| last2 = Chua | first2 = G. H.| last3 = White | first3 = P. R.|bibcode = 2012RSPSA.468.3517L | doi-access = free}}</ref><ref name=\"ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\">{{Cite journal| pmid = 22088017| year = 2011| last1 = Leighton| first1 = T. G.| title = Clutter suppression and classification using twin inverted pulse sonar in ship wakes| journal = The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America| volume = 130| issue = 5| pages = 3431\u20137| last2 = Finfer| first2 = D. C.| last3 = Chua| first3 = G. H.| last4 = White| first4 = P. R.| last5 = Dix| first5 = J. K.| doi = 10.1121/1.3626131| bibcode = 2011ASAJ..130.3431L}}</ref><ref name=TWIPS_2010>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1098/rspa.2010.0154| title = Clutter suppression and classification using twin inverted pulse sonar (TWIPS)| journal = Proceedings of the Royal Society A| volume = 466| issue = 2124| pages = 3453\u20133478| year = 2010| last1 = Leighton | first1 = T. G.| last2 = Finfer | first2 = D. C.| last3 = White | first3 = P. R.| last4 = Chua | first4 = G. \u2013 H. | last5 = Dix | first5 = J. K.|bibcode = 2010RSPSA.466.3453L | doi-access = free}}</ref> - mine detection is often an ongoing problem long after conflict has reduced and civilians return to former conflict zones (key collaborator: Paul White<ref name=\"southampton.ac.uk\">{{cite web |last1=Paul |first1=White |title=University of Southampton \u2013 webpage |url= http://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/about/staff/prw.page |website=southampton.ac.uk/engineerin |accessdate=2014-09-26}}</ref>) \n* a number of systems for detecting objects buried in the seabed<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Leighton|first=T. G.|last2=Evans|first2=R. C. P.|date=1 May 2008|title=The detection by sonar of difficult targets (including centimetre-scale plastic objects and optical fibres) buried in saturated sediment|url= |journal=Applied Acoustics|series=The detection of buried marine targets|volume=69|issue=5|pages=438\u2013463|doi=10.1016/j.apacoust.2007.05.002}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub9296.pdf|title=Studies into the detection of buried objects (particularly optical fibres) in saturated sediment. Part 1: Background|last=Leighton|first=Timothy|last2=Evans|first2=Ruthven|publisher=University of Southampton|year=2007|isbn=|location=|pages=1\u201340}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub9297.pdf|title=Studies into the detection of buried objects (particularly optical fibres) in saturated sediment. Part 2: Design and commissioning of test tank|last=Leighton|first=Timothy|last2=Evans|first2=Ruthven|publisher=University of Southampton|year=2007|isbn=|location=|pages=1\u201368}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub9298.pdf|title=Studies into the detection of buried objects (particularly optical fibres) in saturated sediment. Part 3: Experimental investigation of acoustic penetration of saturated sediment|last=Evans|first=Ruthven|last2=Leighton|first2=Timothy|publisher=University of Southampton|year=2007|isbn=|location=|pages=1\u201343}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub9299.pdf|title=Studies into the detection of buried objects (particularly optical fibres) in saturated sediment. Part 4: Experimental investigations into the acoustic detection of objects buried in saturated sediment|last=Evans|first=Ruthvan|last2=Leighton|first2=Timothy|publisher=University of Southampton|year=2007|isbn=|location=|pages=1\u201381}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub9300.pdf|title=Studies into the detection of buried objects (particularly optical fibres) in saturated sediment. Part 5: An acousto-optic detection system|last=Evans|first=Ruthven|last2=Leighton|first2=Timothy|publisher=University of Southampton|year=2007|isbn=|location=|pages=1\u201350}}</ref>\n\nand, in collaboration with the [[National Oceanography Centre]], one sold by Kongsberg<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.km.kongsberg.com/ks/web/nokbg0238.nsf/AllWeb/D4255184034A25A5C1257CCF0039A972?OpenDocument|title=Kongsberg GeoAcoustics GeoChirp 3D sub-bottom profiler delivered to China|last=Kongsberg|website=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gutowski|first=M|last2=Bull|first2=J|last3=Dix|first3=J|last4=Henstock|first4=T|last5=Hogarth|first5=P|last6=White|first6=P|last7=Leighton|first7=T|year=2005|title=Chirp sub-bottom profiler source signature design and field testing|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/257618978|journal=Marine Geophysical Researches|volume=26|issue=2\u20134|doi=10.1007/s11001-005-3715-8|pages=157\u2013169}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bull|first=Jonathan M.|last2=Gutowski|first2=Martin|last3=Dix|first3=Justin K.|last4=Henstock|first4=Timothy J.|last5=Hogarth|first5=Peter|last6=Leighton|first6=Timothy G.|last7=White|first7=Paul R.|date=1 June 2005|title=Design of a 3D Chirp Sub-bottom Imaging System|journal=Marine Geophysical Researches|language=en|volume=26|issue=2\u20134|pages=157\u2013169|doi=10.1007/s11001-005-3715-8|issn=0025-3235|url=https://eprints.soton.ac.uk/24147/1/__userfiles.soton.ac.uk_Users_nl2_mydesktop_Deposits_One%2520off_Bull_et_al_2005_Mar_Geophys_Res_Authorscopy.pdf|bibcode=2005MarGR..26..157B}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gutowski|first=Martin|last2=Bull|first2=Jonathan M.|last3=Dix|first3=Justin K.|last4=Henstock|first4=Timothy J.|last5=Hogarth|first5=Peter|last6=Hiller|first6=Tom|last7=Leighton|first7=Timothy G.|last8=White|first8=Paul R.|date=1 March 2008|title=3D high-resolution acoustic imaging of the sub-seabed|url= |journal=Applied Acoustics|volume=69|issue=3|pages=262\u2013271|doi=10.1016/j.apacoust.2006.08.010}}</ref> for archaeological and civil engineering purposes. Various collaborations are looking at ways of providing clean water from waste in Low- and Middle-Income Countries,<ref name=\"water_from_waste_1\">{{cite web |title=Clean water from waste|url= http://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/research/clean-water-waste.page|accessdate=2016-08-30}}</ref> including mentorships of young entrepreneurs in Africa.<ref>{{cite web |title= Timothy Kayondo and team mentored by for Africa Prize|url= http://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/research/clean-water-waste.page|accessdate=2016-01-23}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Seeps.png|thumb|Methodology by which active (red) and passive (yellow) sonar can be used to detect and quantify leaks from natural seeps or Carbon Capture and Storage Facilities, taken from ref.<ref name=\":0\"/>]]\n\n===Environmental and Safety===\n\nLeighton: \n* devised and conducted the experiment that revealed that the amount of carbon dioxide dissolving into the oceans was much greater than the values previously used in predicting climate change and ocean acidification;<ref name= CO2_Nature_2018>{{cite journal|last1= Leighton, T.G., Coles, D.C.H., Srokosz, M., White, P.R. and Woolf, D.K. |title=Asymmetric transfer of CO2 across a broken sea surface|journal= Scientific Reports |year=2018 |volume=8 |issue=1|pages=8301|doi=10.1038/s41598-018-25818-6|pmid=29844316|pmc=5974314|bibcode=2018NatSR...8.8301L}}</ref> \n* invented technology used by environmental agencies and oil and gas companies to monitor for undersea gas leaks<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G. and White, P.R.|title=Quantification of undersea gas leaks from carbon capture and storage facilities, from pipelines and from methane seeps, by their acoustic emissions|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society A|year=2012|volume=468|issue=2138|pages=485\u2013510|doi=10.1098/rspa.2011.0221|bibcode=2012RSPSA.468..485L|doi-access=free}}</ref> from pipelines, and from methane seeps, by their acoustic emissions. \n* devised the theory and methodology<ref name=\":0\"/> by which sonar could be used to monitor and quantify gas leaks from carbon capture and storage facilities in the seabed. This was later included as part of large-scale multinational trials on the North Sea seabed and elsewhere to assess leakage<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal|last1=Blackford, J., Stahl, H., Bull, J., Berges, B., Cevatoglu, M., Lichtschlag, A., Connelly, D., James, R., Kita, J., Long, D., Naylor, M., Shitashima, K., Smith, D., Taylor, P., Wright, I., Akhurst, M., Chen, B., Gernon, T., Hauton, C., Hayashi, M., Kaieda, H., Leighton, T., Sato, T., Sayer, M., Suzumura, M., Tait, K., Vardy, M., White, P., and Widdicombe, S.|title=Detection and impacts of leakage from sub-seafloor deep geological carbon dioxide storage|journal=Nature Climate Change|date=28 September 2014|page=Published online|doi=10.1038/nclimate2381|volume=4|issue=11|url=https://eprints.soton.ac.uk/369551/1/Blackford%2520et%2520al%2520Nature%2520Climate%2520Change%2520QICS-postprint.pdf|bibcode=2014NatCC...4.1011B}}</ref><ref name=\"Berges1\">{{cite journal |last1=Berges, B. J. P, Leighton, T.G. and White, P.R. |title=Passive acoustic quantification of gas fluxes during controlled gas release experiments |journal=International Journal of Greenhouse Gas Control |year=2015 |volume=38  |pages=64\u201379 |doi=  10.1016/j.ijggc.2015.02.008|url=http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/375114}}</ref><ref name= Hannis_2015>{{cite journal|last1= Hannis, S., Chadwick, A., Pearce, J., Jones, D., White, J., Wright, I., Connelly, D., Widdicombe, S., Blackford, J., White, P., Leighton, T. |title=Review of Offshore Monitoring for CCS Projects |journal= IEAGHG Technical Report 2015-02 (July 2015)   |year=2015 | pages=Copyright 2016 IEAGHG |url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pubs12721.pdf}}</ref><ref name= Hannis_2017>{{cite journal|last1= Hannis, S., Chadwick, A., Connelly, D., Blackford, J., Leighton, T., Jones, D., White, J., White, P.R., Wright, I., Widdicombe, S., Craig, J. and Dixon, T. |title=Review of offshore CO2 storage monitoring: Operational and research experiences of meeting regulatory and technical requirements |journal= Energy Procedia   |year=2017 |volume=114 |pages=5967\u20135980 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/319195925|doi=10.1016/j.egypro.2017.03.1732 |doi-access=free }}</ref><ref name=\"Li_ Leighton_OcEng_2019\">{{cite journal|last1= Li, J., White, P.R., Bull, J. M. and Leighton, T. G. |title= A noise impact assessment model for passive acoustic measurements of seabed gas fluxes|journal= Ocean Engineering |year=2019 |volume=183  |pages= 294\u2013304 | doi=10.1016/j.oceaneng.2019.03.046|url=  http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2019_Li_White_Bull_Leighton_(A_noise_impact_assessment)_Ocean_Enginerering.pdf}}</ref><ref name= Li_OCEANS2019_tidal-cycles>{{cite journal|last1= Li, J., White, P.R., Roche, B., Bull, J. M., Davis, J. W., Leighton, T. G, Depont, M., Gordini, E. and Cotterle, D. |title= Natural seabed gas leakage -- variability imposed by tidal cycles | journal= Proceedings of MTS-IEEE Oceans 2019 (Seattle, October 27\u201331, 2019)|pages= 1\u20136 |year=2019 |doi= 10.23919/OCEANS40490.2019.8962746 |url= https://eprints.soton.ac.uk/432561/1/PID6132405.pdf |isbn= 978-0-578-57618-3 }}</ref><ref name= Li_OCEANS2019_sounds-speed>{{cite journal|last1= Li, J., White, P.R., Bull, J. M., Leighton, T. G. and Roche, B. |title= A model for variations of sound speed and attenuation from seabed gas emissions | journal= Proceedings of MTS-IEEE Oceans 2019 (Seattle, October 27\u201331, 2019)|pages= 1\u20139 |year=2019 |doi= 10.23919/OCEANS40490.2019.8962861 |url= https://eprints.soton.ac.uk/432562/1/PID6132409.pdf |isbn= 978-0-578-57618-3 }}</ref> \n* systems assess the amount of methane in the seabed.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Leighton|first=T. G.|date=1 September 2007|title=Theory for acoustic propagation in marine sediment containing gas bubbles which may pulsate in a non-stationary nonlinear manner|journal=Geophysical Research Letters|language=en|volume=34|issue=17|pages=L17607|doi=10.1029/2007GL030803|issn=1944-8007|bibcode=2007GeoRL..3417607L}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mantouka|first=A|last2=Dogan|first2=H|last3=White|first3=P|last4=Leighton|first4=T|date=1 July 2016|title=Modelling acoustic scattering, sound speed, and attenuation in gassy soft marine sediments|journal=The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America|volume=140|issue=1|pages=274\u2013282|doi=10.1121/1.4954753|pmid=27475152|issn=0001-4966|bibcode=2016ASAJ..140..274M|url=https://eprints.soton.ac.uk/396674/1/__soton.ac.uk_ude_PersonalFiles_Users_cc1n12_mydocuments_PROF%2520LEIGHTON_Article%2520pdfs_Mantouka%252C%2520Dogan%252C%2520White%2520and%2520Leighton%2520%25282016%2529.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dogan|first=H|last2=White|first2=P|last3=Leighton|first3=T|date=1 March 2017|title=Acoustic wave propagation in gassy porous marine sediments: The rheological and the elastic effects|journal=The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America|volume=141|issue=3|pages=2277\u20132288|doi=10.1121/1.4978926|pmid=28372087|issn=0001-4966|bibcode=2017ASAJ..141.2277D|url=https://eprints.soton.ac.uk/407429/1/JASA_00014_R2.pdf}}</ref> This is important to assess the potential for leaks from these reserves into the sea and (eventually) the atmosphere (in the seabed, there is probably more carbon trapped in methane than there is in all other forms of conventional fossil fuel, yet as a greenhouse gas methane is 20 times more potent per molecule than carbon dioxide, so assessing how much is in the seabed, and how much leaks into the atmosphere, is a key task).<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1121/1.2993744| pmid = 19045684| title = Preliminary mapping of void fractions and sound speeds in gassy marine sediments from subbottom profiles| journal = The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America| volume = 124| issue = 5| pages = EL313\u201320| year = 2008| last1 = Leighton | first1 = T. G.| last2 = Robb | first2 = G. B. N.| bibcode = 2008ASAJ..124L.313L}}</ref> \n* devised theory and methodology for measuring key parameters in the transfer of atmospheric gas between atmosphere and ocean, that was later included in large-scale multi-national trials<ref name=propagation>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1098/rspa.2004.1298| title = Propagation through nonlinear time-dependent bubble clouds and the estimation of bubble populations from measured acoustic characteristics| journal = Proceedings of the Royal Society A| volume = 460| issue = 2049| pages = 2521\u20132550| year = 2004| last1 = Leighton | first1 = T. G.| last2 = Meers | first2 = S. D.| last3 = White | first3 = P. R.|bibcode = 2004RSPSA.460.2521L }}</ref><ref name=\"eprints.soton.ac.uk\">{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G.|title=From seas to surgeries, from babbling brooks to baby scans: The acoustics of gas bubbles in liquids|journal=International Journal of Modern Physics|year=2004|volume=18|issue=25|pages=3267\u20133314|url=http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/27995/|doi=10.1142/s0217979204026494}}</ref><ref name=Brooks2009a>{{cite journal|last1=Brooks, I.M., Yelland, M.J., Upstill-Goddard, R.C., Nightingale, P.D., Archer, S., D'Asaro, E., Beale, R., Beatty, C., Blomquist, B., Bloom, A. A., Brooks, B. J., Cluderay, J., Coles, D., Dacey, J., DeGrandpre, M., Dixon, J., Drennan, W. M., Gabriele, J., Goldson, L., Hardman-Mountford, N., Hill, M. K., Horn, M., Hsueh, P.-C., Huebert, B., de Leeuwuw, G., Leighton, T. G., Liddicicoat, M., Lingard, J. J. N., McNeil, C., McQuaid, J. B., Moat, B. I., Moore, G., Neill, C., Norris, S. J., O-Doherty, S., Pascal, R. W., Prytherch, J., Rebozo, M., Sahlee, E., Salter, M., Schuster, U., Skjelvan, I., Slagter, H., Smith, M. H., Smith, P. D., Srokosz, M., Stephens, J. A., Taylor, P. K., Telszewski, M., Walsh, R., Ward, B., Woolf, D. K., Young, D. and Zemmmmelink, H.|title=Physical Exchanges at the Air-Sea Interface: UK-SOLAS Field Measurements|journal=Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society|year=