tonnes of atmospheric carbon transfers each year between atmosphere and ocean.\n* Inventions assist safety in the world's most powerful pulsed spallation neutron source ($1.3&nbsp;billion) at the [[Oak Ridge National Laboratory]] in the [[United States]].<ref name=\"Baik2014\">{{cite journal|last1= Baik, K., Leighton, T. G and Jiang, J.|title=Investigation of a method for real time quantification of gas bubbles in pipelines|journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America|year=2014|volume=136|issue=2|pages= 502\u2013513 |doi=10.1121/1.4881922|pmid=25096085 |url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Baik%20et%20al%20(JASA%202014)%20(Chi%20beam%20C+P).pdf|bibcode=2014ASAJ..136..502B}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1121/1.4773863| pmid = 23463995| title = Acoustic attenuation, phase and group velocities in liquid-filled pipes III: Nonaxisymmetric propagation and circumferential modes in lossless conditions| journal = The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America| volume = 133| issue = 3| pages = 1225\u201336| year = 2013| last1 = Baik | first1 = K. | last2 = Jiang | first2 = J. | last3 = Leighton | first3 = T. G. | bibcode = 2013ASAJ..133.1225B}}</ref><ref name=inversion>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1098/rspa.2012.0053| title = The use of acoustic inversion to estimate the bubble size distribution in pipelines| journal = Proceedings of the Royal Society A| volume = 468| issue = 2145| pages = 2461\u20132484| year = 2012| last1 = Leighton | first1 = T. G.| last2 = Baik | first2 = K.| last3 = Jiang | first3 = J.|bibcode = 2012RSPSA.468.2461L | doi-access = free}}</ref><ref name=fog>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1121/1.3676732| pmid = 22423788| title = Demonstration comparing sound wave attenuation inside pipes containing bubbly water and water droplet fog| journal = The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America| volume = 131| issue = 3| pages = 2413\u201321| year = 2012| last1 = Leighton | first1 = T. G. | last2 = Jiang | first2 = J. | last3 = Baik | first3 = K. | bibcode = 2012ASAJ..131.2413L| url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/8919db5f93dbda482d824db1c6f4ad7fc5a492bf}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G., Jiang, J. and Baik, K|title=A TV demonstration of sound absorption connecting the space shuttle to submarines |journal=Acoustics Bulletin|year=2011|volume=36|issue=4|pages=35\u201340}}</ref>\n\n===Sloan Water Technology Ltd.===\n\nIn the late 1980s, Leighton<ref name=\"Leighton+Lingard+et+al\">{{cite journal |last1=Leighton, T.G., Lingard, R.J., Walton, A.J. and Field, J.E.|title=Acoustic bubble sizing by the combination of subharmonic emissions with an imaging frequency|journal= Ultrasonics|year=1991|volume=29|issue=4|pages=319\u2013323| url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2516.pdf|doi=10.1016/0041-624X(91)90029-8}}</ref> discovered a new ultrasonic signal<ref name=\"Leighton+Lingard+et+al\"/><ref name=\"Environmental Engineering 1\">{{cite journal|last1=Leighton T.G. |title=Acoustic bubble detection. I. The detection of stable gas bodies|journal=Environmental Engineering|year=1994 |volume=7 |pages=9\u201316 |url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2519.pdf}}</ref><ref name=Ultrasonics_1996>{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G., Phelps, A.D., Ramble, D.G. and Sharpe, D.A.|title=Comparison of the abilities of eight acoustic techniques to detect and size a single bubble |journal=Ultrasonics |year=1996 |volume=34 |issue=6 |pages=661\u2013667 |doi= 10.1016/0041-624X(96)00053-4 |url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2525.pdf}}</ref><ref name=jasa1997>{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G., Ramble, D.G. and Phelps, A.D |title=The detection of tethered and rising bubbles using multiple acoustic techniques |journal=Journal of the Acoustical Society of America |year=1997 |volume=101|issue=5 |pages=2626\u20132635|doi= 10.1121/1.418503 |url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2530.pdf|bibcode=1997ASAJ..101.2626L }}</ref> that he identified as due to surface waves on the walls of gas bubbles in liquids.<ref name=jasa1996>{{cite journal|last1=Phelps, A.D. and Leighton, T.G.|title=High-resolution bubble sizing through detection of the subharmonic response with a two frequency excitation technique |journal=Journal of the Acoustical Society of America |year=1996 |volume=99 |issue=4 |pages=1985\u20131992 |url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2524.pdf|doi=10.1121/1.415385 |bibcode=1996ASAJ...99.1985P }}</ref><ref name= Acustica_1997>{{cite journal|last1= Phelps, A.D. and Leighton, T.G. |title=The subharmonic oscillations and combination-frequency emissions from a resonant bubble: their properties and generation mechanisms |journal= Acta Acustica |year=1997 |volume=83 |pages=59\u201366 |url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2526.pdf}}</ref><ref name= Acustica_1998>{{cite journal|last1= Ramble D.G., Phelps, A.D. and Leighton, T.G. |title=On the relation between surface waves on a bubble and the subharmonic combination-frequency emission|journal= Acustica with Acta Acustica |year=1998 |volume=84 |issue=5 |pages=986\u2013988|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub185.pdf \n}}</ref> Multidisciplinary research in the following ten parallel streams of work turned this discovery into Sloan Water Technology Ltd:\n# Theory of how to stimulate these surface waves;<ref name= Makasimov+Leighton_2001>{{cite journal|last1= Maksimov, A.O. and Leighton, T.G. |title=Transient processes near the threshold of acoustically driven bubble shape oscillations |journal= Acta Acustica |year=2001 |volume=87 |issue=3 |pages=322\u2013332 |url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub1295.pdf}}</ref><ref name= Makasimov+Leighton_2012>{{cite journal|last1= Maksimov, A.O. and Leighton, T.G. |title=Pattern formation on the surface of a bubble driven by an acoustic field |journal= Proceedings of the Royal Society A |year=2012 |volume=468 |issue=2137 | pages=57\u201375 |doi=10.1098/rspa.2011.0366|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2012%20Maksimov%20and%20Leighton%20(PRS)%20Pattern%20formation.pdf|bibcode=2012RSPSA.468...57M }}</ref>\n# measurement of the liquid convection and shear they generate;<ref name=\"eprints.soton.ac.uk\"/><ref name=abubble/><ref name=what_is_ultrasound/><ref name=POMA_2016/><ref name=IOP2017/> theory on how sound causes the bubbles to generate cracks;<ref name=abubble/><ref name=\"Primary_Bjerknes_1990\">{{cite journal|last1= Leighton, T.G., Walton, A.J. and Pickworth, M.J.W. |title=Primary Bjerknes forces|journal= European Journal of Physics |year=1990|volume=11|issue=1|pages=47\u201350|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2513.pdf |doi=10.1088/0143-0807/11/1/009|bibcode=1990EJPh...11...47L}}</ref><ref name=\"Makasimov+Leighton_2018\">{{cite journal|last1= Maksimov, A.O. and Leighton, T.G. |title= Acoustic radiation force on a parametrically distorted bubble |journal= J. Acoust. Soc. Am.|year=2018 |volume=143 |issue= 1 |pages=296\u2013305 |doi= 10.1121/1.5020786|pmid= 29390754 |bibcode= 2018ASAJ..143..296M |url= https://eprints.soton.ac.uk/416536/1/JASA_02137_R1_accepted_version_.pdf }}</ref> \n# theory for acoustics in porous materials (leading to the first theory to show why passing ultrasound through different directions in the human ankle could monitor osteoporosis);<ref name=\"Leighton_osteoporosis\"/><ref name=\"Osteo_EPSRC\"/><ref name=\"Hughes_etalAcBull\"/><ref name=\"pmid10414898|noedit\"/><ref name=\"pmid12788218|noedit\"/><ref name=\"Hughes_et_al_2017\"/><ref name=\"Lee_etal2007\"/> \n# the world's first measurements of the bubble size distribution for industry and in the ocean surf zone,<ref name=JASA_1997_surf>{{cite journal|last1= Phelps, A.D., Ramble, D.G. and Leighton, T.G.  |title=The use of a combination frequency technique to measure the surf zone bubble population|journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America  |year=1997 |volume=101 |issue=4 |pages=1981\u20131989 |doi= 10.1121/1.418199 |url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2529.pdf|bibcode=1997ASAJ..101.1981P}}</ref><ref name= IEEE_1998>{{cite journal|last1= Phelps, A.D. and Leighton, T.G. |title=Oceanic bubble population measurements using a buoy-deployed combination frequency technique|journal= IEEE Journal of Oceanic Engineering |year=1998 |volume=23 |issue=4 |pages=400\u2013410|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub183.pdf|doi=10.1109/48.725234|bibcode=1998IJOE...23..400P}}</ref> leading to ocean measurements necessary to predict the climatological significance of the transfer of carbon dioxide between atmosphere and ocean.<ref name= CO2_Nature_2018/> It also provided techniques for measurement in industrial pipelines<ref name= Leighton_Pipe_1998>{{cite journal|last1= Leighton, T.G., Ramble, D.G., Phelps, A.D., Morfey, C.L. and Harris, P.P.|title=Acoustic detection of gas bubbles in a pipe|journal= Acustica with Acta Acustica |year=1998 |volume=84 |issue=5 |pages=801\u2013814|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub184.pdf}}</ref><ref name= JASA_2002_reverb>{{cite journal|last1= Leighton, T.G., White, P.R., Morfey, C.L., Clarke, J.W.L., Heald, G.J., Dumbrell, H.A. and Holland, K.R. |title=The effect of reverberation on the damping of bubbles |journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America  |year=2002 |volume=112 |issue=4 |pages=1366\u20131376 |url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub1612.pdf|doi=10.1121/1.1501895 |pmid=12398444 |bibcode=2002ASAJ..112.1366L }}</ref> which led to sensors for the oil and gas,<ref name=\":0\"/> carbon capture and storage,<ref name=\":0\"/><ref name=\":1\"/><ref name=\"Berges1\"/> ceramics<ref name=\"Yim+Leighton\">{{cite journal|last1= Yim, G.-T. and Leighton, T.G. |title= Real-time on-line monitoring of ceramic \"slip\" in pottery pipe-lines using ultrasound |journal= Ultrasonics |year=2010 |volume=50 |issue=1 |pages=60\u201367|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub11434.pdf|doi= 10.1016/j.ultras.2009.07.008 |pmid= 19709710 }}</ref> and nuclear<ref name=\"inversion\"/><ref name=\"Baik2014\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> industries.\n# measurement of the liquid convection and shear from these surface waves;<ref name=\"eprints.soton.ac.uk\"/><ref name=abubble/><ref name=what_is_ultrasound/><ref name=POMA_2016/><ref name=IOP2017/> theory on how sound causes the bubbles to generate cracks;<ref name=abubble/><ref name=\"Primary_Bjerknes_1990\"/><ref name=\"Makasimov+Leighton_2018\"/>\n# acoustic losses in water surrounded on all sides by air and containing microscopic natural particles;<ref name=\"Richards+Leighton_PRS2003\">{{cite journal|last1=   Richards, S.D., Leighton, T.G. and Brown, N.R. |title= Visco-inertial absorption in dilute suspensions of irregular particles|journal= Proceedings of the Royal Society A|year=2003 |volume=459  |issue= 2038|pages= 2153\u20132167|url=  http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2003%20Richards%20Leighton%20Brown%20(PRS)%20Visco-inertial%20absorption.pdf|doi= 10.1098/rspa.2003.1126|bibcode= 2003RSPSA.459.2153R}}</ref><ref name=\"Richards+Leighton_JASA2003\">{{cite journal|last1=   Richards, S.D., Leighton, T.G. and Brown, N.R. |title=  Sound absorption by suspensions of nonspherical particles: Measurements compared with predictions using various particle sizing techniques|journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America|year=2003 |volume=114  |issue= 4|pages= 1841\u20131850|url=  http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2538.pdf|doi= 10.1121/1.1610449|pmid= 14587585|bibcode= 2003ASAJ..114.1841R}}</ref><ref name=\"Brown+Leighton_JASA1998\">{{cite journal|last1=   Brown, N.R., Leighton, T.G., Richards, S.D. and Heathershaw, A.D.|title= Measurement of viscous sound absorption at 50-150 kHz in a model turbid environment|journal= Journal of the Acoustical Society of America |year=1998 |volume=104  |issue= 4|pages= 2114\u20132120 |url=  http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub182.pdf|doi= 10.1121/1.423725|bibcode= 1998ASAJ..104.2114B}}</ref> \n# acoustic propagation down curved columns of fluid, and how horns could facilitate this;<ref name=\"Music in Space\"/><ref name=\":2\"/><ref name=planetaria/><ref name=\"Fluid_loading\"/><ref name=\"multidisciplinary_lecture_2\">{{cite web|title=T.G. Leighton, lecture, University of Southampton Multidisciplinary Research Week 2013|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5H4toaWU_IY&t=2791s |accessdate=2018-10-01}}</ref>\n# use of acoustic pulses to enhance bubble activity;<ref name=abubble/><ref name=\"Leighton+Pickworth1\">{{cite journal|last1= Leighton, T.G., Pickworth, M.J.W., Walton, A.J. and Dendy, P.P.|title=  Studies of the cavitational effects of clinical ultrasound by sonoluminescence: 1 correlation of sonoluminescence with the standing-wave pattern in an acoustic field produced by a therapeutic unit|journal= Physics in Medicine and Biology|year=1988 |volume=33 |issue=11 |pages=1239\u20131248|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2492.pdf|doi= 10.1088/0031-9155/33/11/002|bibcode= 1988PMB....33.1239L}}</ref><ref name=\"Leighton+Pickworth2\">{{cite journal|last1=  Pickworth, M.J.W., Dendy, P.P., Leighton, T.G. and Walton, A.J. |title=   Studies of the cavitational effects of clinical ultrasound by sonoluminescence: 2 Thresholds for sonoluminescence from a therapeutic ultrasound beam and the effect of temperature and duty cycle|journal= Physics in Medicine and Biology|year=1988 |volume=33 |issue=11 |pages=1249\u20131260|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2493.pdf|doi= 10.1088/0031-9155/33/11/003|bibcode= 1988PMB....33.1249P}}</ref><ref name=\"Leighton_Transient_Excitation1\">{{cite journal|last1=   Leighton, T.G. |title=  Transient excitation of insonated bubbles|journal= Ultrasonics|year=1989 |volume=27 |issue=1 |pages=50\u201353|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2511.pdf|doi= 10.1016/0041-624X(89)90009-7}}</ref><ref name=\"Leighton_Transient_Excitation2\">{{cite journal|last1=   Leighton, T.G., Walton, A.J. and Field, J.E. |title=   High-speed photography of transient excitation|journal= Ultrasonics|year=1989 |volume=27  |issue= 6|pages=370\u2013373|url=  http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2512.pdf|doi= 10.1016/0041-624X(89)90036-X}}</ref><ref name=\"Leighton+Pickworth3\">{{cite journal|last1= Pickworth, M.J.W., Dendy, P.P., Leighton, T.G., Worpe, E. and Chivers, R.C. |title=  Studies of the cavitational effects of clinical ultrasound by sonoluminescence: 3 Cavitation from pulses a few microseconds in length |journal= Physics in Medicine and Biology|year=1989 |volume=34 |issue=9 |pages=1139\u20131151|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2507.pdf|doi= 10.1088/0031-9155/34/9/001 |bibcode= 1989PMB....34.1139P }}</ref>\n# controlled bubble generation;<ref name=\"swarm\"/>\n# how these bubbles affect living cells<ref name=abubble/><ref name=\"Leighton_cheek\">{{cite journal|last1= Leighton, T.G., Pickworth M.J.W., Tudor, J. and Dendy, P.P.|title=   Search for sonoluminescence in vivo in the human cheek|journal= Ultrasonics|year=1990 |volume=28 |issue= 3|pages=181\u2013184|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Pub2510.pdf|doi= 10.1016/0041-624X(90)90083-Z|pmid= 2339477}}</ref> and surfaces.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Howlin R.P., Fabbri S., Offin D.G., Symonds N., Kiang K.S., Knee R.J., Yoganantham D.C., Webb J.S., Birkin P.R., Leighton T.G., Stoodley P. |title=Removal of dental biofilms with a novel ultrasonically-activated water stream |journal=Journal of Dental Research |year=2015 |volume=94|issue=9 |pages=1303\u20131309 |url=http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/377560/ |postscript= (electronic supplement at url: http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/377535/). |doi=10.1177/0022034515589284|pmid=26056055 }}</ref><ref name=SS2015a>{{cite journal|last1=Birkin P.R., Offin D.G., Vian C.J.B., Howlin R.P., Dawson J.I., Secker T.J., Herve R.C., Stoodley P., Oreffo R.O.C., Keevil C.W. and Leighton T.G. |title=Cold water cleaning of brain proteins, biofilm and bone \u2013 harnessing an ultrasonically activated stream |journal=Physical Chemistry Chemical Physics |year=2015 |volume=17 |issue=32 |pages=20574\u201320579 |doi= 10.1039/C5CP02406D |pmid=26200694 |url=http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/378564/|bibcode=2015PCCP...1720574B }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Birkin, P.R., Offin, D.G., and Leighton, T.G. |title=An activated fluid stream - new techniques for cold water cleaning |journal=UltrasonicsSonochemistry |year=2016 |volume=29 |pages=612\u2013618 |doi= 10.1016/j.ultsonch.2015.10.001 |pmid=26522990 |url=http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/382666/}}</ref><ref name=\"swarm\">{{cite journal |last1=Birkin, P.R., Offin, D.G., Vian, C.J.B. and Leighton, T.G. |title=Electrochemical 'bubble swarm' enhancement of ultrasonic surface cleaning |journal= Physical Chemistry Chemical Physics |year=2015 |volume=17 |issue=33 |pages=21709\u201321715 |doi= 10.1039/c5cp02933c | pmid=26234563 |url= http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/381291/|bibcode=2015PCCP...1721709B }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Salta|first=M|last2=Goodes|first2=L R|last3=Maas|first3=B J|last4=Dennington|first4=S P|last5=Secker|first5=T J|last6=Leighton|first6=T G|title=Bubbles versus biofilms: a novel method for the removal of marine biofilms attached on antifouling coatings using an ultrasonically activated water stream|journal=Surface Topography: Metrology and Properties|volume=4|issue=3|doi=10.1088/2051-672x/4/3/034009|year=2016|page=034009|bibcode=2016SuTMP...4c4009S|url=https://eprints.soton.ac.uk/399242/1/Manuscript_GT_Salta_2ndResubmission_v5.docx}}</ref><ref name=\"Goodes_2016\">{{cite journal |last1=Goodes, L., Harvey, T., Symonds, N. and Leighton, T.G. |title=A comparison of ultrasonically activated stream and ultrasonic bath immersion cleaning of railhead leaf-film contaminant|journal= Surface Topography: Metrology and Properties|year=2016 |volume=4 |issue=3 |pages=034003|doi= 10.1088/2051-672X/4/3/034003| url= http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/394497/}}</ref> \nThese 10 streams of fundamental research represented the knowledge on which Sloan Water Technology Ltd. was founded.<ref name=\"Sloan Water Technology Ltd. homepage\"/> It is currently producing technology for cleaning and changing surfaces using only cold water, air bubbles and sound (without chemicals or drugs).<ref name=Rayleigh_Medal_paper>{{Cite journal|last=Leighton |first=Timothy | authorlink1 = Timothy Leighton|year=2014 |title=Bubble Acoustics: From whales to other worlds |journal= Proceedings of the Institute of Acoustics |volume=36|issue=3 |pages= 58\u201386|doi=}}</ref><ref name=\"Baking_Europe_2018\">{{Cite journal|last=Leighton |first=Timothy | authorlink1 = Timothy Leighton|year=2018 |title= Cold water cleaning in the preparation of food and beverages: The power of shimmering bubbles|journal= Baking Europe |volume=Summer 2018|issue= |pages= 8\u201312|url= http://www.bakingeurope.eu/previews/2018/BakingEurope-Summer-2018.pdf|accessdate=2018-08-18}}</ref><ref name=IOP2017>{{Cite journal|last=Leighton|first=T. G.|date=1 January 2017|title=The acoustic bubble: Ocean, cetacean and extraterrestrial acoustics, and cold water cleaning|journal=Journal of Physics: Conference Series|language=en|volume=797|issue=1|pages=012001|doi=10.1088/1742-6596/797/1/012001|issn=1742-6596|bibcode=2017JPhCS.797a2001L|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\"POMA_2016\">{{cite journal|last1=Leighton, T.G.|title=The acoustic bubble: Oceanic bubble acoustics and ultrasonic cleaning|journal= Proceedings of Meetings on Acoustics|year=2016|volume=24|pages=070006|doi=10.1121/2.0000121|doi-access=free}}</ref> This reduces the use of water and electricity,<ref name=ICSV17>{{Cite journal|last=Leighton |first=Timothy | authorlink1 = Timothy Leighton|year=2017 |title= Climate change, dolphins, spaceships and anti-microbial resistance - The impact of bubble acoustics |journal= Proceedings of the International Congress on Sound and Vibration |volume=24|issue= |pages= 1\u201316|doi=}}</ref> reduces pollution and has run-off that is easier to convert back to drinking water, and reduces the threat of \u2018superbugs\u2019.<ref name=\"NewScientistNAMRIP\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg22930662-500-resistance-fighter-takes-the-battle-to-microbes/ |title=Resistance fighter takes the battle to the microbes|publisher=Author: J. Webb, New Scientist (26 March 2016, pp. 32\u201333) published online entitled \"I\u2019m finding new ways to beat antibiotic resistance\"|accessdate=2016-08-29}}</ref><ref name=POST_Journal2018/>\n\n==Awards and honours==\nLeighton has been awarded the following medals and distinctions:\n\n===Medals===\n{{div col|colwidth=35em}}\n* the 2017 [[Clifford Paterson Lecture]] and Medal of the Royal Society<ref name=\"RS_Paterson\">{{cite web|title=Engineering professor honoured with Royal Society award|url=https://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/news/2017/07/19-scientist-honoured-with-award.page|accessdate=2017-07-31}}</ref><ref name=\"RS_Paterson_storify\">{{cite web |title=Royal Society medal awarded to T G Leighton (18 July 2017)|url= https://www.southampton.ac.uk/news/2017/07/leighton-royal-society-award.page|publisher=University of Southampton|accessdate=2017-07-31}}</ref> (video of Lecture here<ref name=\"RS_Paterson_Lecture_video\">{{cite web|title=Royal Society Paterson Medal Lecture (5 September 2018)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DhCRI_CsIP4|accessdate=2018-10-31}}</ref>)\n* the 2014 [[Rayleigh Medal]] of the [[Institute of Acoustics (United Kingdom)|Institute of Acoustics]]<ref name=\"UOS_IOA_Rayleigh\">{{cite web|title=Prestigious acoustics medal for Southampton Professor|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/mediacentre/features/timleighton_ioaaward.shtml|accessdate=2014-09-26}}</ref><ref name=\"IOA_Rayleigh_storify\">{{cite web |title=FRS award|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Acoustics_Bulletin_Jan-Feb_2015_0_page28.pdf|publisher=Institute of Acoustics|accessdate=2016-09-04}}</ref>\n* the 2013 Helmholtz-Rayleigh Interdisciplinary Silver Medal of the [[Acoustical Society of America]]<ref name=\"ASA_Citation_Rayleigh\">{{cite web|title=Citation for the Helmholtz-Rayleigh Interdisciplinary Silver Medal (Acoustical Society of America)|url= http://www.southampton.ac.uk/assets/sharepoint/groupsite/Administration/SitePublisher-document-store/Documents/passlvrhelm_ray.pdf |accessdate=2016-09-04}}</ref><ref name=\"ASA_Silver_Rayleigh\">{{cite web|title=The Helmholtz-Rayleigh Interdisciplinary Silver Medal (Acoustical Society of America)|url= http://www.southampton.ac.uk/sites/engineering/research/projects/media/rayleigh_medal/tim_leighton_awarded_the_helmholtz_rayleigh.page |accessdate=2016-09-04}}</ref>\n* the 2009 R W B Stephens Medal of the Institute of Acoustics<ref>{{cite web|title=The RWB Stephens Medal awarded to Professor T G Leighton|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/Stephens_Medal_Acoustics_Bulletin_Mar-Apr_2009.pdf|accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref>\n* the 2006 Paterson Medal of the Institute of Physics<ref name=Paterson_1/><ref>{{cite web|title=The Clifford Paterson Medal awarded to Professor T G Leighton|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/2006_v2.pdf|accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref>\n* the inaugural 2004 Early Career Medal and Award of the [[International Commission for Acoustics]]\n* the 2002 Tyndall Medal of the Institute of Acoustics\n* the 1994 A. B. Wood Medal of the Institute of Acoustics<ref>{{cite web|title=1994 A B Wood Medal|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/A_B_Wood.pdf|accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\nThe citation of the 2006 Paterson Medal of the [[Institute of Physics]] states that: {{centred pull quote|Timothy Leighton's contribution is outstanding in both breadth and depth. He is an acknowledged world leader in four fields... He has delivered over 70 pioneering advances, from devices now used in hospitals to the world's first count of bubbles in the surf zone (crucial to our understanding of atmosphere-ocean gas flux, coastal erosion and the optimisation of military [[sonar]]). Behind these advances lies rigorous physics.<ref name=\"Paterson_1\">{{cite web|title=The Paterson Medal awarded to Professor T G Leighton|url= http://www.southampton.ac.uk/news/2005/10/physics-prize-for-professor.page |accessdate=2016-09-04}}</ref>}}\n\n===Awards===\n{{div col|colwidth=35em}}\n* 2019 Doctor of Science, University of Cambridge<ref name=\"ScD_Eng_Jan2019\">{{cite web|title= Southampton professor Tim Leighton honoured as Doctor of Science |url= https://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/news/2019/01/tim-leighton-doctor-of-science.page |accessdate=2019-01-26}}</ref>\n* 2018 Royal Society's Lord Leonard and Lady Estelle Wolfson Foundation Translation Award for the StarHealer<ref name=\"Wolfson_StarHealer_2018\">{{cite web|title= Royal Society Award to NAMRIP team for StarHealer|url= https://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/news/2018/03/royal-society-prince-andrew-award.page |accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref>\n* the 2014 'Best new product of the year' award for StarStream<ref name=\"S-lab_storify\">{{cite web |title=Best New Product|url= https://www.labmate-online.com/news/news-and-views/5/university_of_southampton/product_of_the_year_award_for_cleaning_device/31844 |publisher=LabMate|accessdate=2016-09-04}}</ref><ref name=\"New_Product_1\">{{cite web|title=Southampton 'StarStream' cleaning technology wins prestigious award|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DTSgCvdnGfc|publisher=University of southampton, chemistry|accessdate=2014-09-26}}</ref><ref name=\"New_Product_2\">{{cite web|title=Ultrasonic device which enhances water's ability to clean wins 'Product of the Year'|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/mediacentre/news/2014/sep/14_162.shtml|accessdate=2014-09-26}}</ref><ref name=\"New_Product_ITV\">{{cite web|title= ITV News - University demonstrates pioneering device for cleaning medical instruments\n|url= https://www.itv.com/news/meridian/2015-09-17/university-demonstrates-pioneering-device-for-cleaning-medical-instruments/|accessdate=2016-09-26}}</ref>\n* the 2012 Institute of Chemical Engineering Award for Water Management and Supply<ref name=\"IChemE-Storify\">{{cite web|title= The 2012 Institute of Chemical Engineering Award for 'Water Management and Supply'  |url= http://www.discoversouthampton.co.uk/living/news/2015/09/16/using-ultrasound-to-clean-medical-instruments |accessdate=2016-09-04}}</ref>\n* the 2011 Royal Society [[Frank Brian Mercer|Brian Mercer Award]] for Innovation<ref name=\"RS_Mercer_video\">{{cite web|title= Royal Society Brian Mercer Award video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I__tsXsYbQA|accessdate=2016-09-04}}</ref><ref name=\"RS_Mercer_1\">{{cite web|title= Royal Society Brian Mercer Award clippings|url= http://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/research/projects/media/starstream_media_coverage/part_one_royal_society_premier_award.page |accessdate=2016-09-04}}</ref>\n* the 2008 'Medical & Healthcare' award from '[[The Engineer (UK magazine)|The Engineer]]'<ref name=Litho_1/><ref name=\"Litho_2\">{{cite web|title=The Engneer Magazine 2008 Technology and innovation awards 2008|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/litho_the_engineer_2008.pdf|accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref>\n* the inaugural 2001 International Medwin Prize for Acoustical Oceanography from the [[Acoustical Society of America]]<ref name=\"Medwin_1\">{{cite web|title=Inaugural Medwin Prize in Acoustical Oceanography awarded to Professor T G Leighton|url= http://www.southampton.ac.uk/assets/sharepoint/groupsite/Administration/SitePublisher-document-store/Documents/timothy_leighton_awarded_medwin_prize.pdf |accessdate=2016-09-04}}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Fellowships===\nLeighton is an Academician of three National Academies.<ref name=\"TripleCrown\"/> He was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society]] (FRS) in 2014.<ref name=\"FRS_WorldwideUniversitiesNetwork\">{{cite web|title= Worldwide Universities Network - Southampton professor receives prestigious Fellowship of the Royal Society|url= https://wun.ac.uk/article/southampton-professor-receives-prestigious-fellowship-royal-society |accessdate=2016-09-26}}</ref><ref name=frs/><ref name=\"FRS_AcousticsToday\">{{cite web|title= Acoustics Today - ASA fellow Timothy G. Leighton \u2013 Radar System TWIPR|url=https://acousticstoday.org/fellowship-royal-society/|accessdate=2016-09-26}}</ref> His nomination reads: {{centred pull quote|Timothy Leighton is distinguished for his research on the [[Acoustics|acoustical physics]] of bubbles, especially their [[Nonlinear system|nonlinear behaviour]]; for his inventions and discoveries including bubble measurements in the [[surf zone]], pipelines and [[Cold seep|methane seeps]]; for [[shock wave]] [[lithotripsy]] monitoring, disease detection in [[cancellous bone]] and needle free injection; for [[sonar]] systems that overcome bubble masking and numerous industrial applications. His seminal monograph The Acoustic Bubble has become the primary reference on bubble physical acoustics.<ref name=frs/>}}\n\nIn 2018 he was elected to Fellowship of the Academy of Medical Sciences, the citation reading for 'harnessing the physical sciences for the benefit of patients' as: {{centred pull quote|an outstanding academic inventor whose leadership in acoustical physics of bubbles has led to the development of new medical devices and procedures. His research has dominated the field of acoustic bubbles since the appearance of his monograph in 1994, \u2018The Acoustic Bubble\u2019, which was published at the age of 29. In this, he laid out the mathematical foundation upon which much of the recent cutting edge research on ultrasonic contrast agents, drug delivery, and focused ultrasound surgery has been based. He has exceptional ability to deliver engineering solutions to real world problems from conceptualisation to product development embracing an advanced practical knowledge of IP strategy.<ref name=\"TripleCrown\"/>}}\n\nLeighton was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering]] (FREng)<ref name=\"List of Fellows\"/> in 2012<ref name=\"whoswho\"/> for his services to Engineering and society.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Univ. of South Hampton |date=20 July 2012 |title=Major honor for Professor Leighton |url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/news/2012/07/19_major_honour.page}}</ref> He was elected a [[Fellow of the Institute of Physics]] (FInstP) in 2000,<ref name=\"FInstP2000\">{{cite web|title=Fellowship of the Institute of Physics|url= https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Category:Fellows_of_the_Institute_of_Physics|accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref>{{Circular reference|date=July 2019}} Fellowship of [[Institute of Acoustics (United Kingdom)|Institute of Acoustics]] in 1999,<ref name=\"ISVR50_interview\">{{cite web|title= ISVR50_interview |url= http://www.isvr50.soton.ac.uk/interviews/Tim-Leighton-interview.htm|accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref> Fellowship of the [[Acoustical Society of America]] in 1998,<ref name=\"FASA1998\">{{cite web|title=Fellowship of the Acoustical Society of America|url= http://acousticstoday.org/fellowship-royal-society/|accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref> and Fellowship of the Cambridge Philosophical Society in 1988.<ref name=\"cambridgephilosophicalsociety\">{{cite web|title=Cambridge Philosophical Society |url= http://www.cambridgephilosophicalsociety.org/history.shtml|accessdate=2018-06-29}}</ref> He is a Visiting Fellow of the Institute of Advanced Studies of Loughborough University.<ref name=\"IAS_Loughborough\">{{cite web|title=Fellowship of the Institute of Advanced Studies of Loughborough University|url= http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/PubPDFs/%20Institute%20of%20Advanced%20Studies%20Sound%20Theme%20Summit.pdf|accessdate=2019-11-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 the International Institute of Acoustics and Vibration (IIAV), of which he had not been a member, undertook a change to its Bylaws, and vote of all IIAV members, to create new rank of Distinguished Fellow. It is the highest rank for individual IIAV members of this international body, and Professor Leighton was the recipient in its inaugural year.<ref>{{cite web|title=IIAV Distinguished Fellow |url= https://www.southampton.ac.uk/namrip/news/2018/11/tim-leighton-honour.page?|accessdate=2018-11-10}}</ref>\n\n==Outreach, TV and radio work==\nLeighton has developed and conducted multiply-award-winning outreach activities to the public, and to encourage of young men and women to engage, and possibly follow careers in, science and engineering, with school visits, science fairs, exhibits, games, and appearances on TV and radio.<ref name=accoubub/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Leighton|first1=Timothy|title=Home Page soton uni|url=http://www.southampton.ac.uk/engineering/about/staff/tgl.page#tab1|accessdate=2014-08-25}}</ref><ref name=\"TV+radio\">{{cite web|title=Downloads of Video and audio appearances of Professor Leighton|url=http://resource.isvr.soton.ac.uk/staff/pubs/TV_and_radio_appearances_Leighton.htm|accessdate=2018-07-03}}</ref>\nHis public engagement work regarding his invention, \u201cThe most dangerous game in the world\u201d, which he designed to communicate with the public on the issue of superbugs and how they can protect themselves and society, was mentioned by Steve Brine MP, the Under-Secretary of State for Health on 16 November 2017.<ref name=\"Brine_Nov17\"/><ref name=\"Brine_TV_Nov17\"/> The IMDb and \"Who's Who\" have collated entries for Professor Leighton.<ref name=\"IMDB_Leighton\">{{Cite journal| last1= IMDb | title=  IMDb |series= IMDb database of movie and TV content |year=2011|volume=Record for T. G. Leighton|url= https://www.imdb.com/name/nm4575762/?ref_=ttfc_fc_cl_t62}}</ref><ref name=\"whoswho\"/> In his 2014 book 'Sonic Wonderland', the broadcaster Trevor Cox described Professor Leighton as 'a middle-aged Harry Potter'.<ref name=\"Cox1\">{{cite journal|last1=Cox, T.|title=Sonic Wonderland| publisher= Bodley Head |year=2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{CC-notice|cc=by4|url=https://royalsociety.org/people/timothy-leighton-11808/}}\n\n{{FRS 2014}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leighton, Timothy Grant}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Academy of Engineering]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Institute of Physics]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n", "name_user": "Dondervogel 2", "label": "safe", "comment": "caps", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timothy_Leighton"}
